WEBVTT

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:31.800
The time-traveler, for so it will be convenient to speak of him, was expounding a recondite matter

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:39.180
to us. His gray eyes shone and twinkled, and his usually pale face was flushed and animated.

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:46.080
The fire burned brightly, and the soft radiance of the incandescent lights in the lilies of silver

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:52.560
caught the bubbles that flashed and passed in our glasses. Our chairs, being his patents,

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:58.180
embraced and caressed us rather than submitted to be sat upon, and there is that luxurious

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:03.820
after-dinner atmosphere when thought roams gracefully free of the trammels of precision.

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:10.480
And he put it to us in this way, marking the points with a lean forefinger as we sat and

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:16.840
lazily admired his earnestness over this new paradox as we thought it and his fecundity.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:22.740
You must follow me carefully. I shall have to controvert one or two ideas that are almost

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:28.000
universally accepted. The geometry, for instance, they taught you at school is founded on a

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.860
misconception. It's not that rather a large thing to expect us to begin upon, said Philby,

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:40.840
an argumentative person with red hair. I do not mean to ask you to accept anything without

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:46.520
reasonable ground for it. You will soon admit as much as I need from you. You know, of course,

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:53.180
a mathematical line, a line of thickness, Nil, has no real existence. They taught you that.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:58.740
Neither has a mathematical plane. These things are mere abstractions.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:04.720
That is all right, said the psychologist. Nor having only length, breadth, and thickness

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:12.380
can a cube have a real existence. There I object, said Philby. Of course a solid body may exist.

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:19.140
All real things. So most people think, but wait a minute. Can an instantaneous cube exist?

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:26.400
Don't follow you, said Philby. Can a cube that does not last for any time at all have a real

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:34.020
existence? Philby became pensive. Clearly, the time traveler proceeded. Any real body must have

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:41.220
extension in four directions. It must have length, breadth, thickness, and duration.

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:47.000
But through a natural infirmity of the flesh, which I will explain to you in a moment,

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:53.660
we incline to overlook this fact. There are really four dimensions, three which we call the three

00:02:53.660 --> 00:03:01.660
planes of space, and a fourth, time. There is, however, a tendency to draw an unreal distinction

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:06.200
between the former three dimensions and the latter because it happens that our consciousness

00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:12.260
moves intermittently in one direction along the latter from the beginning to the end of our lives.

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:18.520
That, said a very young man making spasmodic efforts to relight his cigar over the lamp.

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:26.180
That, very clear indeed. Now it is very remarkable that this is so extensively overlooked,

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:30.280
continued the time traveler, with a slight accession of cheerfulness.

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:35.840
Really, this is what is meant by the fourth dimension, though some people who talk about

00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:41.500
the fourth dimension do not know they mean it. It is only another way of looking at time.

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:46.880
There is no difference between time and any of the three dimensions of space,

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:53.760
except that our consciousness moves along it. But some foolish people have got hold of the wrong

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:58.680
of that idea. You have all heard what they have to say about this fourth dimension?

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:07.060
I have not, said the provincial mayor. It is simply this, that space, as our mathematicians have it,

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:13.740
is spoken of as having three dimensions, which one may call length, breadth, and thickness,

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:19.400
and is always definable by reference to three planes, each at right angles to the others.

00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:24.580
But some philosophical people have been asking why three dimensions particularly,

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:28.380
why not another direction at right angles to the other three?

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.640
And have even tried to construct a fourth dimension, geometry.

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:41.240
Professor Simon Newcomb was expounding this to the New York Mathematical Society only a month or so

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:47.900
ago. You know how on a flat surface which has only two dimensions, we can represent a figure

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:53.560
of a three-dimensional solid, and similarly, they think that by models of three dimensions,

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:59.400
they could represent one of four if they could master the perspective of the thing. See?

00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:06.060
I think so, murmured the provincial mayor, and knitting his brows, he lapsed into an

00:05:06.060 --> 00:05:12.560
introspective state, his lips moving as one who repeats mystic words. Yes, I think I see it now,

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:16.360
he said after some time brightening in a quite transitory manner.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:21.580
Well, I do not mind telling you I have been at work upon this geometry of four dimensions for

00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:28.120
some time. Some of my results are curious. For instance, here is a portrait of a man at eight

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:34.040
years old, another at fifteen, another at seventeen, another at twenty-three, and so on.

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:40.240
All these are evidently sections, as it were, three-dimensional representations of this four

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:47.120
dimensioned being, which is a fixed and unaltered thing. Scientific people, preceded the time

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:53.840
traveler, after the pause required for the proper assimilation of this, know very well that time is

00:05:53.840 --> 00:06:01.280
only a kind of space. Here is a popular scientific diagram, a weather record. This line I trace with

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:09.220
my finger shows the movement of the barometer. Yesterday it was so high, yesterday night it fell,

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:15.640
then this morning it rose again, and so gently upward to here. Surely the Mercury did not trace

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:21.120
this line in any of the dimensions of space generally recognized? But certainly it traced

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:26.940
such a line, and that line, therefore, we must conclude, was along the time dimension.

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:35.460
But, said the medical man, staring hard at a coal in the fire, if time is really only a fourth

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:41.080
dimension of space, why is it, and why has it always been, regarded as something different?

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:46.280
And why cannot we move in time as we move about in the other dimensions of space?

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:53.460
The time traveler smiled. Are you sure we can move freely in space? Right and left we can go,

00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:58.820
backward and forward freely enough, and men always have done so, I admit, we move freely in two

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:05.440
dimensions, but how about up and down? Gravitation limits us there. Not exactly, said the medical

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:12.000
man, there are balloons. But before the balloons, save for spasmodic jumping and the inequalities

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.560
of the surface, man had no freedom of vertical movement. Still, they could move a little up and

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:24.340
down, said the medical man, easier, far easier down than up. And you cannot move at all in time,

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:29.360
you cannot get away from the present moment. My dear sir, that is just where you are wrong,

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:34.880
that is just where the whole world has gone wrong. We are always getting away from the present

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:41.280
moment. Our mental existences, which are immaterial and have no dimensions, are passing along the time

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:48.260
dimension with a uniform velocity from the cradle to the grave. Just as we should travel down if we

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:54.400
begin our existence 50 miles above the earth's surface. But the great difficulty is this,

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:59.700
interrupted the psychologist, you can move about in all directions of space, but you cannot move

00:07:59.700 --> 00:08:05.880
about in time. That is the germ of my great discovery, but you are wrong to say that we

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:12.500
cannot move about in time. For instance, if I am recalling an incident very vividly, I go back to

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:19.100
the instant of its occurrence, I become absent-minded as you say, I jump back for a moment. Of course,

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:25.080
we have no means of staying back for any length of time, any more than a savage or an animal has of

00:08:25.640 --> 00:08:32.580
above the ground. But a civilized man is better off than a savage in this respect. He can go up

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:38.540
against gravitation in a balloon. And why should he not hope that ultimately he may be able to stop

00:08:38.540 --> 00:08:44.680
or accelerate his drift along the time dimension, or even turn about and travel the other way?

00:08:45.620 --> 00:08:51.300
Oh, this, began Philby, is all. Why not, said the time traveler? It's against reason, said Philby.

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:56.540
What reason, said the time traveler? You can show black as white by argument, said Philby,

00:08:56.660 --> 00:09:02.660
but you will never convince me. Possibly not, said the time traveler, but now you begin to see the

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:09.320
object of my investigations into the geometry of four dimensions. Long ago I had a vague inkling

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:16.000
of a machine, to travel through time, exclaimed the very young man, that shall travel indifferently

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:22.640
in any direction of space and time as the driver determines. Philby contented himself with laughter.

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:29.220
But I have experimental verification, said the time traveler. It would be remarkably convenient

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:34.740
for the historian, the psychologist suggested, one might travel back and verify the accepted account

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:39.640
of the Battle of Hastings, for instance. Don't you think you would attract attention,

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:44.300
said the medical man? Our ancestors had no great tolerance for anachronisms.

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:50.160
One might get one's Greek from the very lips of Homer and Plato, the very young man thought,

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:54.840
in which case they would certainly plow you for the little go. The German scholars have

00:09:54.840 --> 00:10:00.360
improved Greek so much. Then there is the future, said the very young man. Just think,

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:05.440
one might invest all one's money, leave it to the accumulant at interest, and hurry on ahead.

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.620
To discover a society, said I, erected on a strictly communistic basis.

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:15.900
Of all the wild extravagant theories, began the psychologist.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:19.920
Yes, so it seems to me, and so I never talked of it until

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:24.440
experimental verification, cried I. You are going to verify that?

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:28.720
The experiment, cried Philby, who is getting brain weary.

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:34.320
Let's see your experiment anyhow, said the psychologist. Though it's all humbug, you know.

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:41.200
The time traveler smiled round at us, then, still smiling faintly, and with his hands,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:47.880
deep in his trouser pockets, he walked slowly out of the room and we heard his slippers shuffling

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:53.480
down the long passage to his laboratory. The psychologist looked at us. I wonder what he's

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:59.840
got. Some sleight of hand trick or other, said the medical man, and Philby tried to tell us about a

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:06.240
conjurer he had seen at Burslem, but before he had finished his preface, the time traveler came back

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:13.480
and Philby's antidote collapsed. The thing the time traveler held in his hand was a glittering

00:11:13.480 --> 00:11:20.700
metallic framework, scarcely larger than a small clock and very delicately made. There was ivory

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:27.720
in it and some transparent crystalline substance, and now I must be explicit, for this that follows,

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:33.440
unless his explanation is to be accepted, is an absolute unaccountable thing.

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:40.920
He took one of the small octagonal tables that were scattered about the room and set it in front

00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:49.860
of the fire with two legs on the hearth rug. On this table he placed the mechanism. Then he drew

00:11:49.860 --> 00:11:56.420
up a chair and sat down. The only other object on the table was a small shaded lamp, the bright light

00:11:56.420 --> 00:12:02.060
which fell upon the model. There were also perhaps a dozen candles about,

00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:08.880
two in brass candlesticks upon the mantle, and several in sconces so that the room was brilliantly

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:16.640
illuminated. I sat in a low armchair nearest the fire, and I drew this forward so as to be almost

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:22.380
between the time traveler and the fireplace. Philby sat behind him, looking over his shoulder.

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:27.120
The medical man and the provincial mayor watched him in profile from the right,

00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:32.840
the psychologist from the left. The very young man stood behind the psychologist.

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:39.960
We were all on the alert. It appears incredible to me that any kind of trick, however subtly

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:45.860
conceived and however adroitly done, could have been played upon us under these conditions.

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:49.760
The time traveler looked at us and then at the mechanism.

00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:56.940
Well, said the psychologist, this little affair, said the time traveler, resting his elbows upon

00:12:56.940 --> 00:13:03.840
the table and pressing his hands together above the apparatus is only a model. It is my plan for

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:15.840
a machine to travel through time. You will notice that it looks singularly askew and that there is

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:21.900
in some way unreal. He pointed to the part with his finger. Also, here is one little white lever

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:27.800
and here is another. The medical man got up out of his chair and peered into the thing.

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:33.860
It's beautifully made, he said. It took two years to make, retorted the time traveler. Then,

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:40.380
when we had all imitated the action of the medical man, he said, now I want you to clearly

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:46.240
understand that this lever being pressed over sends the machine gliding into the future

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:54.180
and this other reverses the motion. This saddle represents the seat of a time traveler. Presently,

00:13:54.240 --> 00:14:00.820
I am going to press the lever and off the machine will go. It will vanish, pass into future time,

00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:06.520
and disappear. Have a good look at the thing. Look at the table too and satisfy yourselves.

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:12.240
There is no trickery. I don't want to waste this model and then be told I'm a quack.

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:17.860
There was a minute's pause, perhaps. The psychologist seemed about to speak to me, but

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:23.300
changed his mind. Then the time traveler put forth his finger towards the lever.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:28.940
No, he said suddenly, lend me your hand. And turning to the psychologist, he took that

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:35.660
individual's hand in his own and told him to put out his forefinger so that it was the psychologist

00:14:35.660 --> 00:14:43.340
himself who sent forth the model time machine on its interminable voyage. We all saw the lever turn.

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:50.420
I am absolutely certain there was no trickery. There was a breath of wind and the lamp flame

00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:56.060
jumped. One of the candles on the mantle was blown out and the little machine suddenly swung

00:14:56.060 --> 00:15:03.540
round, became indistinct, was seen as a ghost for a second, perhaps, as in Eddie, a faintly glittering

00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:12.160
ivory, and it was gone. Vanished. Save for the lamp the table was bare. Everyone was silent for a

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:18.360
minute. Then Philby said he was damned. The psychologist recovered from his stupor and

00:15:18.360 --> 00:15:24.900
suddenly looked under the table. At that, the time traveler laughed cheerfully. Well, he said,

00:15:25.220 --> 00:15:33.520
with a reminiscence of the psychologist, then getting up, he went to the tobacco jar on the

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:39.860
pipe. We stared at each other. Look here, said the medical man. Are you in earnest about this?

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:45.780
Do you seriously believe that that machine has traveled into time? Certainly, said the

00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:50.400
time traveler, stooping to light a spill at the fire. Then he turned, lighting his pipe to look

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:56.140
at the psychologist's face. The psychologist, to show that he was not unhinged, helped himself

00:15:56.140 --> 00:16:03.200
to a cigar and tried to light it. Uncut. What is more, I have a big machine nearly finished in there.

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:08.260
He indicated the laboratory. And when that is put together, I mean to have a journey on my own

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:13.540
account. You mean to say that that machine has traveled into the future, said Philby?

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:19.140
Into the future or the past, I don't for certain know which. After an interval,

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:24.660
the psychologist had an inspiration. It must have gone into the past if it has gone anywhere, he

00:16:24.660 --> 00:16:30.200
said. Why, said the time traveler, because I presumed that it has not moved in space,

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:34.360
and if it traveled into the future, it would still be here all this time,

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:40.600
since it must have traveled through this time. But, I said, if it traveled into the past,

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:46.080
it would have been visible when we came first into this room, and last Thursday when we were here,

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:51.580
and the Thursday before that, and so forth. Serious objections, remarked the provincial

00:16:51.580 --> 00:16:55.540
mayor, with an air of impartiality, turning towards the time traveler.

00:16:56.420 --> 00:17:02.440
Not a bit, said the time traveler, and to the psychologist, you think. You can explain that.

00:17:02.740 --> 00:17:06.660
It's presentation below the threshold. You know, diluted presentation.

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:12.360
Of course, said the psychologist and reassured us, that's a simple point of psychology. I should

00:17:12.360 --> 00:17:17.580
have thought of it. It's plain enough and helps the paradox delightfully. We cannot see it, nor

00:17:17.580 --> 00:17:23.140
can we appreciate this machine any more than we can the spoke of a wheel spinning or a bullet

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:29.100
flying through the air. If it is traveling through time 50 times or 100 times faster than we are,

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:34.800
if it gets through a minute while we get through a second, the impression it creates will of course

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:41.000
be only one-fiftieth or one-hundredth of what it would make if it were not traveling in time.

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:45.280
That's plain enough. He passed his hand through the space in which the machine had been.

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:51.100
You see? He said, laughing. We sat and stared at the vacant table for a minute or so.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:54.900
Then the time traveler asked us what we thought of it all.

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:59.380
It sounds plausible enough tonight, said the medical man, but wait until tomorrow.

00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:04.620
Wait for the common sense of morning. Would you like to see the time machine itself?

00:18:05.120 --> 00:18:11.060
asked the time traveler, and therewith, taking the lamp in his hand, he led the way down the long

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:18.000
drafty corridor to his laboratory. I remember vividly the flickering light, his queer broad

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.440
head in silhouette, the dance of the shadows, how we all followed him, puzzled but incredulous,

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:28.840
and how there in the laboratory we beheld a large rendition of the little mechanism

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:35.880
which we had seen vanish from before our eyes. Parts were of nickel, parts of ivory,

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:42.840
parts had certainly been filed or sawn out of rock crystal. The thing was generally complete,

00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:49.420
but the twisted crystalline bars lay unfinished upon the bench beside some sheets of drawings,

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:54.060
and I took one up for a better look at it. Quartz, it seemed to be.

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:58.360
Look here, said the medical man. Are you perfectly serious, or is this a trick

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:04.220
like that ghost you showed us last Christmas? Upon that machine, said the time traveler,

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:11.720
holding the lamp aloft, I intend to explore time. Is that plain? I was never more serious in my life.

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:16.480
None of us quite knew how to take it. I caught Philby's eye

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:19.960
over the shoulder of the medical man, and he winked at me solemnly.

00:19:48.769 --> 00:19:54.049
That's L-I-B-R-I-V-O-X dot org.

00:19:55.249 --> 00:20:00.109
The Time Machine by H.G. Wells

00:20:00.109 --> 00:20:08.089
The Time Traveler, for so it will be convenient to speak of him, was exploiting a recounted matter to us.

00:20:08.409 --> 00:20:15.589
His grey eyes shone and twinkled, and his usually pale face was flourished and animated.

00:20:16.329 --> 00:20:29.549
The fire burned brightly, and the soft radiance of the incandescent light in the lilies of silver caught the bubbles that flashed and passed in our glasses.

00:20:29.549 --> 00:20:38.809
Our chairs, being his patience, embraced and caressed us rather than submitting to be sat upon.

00:20:39.309 --> 00:20:49.949
And there was that luxurious after-dinner atmosphere, when thought roams gracefully free of the trammels of precision.

00:20:49.949 --> 00:21:08.629
And he put it to us in this way, marking the points which a lean forefinger as we sat and lazily admired his earnestness over this new paradox, as we thought it, and his feudancy.

00:21:09.089 --> 00:21:16.189
You must follow me carefully. I shall have to controvert one or two ideas that are almost universally accepted.

00:21:16.189 --> 00:21:23.709
The geometry, for instance, they taught you at school is founded on a misconception.

00:21:24.989 --> 00:21:34.529
Is not that rather a large thing to expect us to begin upon? said Philby, an argumentative person with red hair.

00:21:35.229 --> 00:21:40.249
I do not mean to ask you to accept anything without reasonable ground for it.

00:21:40.249 --> 00:21:53.769
You will soon admit, as much as I need from you, you know, of course, that a mathematical line, a line of thickness, nil, has no real existence.

00:21:54.349 --> 00:22:01.909
They taught you that neither has a mathematical plane. These things are mere abstractions.

00:22:01.909 --> 00:22:11.229
That is all right, said the psychologist, nor having only length, breadth, and thickness, can a cube have a real existence.

00:22:12.389 --> 00:22:20.289
There I object, said Philby, of course a solid body may exist, all real things, so most people think.

00:22:20.749 --> 00:22:25.909
But wait a moment, can an instenuous cube exist?

00:22:25.909 --> 00:22:33.989
Don't follow you, said Philby. Can a cube that does not last for any time at all have a real existence?

00:22:34.349 --> 00:22:43.569
Philby became pensive. Clearly, the time traveler proceeded, any real body must have extension in four directions.

00:22:44.149 --> 00:22:49.029
It must have length, breadth, thickness, and duration.

00:22:49.029 --> 00:22:59.569
But through a natural infirmity of the flesh, which I will explain to you in a moment, we include to overlook this fact.

00:23:00.029 --> 00:23:08.289
There are really four dimensions, three which we call the three planes of space, and a fourth time.

00:23:09.029 --> 00:23:17.349
There is, however, a tendency to draw an unreal distinction between the former three dimensions and the latter,

00:23:17.349 --> 00:23:27.129
because it happens that our consciousness moves intermittently in one direction along the latter from the beginning to the end of our lives.

00:23:28.909 --> 00:23:37.589
That, said a very young man, making spamsemitic efforts to relight his cigar over the lamp.

00:23:37.589 --> 00:23:40.089
That, very clear indeed.

00:23:40.909 --> 00:23:52.649
Now, it is very remarkable that this is so extensively overlooked, continued the time traveler, with a slight accession of cheerfulness.

00:23:53.429 --> 00:24:02.969
Really, this is what is meant by the fourth dimension, though some people who talk about the fourth dimension do not know they mean it.

00:24:02.969 --> 00:24:06.789
It is only another way of looking at time.

00:24:07.529 --> 00:24:15.829
There is no difference between time and any of the three dimensions of space, except that our consciousness moves along it.

00:24:16.129 --> 00:24:21.429
But some foolish people have got hold of the wrong side of that idea.

00:24:21.989 --> 00:24:26.829
You have all heard what they have to say about this fourth dimension.

00:24:27.309 --> 00:24:31.189
I have not, said the provincial mayor.

00:24:31.189 --> 00:24:45.589
It is simply this, that space, as our mathematicians have it, is spoken of as having three dimensions, which one may call length, breadth, and thickness,

00:24:45.789 --> 00:24:54.649
and is always definitely by reference to three planes, each at right angles to the others.

00:24:54.649 --> 00:25:06.929
But some philosophical people have been asking why three dimensions, particularly, why not another direction at right angles to the other three,

00:25:07.369 --> 00:25:11.469
and have even tried to construct a four dimensional geometry.

00:25:12.109 --> 00:25:22.009
Professor Simon Newcomb was expounding this to the New York Mathematical Society only a month or so ago.

00:25:22.009 --> 00:25:32.569
You know how on a flat surface, which has only two dimensions, we can represent a figure of a three dimensional solid.

00:25:33.129 --> 00:25:46.789
And similarly, they think that by models of three dimensions, they could represent one of four, if they could master the perspective of the thing.

00:25:46.789 --> 00:25:50.909
See, I think so, murmured the prospective mayor.

00:25:51.449 --> 00:26:02.749
And knitting his brows, he lapsed into an introspective state, his lips moving as one who repeats mystic words.

00:26:03.129 --> 00:26:11.669
Yes, I think I see it now, he said after some time, brightening in a quiet, transitory manner.

00:26:11.669 --> 00:26:21.069
Well, I do not mind telling you I have been at work upon this geometry of four dimensions for some time.

00:26:21.549 --> 00:26:24.909
Some of my results are curious.

00:26:25.349 --> 00:26:38.109
For instance, here is a portrait of a man at eight years old, another at 15, another at 17, another at 23, and so on.

00:26:38.109 --> 00:26:51.209
All these are evidently sections, as it were, three dimensional representations of his four dimensional being, which is a fixed and unalterable thing.

00:26:52.049 --> 00:27:01.309
Scientific people produced the time traveler after the pause requiring for the proper assimilation of this.

00:27:01.309 --> 00:27:05.909
Know very well that time is only a kind of space.

00:27:05.909 --> 00:27:11.149
Here is a popular scientific diagram, a weather record.

00:27:11.609 --> 00:27:16.189
This line I trace with my fingers shows the movement of the barometer.

00:27:16.669 --> 00:27:18.829
Yesterday, it was so high.

00:27:19.229 --> 00:27:20.689
Yesterday night, it fell.

00:27:21.129 --> 00:27:25.009
Then this morning, it rose again and so gently upward to here.

00:27:25.009 --> 00:27:35.729
Surely the mercury did not trace this line in any of the dimensions of space generally recognized, but surely it traced such a line.

00:27:36.209 --> 00:27:41.609
And that line, therefore, we must conclude, was along the time dimension.

00:27:42.089 --> 00:27:46.869
But the medical man staring hard at a coal in the fire.

00:27:46.869 --> 00:27:56.769
If time is really only a fourth dimension of space, why is it and why has it always been regarded as something different?

00:27:57.129 --> 00:28:02.149
And why cannot we move in time as we move about in the other dimensions of space?

00:28:02.769 --> 00:28:04.069
The time traveler smiled.

00:28:04.789 --> 00:28:07.369
Are you sure we can move freely in space?

00:28:07.989 --> 00:28:13.429
Right and left, we can go backward and forward freely enough, and men have always done so.

00:28:13.429 --> 00:28:17.709
I admit we move more freely in two dimensions.

00:28:18.189 --> 00:28:19.649
But how about up and down?

00:28:20.249 --> 00:28:22.549
Gravitation limits us there.

00:28:22.969 --> 00:28:24.729
Not exactly the medical man.

00:28:25.289 --> 00:28:26.129
There are balloons.

00:28:27.509 --> 00:28:39.549
But before the balloons save for spasmatic jumping and the inequalities of the surface, man had no freedom of vertical movement.

00:28:40.349 --> 00:28:45.709
Still, they could move a little up and down, said the medical man.

00:28:46.269 --> 00:28:48.909
Easier, far easier, down than up.

00:28:49.589 --> 00:28:51.749
And you cannot move at all in time.

00:28:51.829 --> 00:28:53.909
You cannot get away from the present moment.

00:28:54.369 --> 00:28:57.509
My dear sir, that is just where you are wrong.

00:28:57.949 --> 00:29:00.669
That is just where the whole world has gone wrong.

00:29:01.029 --> 00:29:03.869
We are always getting away from the present moment.

00:29:03.869 --> 00:29:16.209
Our mental existence, which are immaterial and have no dimensions, are passing along the time dimension with a uniform velocity from the cradle to the grave.

00:29:16.489 --> 00:29:22.669
Just as we should travel down if we begin our existence 50 miles above the Earth's surface.

00:29:23.449 --> 00:29:26.809
But the great difficulty is this, interrupted the psychologist.

00:29:27.429 --> 00:29:31.389
You can move about in all directions of space.

00:29:31.389 --> 00:29:34.349
But you cannot move about in time.

00:29:36.389 --> 00:29:39.449
That is the germ of my great discovery.

00:29:40.189 --> 00:29:44.029
But you are wrong to say that we cannot move about in time.

00:29:44.389 --> 00:29:52.469
For instance, if I am recalling an incident very vividly, I go back to the instance of its occurrence.

00:29:52.949 --> 00:29:55.809
I become absent-minded, as you say.

00:29:56.089 --> 00:29:57.989
I jump back for a moment.

00:29:57.989 --> 00:30:07.729
Of course, we have no means of staying for any length of time, any more than a savage or an animal has of staying six feet above the ground.

00:30:08.589 --> 00:30:12.869
But a civilized man is better off than the savage in this respect.

00:30:13.329 --> 00:30:16.689
He can go up against gravitation in a balloon.

00:30:16.689 --> 00:30:28.389
And why should he not hope that ultimately he may be able to stop or accelerate his drift along the time dimension or even turn about the travel the other way?

00:30:29.569 --> 00:30:32.889
Oh, this, begin Philby, is all.

00:30:33.569 --> 00:30:35.189
Why not, said the time traveler.

00:30:35.829 --> 00:30:38.069
It's against reason, said Philby.

00:30:39.049 --> 00:30:41.029
What reason, said the time traveler.

00:30:41.709 --> 00:30:45.909
You can show black is white by argument, said Philby.

00:30:45.909 --> 00:30:49.029
But you will never convince me.

00:30:49.369 --> 00:30:51.789
Possibly not, said the time traveler.

00:30:52.429 --> 00:30:59.669
But now you begin to see the object of my investigations into the geometry of four dimensions.

00:31:00.089 --> 00:31:04.109
Long ago, I had a vague inkling of a machine.

00:31:04.709 --> 00:31:15.369
To travel through time, exclaimed the very young man, that shall travel indifferently in any direction of space and time, as the driver determines.

00:31:15.369 --> 00:31:19.329
Philby contended himself with laughter.

00:31:20.369 --> 00:31:24.309
But I have experimental verification, said the time traveler.

00:31:25.169 --> 00:31:37.489
It would be remarkably convinced for the historian, the psychologist suggested, one might travel back and verify the accepted account of the Battle of Hastings, for instance.

00:31:38.089 --> 00:31:42.169
Don't you think you would attract attention, said the medical man.

00:31:42.169 --> 00:31:47.249
Our ancestors had no great tolerance for anachronisms.

00:31:47.509 --> 00:31:53.289
One might get one's Greek from the very lips of Homer and Plato, the very young man thought.

00:31:53.869 --> 00:32:02.349
In which case, they would certainly plow you, for the little go, the German scholars, have improved Greek so much.

00:32:03.249 --> 00:32:06.009
Then there's the future, said the very young man.

00:32:06.009 --> 00:32:14.429
Just think, one might investigate all one's money, leave it to accumulate at interest, and hurry on ahead.

00:32:14.989 --> 00:32:21.229
To discover a society, said I, erected on a strictly communistic basis.

00:32:22.129 --> 00:32:26.469
Of all the wild, extravagant theories, began the psychologist.

00:32:27.069 --> 00:32:31.029
Yes, so it seemed to me, and so I never talked of it until.

00:32:32.269 --> 00:32:37.029
Experimental verification, cried I, you're going to verify that.

00:32:37.609 --> 00:32:41.329
The experiment, cried Philby, who was getting brain weary.

00:32:42.189 --> 00:32:48.029
Let's see your experiment anyhow, said the psychologist, though it's all humbug, you know.

00:32:48.409 --> 00:32:54.229
The time traveler smiled round at us, then, still smiling faintly.

00:32:54.229 --> 00:33:01.869
And with his hands deep in his trouser pockets, he walked slowly out of the room.

00:33:02.169 --> 00:33:07.829
And we heard his slippers shuffling down the long passage to his laboratory.

00:33:08.289 --> 00:33:10.149
The psychologist looked at us.

00:33:10.369 --> 00:33:11.849
I wonder what he's got.

00:33:12.909 --> 00:33:16.649
Some sleight of hand trick or other, said the medical man.

00:33:17.069 --> 00:33:22.429
And Philby tried to tell us about a conjurer he had seen at Breslem.

00:33:22.429 --> 00:33:31.809
But before he had finished his preface, the time traveler came back, and Philby's antidote collapsed.

00:33:32.669 --> 00:33:38.929
The thing the time traveler held in his hand was a glittering, metallic framework.

00:33:39.489 --> 00:33:44.989
Scarcely larger than a small clock, and very delicately made.

00:33:45.849 --> 00:33:51.769
There was ivory in it, and some transparent crystalline substances.

00:33:51.769 --> 00:34:03.209
And now I must be explicit, for this that follows, unless his explanation is to be accepted, is an absolutely unaccurate thing.

00:34:03.669 --> 00:34:16.429
He took one of the small octagonal tables that were scattered about the room, and set it in front of the fire, with two legs on the hearth rug.

00:34:16.849 --> 00:34:19.549
On this table he placed the mechanism.

00:34:19.549 --> 00:34:23.469
Then he drew up a chair and sat down.

00:34:23.769 --> 00:34:31.449
The only other object on the table was a small shaded lamp, the bright light of which fell upon the model.

00:34:32.049 --> 00:34:35.489
There were also perhaps a dozen candles about.

00:34:36.009 --> 00:34:46.089
Two in brass candlesticks upon the mantle, and several in scounces, so that the room was brilliantly illuminated.

00:34:46.089 --> 00:34:57.149
I sat in a low armchair, nearest the fire, and I drew this forward so as to be almost between the time traveler and the fireplace.

00:34:57.869 --> 00:35:01.709
Philby sat behind him, looking over his shoulder.

00:35:02.429 --> 00:35:11.549
The medical man and the provincial mayor watched him in profile from the right, the psychologist from the left.

00:35:11.809 --> 00:35:14.289
The very young man stood behind the psychologist.

00:35:14.289 --> 00:35:16.909
We were all on alert.

00:35:17.649 --> 00:35:30.289
It appears incredible to me that any kind of trick, however subtly conceived, and however adroitly done, could have been played upon us under these conditions.

00:35:31.189 --> 00:35:34.749
The time traveler looked at us, and then at the mechanism.

00:35:34.749 --> 00:35:49.729
Well, said the psychologist, this little affair, said the time traveler, resting his elbows upon the table and pressing his hands together above the apparatus, is only a model.

00:35:50.149 --> 00:35:53.789
It is my plan for a machine to travel through time.

00:35:53.789 --> 00:36:06.229
You will notice that it looks singularly askew, and that there is an odd twinkling appearance about this bar, as though it was in some way unreal.

00:36:06.569 --> 00:36:10.389
He pointed to the part with his finger.

00:36:10.929 --> 00:36:15.149
Also, here is one little white lever, and here is another.

00:36:15.829 --> 00:36:20.929
The medical man got up out of his chair and peered into the thing.

00:36:20.929 --> 00:36:23.809
It's beautifully made, he said.

00:36:24.489 --> 00:36:27.989
It took two years to make, retorted the time traveler.

00:36:28.789 --> 00:36:34.829
Then, when we have all imitated the action of the medical man, he said,

00:36:35.289 --> 00:36:47.609
Now I want you clearly to understand that this lever, being pressed over, sends the machine gliding into the future, and this other reverses the motion.

00:36:47.609 --> 00:36:51.409
This saddle represents the seat of a time traveler.

00:36:52.069 --> 00:36:57.129
Presently, I'm going to press the lever, and off the machine will go.

00:36:57.809 --> 00:37:02.289
It will vanish, pass into future time, and disappear.

00:37:02.829 --> 00:37:08.089
Have a good look at the thing, look at the table too, and satisfy yourself.

00:37:08.529 --> 00:37:09.949
There is no trickery.

00:37:10.229 --> 00:37:15.009
I don't want to waste this model, and then be told I'm a quack.

00:37:15.009 --> 00:37:23.509
There was a minute's pause, perhaps, and the psychologist seemed about to speak to me, but changed his mind.

00:37:23.889 --> 00:37:27.669
Then the time traveler put forth his finger towards the lever.

00:37:28.389 --> 00:37:34.469
No, he said suddenly, lend me your hand, and turned to the psychologist.

00:37:34.469 --> 00:37:49.609
He took that individual's hand in his own, and told him to put his forefinger so that it was the psychologist himself who sent forth the model time machine on its interminable voyage.

00:37:50.269 --> 00:37:52.089
We all saw the lever turn.

00:37:52.429 --> 00:37:55.809
I am absolutely certain there was no trickery.

00:37:56.449 --> 00:38:00.769
There was a breath of wind, and the lamp flame jumped.

00:38:00.769 --> 00:38:20.309
One of the candles on the mantle was blown out, and the little machine suddenly swung around, became indistinct, was seen as a ghost for a second, perhaps, as an eddy of faintly glittering brass and ivory, and it was gone, vanished.

00:38:20.649 --> 00:38:23.489
Safe for the lamp, the table was bare.

00:38:24.229 --> 00:38:26.009
Everyone was silent for a minute.

00:38:26.609 --> 00:38:29.189
Then Philby said he was damned.

00:38:29.189 --> 00:38:36.589
The psychologist recovered from his stupor, and suddenly looked under the table.

00:38:37.309 --> 00:38:39.449
At that the time traveler laughed cheerfully.

00:38:40.349 --> 00:38:45.549
Well, he said, without a remonstance of the psychologist.

00:38:46.009 --> 00:38:53.609
Then, getting up, he went to the tobacco jar on the mantle, and with his back to us began to fill his pipe.

00:38:54.609 --> 00:38:56.569
We stared at each other.

00:38:56.569 --> 00:38:59.169
Look here, said the medical man.

00:38:59.729 --> 00:39:01.809
Are you in earnest about this?

00:39:02.109 --> 00:39:06.649
Do you seriously believe that the machine has traveled into time?

00:39:07.389 --> 00:39:13.349
Certainly, said the time traveler, stooping to light a spill at the fire.

00:39:13.349 --> 00:39:19.309
Then he turned, lighting his pipe, to look at the psychologist's face.

00:39:19.569 --> 00:39:27.669
The psychologist, to show that he was not unhinged, helped himself to a cigar, and tried to light it uncut.

00:39:28.529 --> 00:39:41.989
What is more, I have a big machine nearly finished in there, he indicated, the laboratory, and when that is put together, I mean to have a journey of my own account.

00:39:41.989 --> 00:39:48.009
You mean to say that the machine has traveled into the future? said Philby.

00:39:48.269 --> 00:39:52.449
Into the future past, I don't for certainly know which.

00:39:53.149 --> 00:39:56.849
After an interval, the psychologist had an inspiration.

00:39:57.849 --> 00:40:01.829
It must have gone into the past, if it has gone anywhere, he said.

00:40:02.669 --> 00:40:11.629
Why, said the time traveler, because I presume that it has not moved in space, and if it traveled into the future, it would still be here.

00:40:11.629 --> 00:40:16.249
All this time, since it must have traveled through this time.

00:40:17.089 --> 00:40:27.609
But, I said, if it traveled into the past, it would have been visible when we came first into this room, and last Thursday when we were here, and the Thursday before that, and so forth.

00:40:29.109 --> 00:40:36.529
Serious objections, remarked the provincial mayor, with an air of impartiality turning towards the time traveler.

00:40:36.529 --> 00:40:42.989
Not a bit, said the time traveler, and to the psychologist, you think you can explain that?

00:40:43.349 --> 00:40:47.069
It's presentation below the threshold, you know.

00:40:48.289 --> 00:40:49.649
Delicated presentation.

00:40:50.429 --> 00:40:56.229
Of course, said the psychologist, and reassured us, that's a simple point of psychology.

00:40:56.849 --> 00:40:58.429
I should have thought of it.

00:40:58.729 --> 00:41:02.429
It's plain enough, and helps the paradox delightfully.

00:41:02.429 --> 00:41:12.969
We cannot see it, nor can we appreciate this machine, any more than we can the spoke of a wheel spinning, or a bullet flying through the air.

00:41:13.209 --> 00:41:22.429
If it is traveling through time fifty times or a hundred times faster than we are, if it gets through a minute while we get through a second,

00:41:22.429 --> 00:41:32.169
The impression it creates will, of course, be only one-fifteenth or one-hundredth of what it would make if it were not traveling in time.

00:41:32.729 --> 00:41:33.869
That's plain enough.

00:41:34.329 --> 00:41:38.409
He passed his hand through the space in which the machine had been.

00:41:38.749 --> 00:41:45.889
You see, said he, laughing, we sat and started at the vacant table for a minute or so.

00:41:46.349 --> 00:41:50.069
Then the time traveler asked us what we thought of it all.

00:41:50.069 --> 00:41:55.769
It sounds plausible enough tonight, said the medical man, but wait until tomorrow.

00:41:56.109 --> 00:41:58.529
Wait for the common sense of the morning.

00:41:59.509 --> 00:42:03.009
Would you like to see the time machine itself? asked the time traveler.

00:42:03.809 --> 00:42:11.669
And there, when taking the lamp in his hand, he led the way down the long drottie corridor to his laboratory.

00:42:11.669 --> 00:42:23.969
I remember vividly the flickering light, his queer broad head in silhouette, the dance of the shadows, how we all followed him,

00:42:24.189 --> 00:42:37.109
puzzled but incredulous, and how there in the laboratory we beheld a larger edition of the light mechanism which we had seen vanish from before our eyes.

00:42:37.109 --> 00:42:45.949
Parts were of nickel, parts of ivory, parts had certainly been filled or sawn out of rock crystal.

00:42:46.609 --> 00:42:58.969
The thing was generally complete, but the twisted crystalline bars lay unfinished upon the bench beside some sheets of drawings,

00:42:59.429 --> 00:43:03.349
and I took one up for a better look at it.

00:43:03.749 --> 00:43:05.169
Quartz seemed to be.

00:43:05.169 --> 00:43:07.589
Look here, said the medical man.

00:43:07.889 --> 00:43:14.289
Are you perfectly serious, or is this a trick, like the ghost you showed us last Christmas?

00:43:15.189 --> 00:43:22.009
Upon the machine, said the time traveler, holding the lamp aloft, I intend to explore time.

00:43:22.649 --> 00:43:26.269
Is that plain? I was never more serious in my life.

00:43:26.889 --> 00:43:29.689
None of us quite knew how to take it.

00:43:29.689 --> 00:43:36.689
I caught Philby's eye over the shoulder of the medical man, and he winked at me solemnly.

00:44:10.497 --> 00:44:14.557
That's L-I-B-R-I-V-O-X dot org.

00:44:15.577 --> 00:44:20.657
The Time Machine by H.G. Wells

00:44:20.657 --> 00:44:25.897
I think that at that time none of us quite believed in the Time Machine.

00:44:26.337 --> 00:44:31.957
The fact is the Time Traveler was one of those men who are too clever to be believed.

00:44:32.637 --> 00:44:35.877
You never felt that you saw all around him.

00:44:36.277 --> 00:44:44.097
You always expected some subtle reserve, some ingenuity, an ambush behind his lucid frankness.

00:44:44.577 --> 00:44:49.917
Had Philby shown the model and explained the matter in the Time Traveler's words,

00:44:49.917 --> 00:44:53.597
we should have shown him far less skepticism.

00:44:54.137 --> 00:44:57.117
For we should have perceived his motives.

00:44:57.637 --> 00:45:00.077
A poor butcher could understand Philby,

00:45:00.517 --> 00:45:06.977
but the Time Traveler had more than a touch of whim among his elements, and we distressed him.

00:45:07.517 --> 00:45:13.897
Things that would have made the frame of a less clever man seem tricks in his hands.

00:45:14.377 --> 00:45:17.317
It is a mistake to do things too easily.

00:45:17.317 --> 00:45:24.197
The serious people who took him seriously never felt quite sure of his department.

00:45:25.117 --> 00:45:34.817
They were somehow aware that trusting their reputations for judgment with him was like furnishing a nursery with eggshell china.

00:45:35.477 --> 00:45:43.717
So I don't think any of us said very much about time traveling in the interval between that Thursday and the next.

00:45:43.717 --> 00:45:49.997
Though its odd potentialities ran, no doubt, in most of our minds.

00:45:50.437 --> 00:45:54.697
Its plausibility, that is, its practical incredibleness,

00:45:55.277 --> 00:46:02.717
the curious possibilities of anachronism and of utter confusion is suggested for my own part.

00:46:03.037 --> 00:46:12.117
I was particularly preoccupied with this trick of the model that I remember discussing with the medical man

00:46:12.117 --> 00:46:15.077
whom I met on Friday at the Lineon.

00:46:15.397 --> 00:46:26.437
He said he had seen a similar thing at Tubings and laid considerable stress on the bellowing out of the candle,

00:46:27.157 --> 00:46:30.277
but how the trick was done he could not explain.

00:46:31.457 --> 00:46:34.637
The next Thursday I went again to Richmond.

00:46:35.017 --> 00:46:39.517
I suppose I was one of the Time Traveler's most constant guests,

00:46:39.517 --> 00:46:45.737
and arriving late found four or five men already assembled in his drawing room.

00:46:46.217 --> 00:46:53.017
The medical man was standing before the fire with a sheet of paper in one hand and his watch in the other.

00:46:53.317 --> 00:46:55.937
I looked around for the Time Traveler and

00:46:55.937 --> 00:46:58.917
It's half past seven now, said the medical man.

00:46:59.257 --> 00:47:01.637
I suppose we'd better have dinner.

00:47:02.577 --> 00:47:04.937
Where's, said I, naming our host.

00:47:05.857 --> 00:47:10.617
You've just come. It's rather odd. He's unavoidably detained.

00:47:11.197 --> 00:47:19.657
He asked me in this note to lead off with dinner at seven if he's not back, says he'll explain when he comes.

00:47:19.657 --> 00:47:29.037
It seems a pity to let the dinner spoil, said the editor of the well-known delay paper, and thereupon the doctor rang the bell.

00:47:29.417 --> 00:47:36.797
The psychologist was the only person besides the doctor and myself who had attended the previous dinner.

00:47:37.417 --> 00:47:39.557
The other men were blank.

00:47:39.557 --> 00:47:50.557
The editor aforementioned a certain journalist, and another, a quite shy man with a beard, whom I didn't know,

00:47:50.797 --> 00:47:57.417
and who, as far as my observation went, never opened his mouth all the evening.

00:47:57.417 --> 00:48:09.297
There was some speculation at the dinner table about the Time Traveler's absence, and I suggested time traveling in a half-jokelar spirit.

00:48:09.877 --> 00:48:12.057
The editor wanted that explained to him.

00:48:12.197 --> 00:48:20.757
The psychologist volunteered a wooden account of the ingenious paradox we had witnessed that day week.

00:48:20.757 --> 00:48:28.417
He was in the midst of his exposition when the door from the corridor opened slowly and without noise.

00:48:28.917 --> 00:48:31.597
I was facing the door and saw it first.

00:48:31.797 --> 00:48:38.977
Hello! I said. At last! And the door opened wider, and the Time Traveler stood before us.

00:48:39.317 --> 00:48:40.877
I gave a cry of surprise.

00:48:41.297 --> 00:48:43.717
Good heavens! Man, what's the matter?

00:48:43.717 --> 00:48:51.037
cried the medical man, who saw him next, and the whole tableful turned towards the door.

00:48:51.917 --> 00:48:59.957
He was in an amazing plight. His coat was dusty and dirty, and smeared with green down the sleeves.

00:49:00.437 --> 00:49:09.677
His hair disordered and, as it seemed to me, grayer, either with dust or dirt, because its color had actually faded.

00:49:09.677 --> 00:49:17.357
His face was ghastly pale. His chin had a brown cut on it, a cut half-healed.

00:49:17.777 --> 00:49:21.717
His expression was haggard and drawn, as if by intense suffering.

00:49:22.317 --> 00:49:28.337
For a moment, he hesitated in the doorway, as if he had been dazzled by the light.

00:49:28.837 --> 00:49:35.717
Then he came into the room. He walked with just such a limp as I have seen in foot-store tramps.

00:49:35.717 --> 00:49:40.217
We stared at him in silence, expecting him to speak.

00:49:40.857 --> 00:49:47.197
He said not a word, but came painfully to the table, and made a motion towards the wine.

00:49:47.717 --> 00:49:53.357
The editor filled a glass of champagne, and pushed it towards him.

00:49:53.937 --> 00:49:57.617
He drained it, and it seemed to do him good.

00:49:57.877 --> 00:50:03.917
For he looked round the table, and the ghost of his old smile flickered across his face.

00:50:03.917 --> 00:50:07.937
What on earth have you been up to, man? said the doctor.

00:50:08.577 --> 00:50:11.737
The time traveler did not seem to hear.

00:50:12.457 --> 00:50:17.557
Don't let me disturb you, he said, with a certain flattery articulation.

00:50:18.537 --> 00:50:24.177
I'm all right, he stopped, held out his glass for more, and took it off at a drop.

00:50:24.737 --> 00:50:30.577
That's good, he said. His eyes grew brighter, and a faint color came into his cheeks.

00:50:30.577 --> 00:50:39.997
His glance flickered over our faces, with a certain dull approval, and then went round the warm and comfortable room.

00:50:40.537 --> 00:50:46.517
Then he spoke again, still, as it were, feeling his way among his words.

00:50:46.977 --> 00:50:52.077
I'm going to wash and dress, and then I'll come down and explain things.

00:50:52.817 --> 00:50:56.397
Save me some of that mutton, I'm starving for a bit of meat.

00:50:56.397 --> 00:51:03.377
He looked across at the editor, who was a rare visitor, and hoped he was all right.

00:51:03.497 --> 00:51:05.157
The editor began a question.

00:51:05.957 --> 00:51:11.257
Tell you presently, said the time traveler, I'm funny, but all right in a minute.

00:51:12.297 --> 00:51:16.817
He put down his glass, and walked towards the staircase door.

00:51:17.397 --> 00:51:23.057
Again, I remarked his lameness, and the soft patting sound of his footfall.

00:51:23.057 --> 00:51:28.797
And standing up in my place, I saw his feet as he went out.

00:51:29.177 --> 00:51:33.737
He had nothing on them but a pair of tattered, blood-stained socks.

00:51:34.317 --> 00:51:36.557
Then the door closed upon him.

00:51:36.917 --> 00:51:43.317
I had half a mind to follow, till I remembered how he detested any fuss about himself.

00:51:43.777 --> 00:51:47.337
For a minute, perhaps, my mind was wool-gathering.

00:51:47.337 --> 00:51:56.297
Then, remarkable behavior of an eminent scientist, I heard the editor say, thinking, after his want, in headliness.

00:51:57.137 --> 00:52:00.457
And this brought my attention back to the bright dinner table.

00:52:01.117 --> 00:52:03.257
What's the game? said the journalist.

00:52:03.997 --> 00:52:08.197
Has he been doing the amateur Codgar? I don't follow.

00:52:08.757 --> 00:52:13.537
I met the eye of the psychologist, and read my own interpretation in his face.

00:52:13.537 --> 00:52:17.677
I thought of the time traveler limping painfully upstairs.

00:52:18.277 --> 00:52:22.397
I don't think anyone else had noticed his lameness.

00:52:22.937 --> 00:52:28.497
The first to recover completely from the surprise was the medical man, who rang the bell.

00:52:28.717 --> 00:52:33.357
The time traveler hated to have servants waiting at dinner for a hot plate.

00:52:34.557 --> 00:52:42.817
At that, the editor turned to his knife and fork with a grunt, and the silent man followed suit.

00:52:42.817 --> 00:52:45.257
The dinner was resumed.

00:52:45.397 --> 00:52:50.157
The conversation was exclamatory for a little while, with gaps of wonderment.

00:52:50.457 --> 00:52:54.037
And then the editor got fervent in his curiosity.

00:52:55.037 --> 00:53:01.997
Does our friend ache out his modest income with a crossing, or has he his nebuchadnezzar phases?

00:53:02.637 --> 00:53:03.717
He inquired.

00:53:04.017 --> 00:53:11.137
I feel assured it's this business of the time machine, I said, and took up the psychologist's account of our previous meeting.

00:53:11.137 --> 00:53:14.937
The new guests were frankly incredulous.

00:53:17.017 --> 00:53:18.837
The editor raised objection.

00:53:19.437 --> 00:53:21.717
What was this time traveling?

00:53:22.317 --> 00:53:27.437
A man couldn't cover himself with dust by rowing in a paradox, could he?

00:53:28.017 --> 00:53:34.157
And then, as the idea came home to him, he resorted to caricature.

00:53:34.857 --> 00:53:37.997
Hadn't they any clothes, brushes in the future?

00:53:37.997 --> 00:53:48.537
The journalist, too, wouldn't not believe at any price, and joined the editor in the easy work of heaping ridicule on the whole thing.

00:53:49.177 --> 00:53:59.977
They were both the new kind of journalists, very joyous, irreverent young men, our special consponent in the day after tomorrow reports.

00:54:00.337 --> 00:54:05.997
The journalist was saying, or rather shouting, when the time traveler came back.

00:54:05.997 --> 00:54:14.917
He was dressed in ordinary evening clothes, and nothing save his haggard look remained of the change that had startled me.

00:54:15.357 --> 00:54:22.777
I say, said the editor, hilarious, these chaps here say you have been traveling into the middle of next week.

00:54:23.457 --> 00:54:27.017
Tell us all about the little Roseberry, will you?

00:54:27.377 --> 00:54:29.337
What will you take for the launch?

00:54:29.877 --> 00:54:34.337
The time traveler came to the place reserved for him without a word.

00:54:34.337 --> 00:54:37.257
He smiled quietly in his old way.

00:54:37.837 --> 00:54:39.557
Where is my mutton? he said.

00:54:40.237 --> 00:54:42.877
What a treat it is to stick for into me again.

00:54:43.877 --> 00:54:45.257
Story, cried the editor.

00:54:45.937 --> 00:54:48.637
Story be damned, said the time traveler.

00:54:48.857 --> 00:54:50.677
I want something to eat.

00:54:51.237 --> 00:54:55.657
I won't say a word until I get some pep done into my arteries.

00:54:56.337 --> 00:54:56.737
Thanks.

00:54:57.497 --> 00:54:58.177
And the salt.

00:54:59.217 --> 00:55:00.317
One word, said I.

00:55:00.877 --> 00:55:02.037
Have you been time traveling?

00:55:02.037 --> 00:55:07.117
Yes, said the time traveler with his mouth full, nodding his head.

00:55:08.337 --> 00:55:12.917
I'd give a shilling a line for a verbatim note, said the editor.

00:55:13.457 --> 00:55:19.537
The time traveler pushed his glass toward the silent man and rang it with his fingernail.

00:55:19.637 --> 00:55:27.717
At which the silent man, who had been staring at his face, started convulsively and poured him wine.

00:55:27.717 --> 00:55:30.717
The rest of the dinner was uncomfortable.

00:55:31.377 --> 00:55:36.177
For my own part, sudden questions kept on rising to my lips.

00:55:36.577 --> 00:55:39.817
And I dare say it was the same with the others.

00:55:40.337 --> 00:55:46.757
The journalist tried to relieve the tension by telling antidotes of Hetty Potter.

00:55:47.337 --> 00:55:54.217
The time traveler devoted his attention to his dinner and displayed the appetite of a tramp.

00:55:54.217 --> 00:56:00.857
The medical man smoked a cigarette and watched the time traveler through his eyelashes.

00:56:01.297 --> 00:56:11.937
The silent man seemed even more clumsy than usual and drank champagne with regularity and determination out of sheer nervousness.

00:56:12.177 --> 00:56:16.557
At last, the time traveler pushed his plate away and looked around us.

00:56:16.757 --> 00:56:18.997
I suppose I must apologize, he said.

00:56:19.357 --> 00:56:20.777
I was simply starving.

00:56:21.357 --> 00:56:23.697
I've had a most amazing time.

00:56:23.697 --> 00:56:29.597
He reached out his hand for a cigar, cut the end, but come into the smoking room.

00:56:29.877 --> 00:56:32.577
It's too long a story to tell over greasy plates.

00:56:33.357 --> 00:56:37.737
And ringing the bell and passing, he led the way into the adjoining room.

00:56:38.097 --> 00:56:40.757
You have told Blank and Dash and Chode about the machine?

00:56:41.417 --> 00:56:46.637
He said to me, leaning back in his easy chair and naming the three new guests.

00:56:47.457 --> 00:56:50.657
But the thing's a mere paradox, said the editor.

00:56:51.057 --> 00:56:52.717
I can't argue tonight.

00:56:52.717 --> 00:56:56.277
I don't mind telling you the story, but I can't argue.

00:56:56.737 --> 00:57:01.857
I will, he went on, tell you the story of what has happened to me, if you like.

00:57:02.297 --> 00:57:05.077
But you must refrain from interruptions.

00:57:05.437 --> 00:57:07.237
I want to tell it badly.

00:57:07.737 --> 00:57:11.037
Most of it will sound like lying, so be it.

00:57:11.237 --> 00:57:12.877
It's true every word of it.

00:57:12.877 --> 00:57:17.137
All the same, I was in my laboratory at four o'clock.

00:57:17.457 --> 00:57:24.357
And since then, I've lived eight days, such days as no human being ever lived before.

00:57:25.017 --> 00:57:26.537
I'm nearly worn out.

00:57:26.877 --> 00:57:29.357
But I shan't sleep till I told this thing over to you.

00:57:29.677 --> 00:57:31.257
Then I should go to bed.

00:57:31.937 --> 00:57:34.017
But no interruption, is it agreed?

00:57:34.677 --> 00:57:38.537
Agreed, said the editor, and the rest of us echoed, agreed.

00:57:38.537 --> 00:57:43.937
And with that, the time traveler began his story, as I have set it forth.

00:57:44.077 --> 00:57:48.597
He sat back in his chair at first and spoke like a weary man.

00:57:49.017 --> 00:57:52.617
Afterwards, he got more animated in writing it down.

00:57:52.757 --> 00:58:03.097
I feel, with only too much keenness, the inadequacy of pen and ink, and, above all, my own inadequacy to express its quality.

00:58:03.097 --> 00:58:17.157
You read, I will suppose, attentively enough, but you cannot see the speaker's white, sincere face in the bright circle of the little lamp, nor hear the intonation of his voice.

00:58:17.357 --> 00:58:22.357
You cannot know how his expression followed, the turns of his story.

00:58:22.357 --> 00:58:35.457
Most of us, hearers, were in shadow, for the candleless in the smoking room had not been lightened, and only the face of the journalist and the legs of the silent man from the knees downward were illuminated.

00:58:35.977 --> 00:58:39.677
At first, we glanced now and again at each other.

00:58:39.857 --> 00:58:45.177
After time, we ceased to do that, and looked only at the time traveler's face.

00:58:50.937 --> 00:58:54.357
This has been a TBOL3 production.

00:59:12.633 --> 00:59:16.413
That's L-I-B-R-I-V-O-X dot org.

00:59:17.893 --> 00:59:20.373
The Time Machine by H.G. Wells.

00:59:21.153 --> 00:59:26.633
I told some of you last Thursday of the principles of the Time Machine,

00:59:27.493 --> 00:59:31.653
and showed you the actual thing itself, incomplete in the workshop.

00:59:32.293 --> 00:59:35.713
There it is now, a little travel-worn truly,

00:59:36.193 --> 00:59:39.993
and one of the ivory bars is cracked, and a brass rail bent.

00:59:40.493 --> 00:59:42.333
But the rest of it's sound enough.

00:59:43.013 --> 00:59:46.393
I expected to finish it on Friday, but on Friday,

00:59:46.393 --> 00:59:49.333
When the putting together was nearly done,

00:59:49.493 --> 00:59:54.333
I found that one of the nickel bars was exactly one inch too short,

00:59:54.753 --> 00:59:57.333
and this I had to get remade,

00:59:57.513 --> 01:00:01.633
so that the thing was not complete until this morning.

01:00:02.173 --> 01:00:04.493
It was at ten o'clock today,

01:00:05.113 --> 01:00:09.173
that the first of all the Time Machines began its career.

01:00:09.793 --> 01:00:14.573
I gave it a last tap, tried all the screws again,

01:00:14.573 --> 01:00:18.793
put one more drop of oil on the quartz rod,

01:00:19.393 --> 01:00:21.193
and sat myself in a saddle.

01:00:21.913 --> 01:00:26.173
I suppose a suicide, who holds a pistol to a school,

01:00:26.693 --> 01:00:31.773
feels much the same wonder at what will come next, as I felt then.

01:00:32.313 --> 01:00:36.793
I took the starting lever in one hand, and the stopping one in the other,

01:00:37.293 --> 01:00:40.633
pressed the first and almost immediately the second.

01:00:40.633 --> 01:00:42.653
I seemed too real.

01:00:42.993 --> 01:00:45.553
I felt a nightmare sensation of falling,

01:00:46.113 --> 01:00:50.073
and looking round, I saw the laboratory exactly as before.

01:00:50.473 --> 01:00:51.653
Had anything happened?

01:00:52.113 --> 01:00:56.793
For a moment, I suspected that my intellect had tricked me.

01:00:57.133 --> 01:00:58.473
Then I noticed the clock.

01:00:59.093 --> 01:01:04.913
A moment before, as it seemed, it had stood at a minute or so past ten.

01:01:05.313 --> 01:01:07.653
Now it was nearly half past three.

01:01:07.653 --> 01:01:10.833
I drew a breath, set my teeth,

01:01:11.113 --> 01:01:14.073
gripped the starting lever with both hands,

01:01:14.453 --> 01:01:16.133
and went off with a thud.

01:01:16.893 --> 01:01:19.773
The laboratory got hazy and went dark.

01:01:20.333 --> 01:01:24.953
Mrs. Wedgecat came in and walked, apparently without seeing me,

01:01:25.113 --> 01:01:26.373
towards the garden door.

01:01:26.933 --> 01:01:31.893
I suppose it took her a minute or so to traverse the place,

01:01:32.193 --> 01:01:36.773
but to me she seemed to shoot across the room like a rocket.

01:01:36.773 --> 01:01:40.153
I pressed the lever over to its extreme position.

01:01:40.913 --> 01:01:43.753
The night came like turning out of a lamp,

01:01:44.433 --> 01:01:46.613
and in another moment came tomorrow.

01:01:47.133 --> 01:01:52.053
The laboratory grew faint and hazy, the fainter and ever fainter.

01:01:52.593 --> 01:01:54.133
Tomorrow night came black.

01:01:54.653 --> 01:01:59.313
Then, day after, night again, day again, faster and faster still,

01:01:59.893 --> 01:02:02.593
an eddying murmur filled my ears,

01:02:02.593 --> 01:02:07.773
and a strange, dumb, confusedness descended on my mind.

01:02:08.273 --> 01:02:12.693
I'm afraid I cannot convey the peculiar sensation of time traveling.

01:02:13.313 --> 01:02:15.553
They are excessively unpleasant.

01:02:16.113 --> 01:02:20.493
There is a feeling exactly like that one has upon a switchback

01:02:20.493 --> 01:02:22.753
of a helpless headlong motion.

01:02:23.433 --> 01:02:28.753
I felt the same horrible anticipation, too, of an imminent smash.

01:02:29.113 --> 01:02:32.193
As I put on pace night followed day,

01:02:32.193 --> 01:02:34.693
like the flapping of a black wing.

01:02:35.053 --> 01:02:41.733
The dim suggestion of the laboratory seemed presently to fall away from me,

01:02:42.193 --> 01:02:46.073
and I saw the sun hoping swiftly across the sky,

01:02:46.393 --> 01:02:49.893
leaping it every minute, and every minute marking a day.

01:02:50.233 --> 01:02:53.033
I suppose that the laboratory had been destroyed,

01:02:53.193 --> 01:02:55.793
and I had come into the open air.

01:02:56.293 --> 01:02:59.793
I had a dim impression of scuffling,

01:02:59.793 --> 01:03:05.553
but I was already going too fast to be conscious of any moving things.

01:03:06.473 --> 01:03:10.973
The slowest snail to ever crawl dashing by too fast for me.

01:03:11.393 --> 01:03:18.333
The twinkling succession of darkness and light was excessively painful to the eye.

01:03:18.713 --> 01:03:21.093
Then, in the intermittent darkness,

01:03:22.033 --> 01:03:28.093
I saw the moon spinning swiftly through her quarters from new to full,

01:03:28.093 --> 01:03:32.553
and had a faint glimpse of the circling stars.

01:03:33.153 --> 01:03:37.553
Presently, as I went on, still gaining velocity,

01:03:38.733 --> 01:03:43.833
the palpitation of night and day merged into one continuous grayness.

01:03:44.313 --> 01:03:47.813
The sky took on a wonderful deepness of blue,

01:03:48.233 --> 01:03:52.633
a splendid lumpious color like that of early twilight.

01:03:53.193 --> 01:03:56.813
The jerking sun became a streak of fire,

01:03:56.813 --> 01:04:02.713
a brilliant arc in space, the moon a fainter fluctuating band,

01:04:03.093 --> 01:04:05.613
and I could see nothing of the stars,

01:04:05.953 --> 01:04:09.653
save now and then a brighter circle flickering in the blue.

01:04:10.193 --> 01:04:12.393
The landscape was misty and vague.

01:04:12.833 --> 01:04:17.153
I was still on the hillside upon which this house now stands,

01:04:17.773 --> 01:04:20.833
and the shoulder rose above me, gray and dim.

01:04:21.253 --> 01:04:25.873
I saw trees growing and changing like puffs of vapor,

01:04:25.873 --> 01:04:28.333
now brown, now green.

01:04:28.553 --> 01:04:32.293
They grew, spreading, shivered, and passed away.

01:04:32.813 --> 01:04:38.373
I saw huge buildings rise up, faint and fair, and pass like dreams.

01:04:39.013 --> 01:04:45.213
The whole surface of the earth seemed changed, melting and flowing under my eyes.

01:04:45.873 --> 01:04:53.733
The little hands upon the dials that registered my speed raced round, faster and faster.

01:04:53.733 --> 01:05:01.913
Presently I noted that the sun belt swayed up and down from solstice to solstice in a minute or less,

01:05:02.433 --> 01:05:06.333
and that consequently my pace was over a year a minute.

01:05:06.973 --> 01:05:12.973
And minute by minute the white snow flashed across the world and vanished,

01:05:13.253 --> 01:05:16.973
and was followed by the bright brief green of spring.

01:05:17.453 --> 01:05:22.353
The unpleasant sensation of the start were less poignant now.

01:05:22.353 --> 01:05:27.033
They merged at last into a kind of hysterical exhilaration.

01:05:27.573 --> 01:05:33.693
I remarked indeed a clumsy swaying of the machine, for which I was unable to account.

01:05:34.413 --> 01:05:37.613
But my mind was too confused to attract to it.

01:05:37.873 --> 01:05:43.873
So with a kind of madness growing upon me, I flung myself into futurity.

01:05:43.873 --> 01:05:51.953
At first I scarce thought of stopping, scarce thought of anything but these new sensations.

01:05:52.533 --> 01:06:01.113
But presently a fresh series of impressions grew up in my mind, a certain curiosity, and there was a certain dread.

01:06:01.513 --> 01:06:04.653
Until at last they took complete possession of me.

01:06:05.013 --> 01:06:12.933
What strange developments of humanity, what wonderful advances upon our rudimentary civilization, I thought.

01:06:12.933 --> 01:06:23.173
Might not appear when I came to look nearly into the dim elusive world that raced and fluctuated before my eyes.

01:06:23.673 --> 01:06:32.693
I saw great and splendid architecture rising about me, more massive than any buildings of our own time.

01:06:32.913 --> 01:06:40.833
And yet, as it seemed built of glimmer and mist, I saw a richer green flow upon the hillside,

01:06:40.833 --> 01:06:44.873
and remained there without any wintry intermission.

01:06:45.073 --> 01:06:52.853
Even through the veil of my confusion, the earth seemed very fair, and so my mind came round to the business of stopping.

01:06:53.293 --> 01:07:03.633
The peculiar risk lay in the possibility of my finding some substance in the space which I or the machine occupied.

01:07:04.013 --> 01:07:09.433
So long as I traveled at a high velocity through time, this scarcity mattered.

01:07:09.433 --> 01:07:19.373
I was, so to speak, attenuated, was slipping like a vapor through the intermisses of intervening substances.

01:07:20.033 --> 01:07:27.433
But to come to a stop involved the jamming of myself, molecule by molecule, into whatever lay in the way.

01:07:27.433 --> 01:07:38.613
Meant bringing my atoms into such intimate contact with those of the obstacles that a profound chemical reaction,

01:07:39.713 --> 01:07:50.353
possibly a fair-reaching explosion, would result, and blow myself and my apparatus out of all possible dimensions into the unknown.

01:07:50.933 --> 01:07:56.633
This possibility had occurred to me again and again while I was making the machine.

01:07:56.633 --> 01:08:05.093
But then I had cheerfully accepted it as an unavoidable risk, one of the risks a man has got to take.

01:08:05.553 --> 01:08:11.813
Now the risk was inevitable. I no longer saw it in the same cheerful light.

01:08:12.393 --> 01:08:21.413
The fact is that, incessantly, the absolute strangeness of everything, the sickly jarring and swaying of the machine,

01:08:21.413 --> 01:08:28.253
about all the feeling of the prolonged falling, had absolutely upset my nerve.

01:08:28.893 --> 01:08:36.293
I told myself that I could never stop, and with a gust of petulance resolved to stop forthwith.

01:08:36.793 --> 01:08:47.393
Like an impatient fool, I lugged over the lever, and, uncountably, the thing went reeling over, and I was flung headlong through the air.

01:08:47.393 --> 01:08:54.013
There was the sound of a clap of thunder in my ears. I may have been stunned for a moment.

01:08:54.433 --> 01:09:01.873
A pitiless hail was hissing round me, and I was sitting on soft turf in front of the overset machine.

01:09:02.673 --> 01:09:09.773
Everything still seemed gray, but presently I remarked that the confusion in my ears was gone.

01:09:09.773 --> 01:09:18.273
I looked round me. I was on what seemed to be a little lawn in a garden, surrounded by road-drawn bushes,

01:09:18.273 --> 01:09:27.033
and I noticed that their wave and purple blossoms were dropping in a shower under the beating of the hell stones.

01:09:27.573 --> 01:09:35.153
The rebounding, dancing hail hung in a cloud over the machine, and drove along the ground like smoke.

01:09:35.153 --> 01:09:37.933
In a moment, I went to the skin.

01:09:38.573 --> 01:09:46.353
Fine hospitality, said I, to a man who was travelling innumerable years to see you.

01:09:47.013 --> 01:09:52.593
Presently, I thought I was a fool. I was to get wet. I stood up and looked round me.

01:09:52.893 --> 01:10:02.873
A colossal figure, carved apparently in some white stone, loomed indistinctly beyond the Redendras, through the hazy downpour.

01:10:02.873 --> 01:10:12.193
But all else of the world was invisible. My sensation would be hard to describe, as the column of hail grew thinner.

01:10:12.793 --> 01:10:20.833
I saw the white figure more distinctly. It was very large, for a silver birch tree touched its shoulder.

01:10:21.313 --> 01:10:26.753
It was of white marble, and shaped something like a winged sphinx.

01:10:26.753 --> 01:10:35.613
But the wings, instead of being carried vertically at the sides, were spread so that it seemed to hover.

01:10:36.273 --> 01:10:43.493
The pedestal, it appeared to me, was of bronze, and was thick with verdigris.

01:10:44.133 --> 01:10:50.593
It chanced that the face was towards me. The sightless eyes seemed to watch me.

01:10:50.593 --> 01:11:01.193
There was the faint shadow of a smile on the lips. It was greatly weather-worn, and that imparted an unpleasant suggestion of disease.

01:11:01.913 --> 01:11:07.333
I stood looking at it for a little space, half a minute perhaps, or half an hour.

01:11:07.593 --> 01:11:14.013
It seemed to advance and to recede as the hail drove before it denser or thinner.

01:11:14.013 --> 01:11:26.953
At last I tore my eyes from it for a moment, and saw the hail curtain had worn, threadbare, and that the sky was lightning with the promise of the sun.

01:11:27.633 --> 01:11:36.413
I looked up again at the crouching white shape, and the full tementary of my voyage came suddenly upon me.

01:11:36.613 --> 01:11:43.213
What might appear when the hazy curtain was altogether withdrawn? What might not have happened to men?

01:11:43.213 --> 01:11:59.553
What if cruelty had grown into a common passion? What if, in this interval, the race had lost its manliness and had developed into something inhuman, unsympathetic, and overwhelmingly powerful?

01:12:00.013 --> 01:12:12.453
I might seem some old-world savage animal, only the more dreadful and disgusting for our common likeness, a foul creature to be incontently slain.

01:12:12.453 --> 01:12:27.513
I already saw other vast shapes, huge buildings with intricate parapets and tall columns with a wooden hillside dimly creeping it upon me through the lessening storm.

01:12:28.133 --> 01:12:36.633
I was seized with a panic fear. I turned frantically to the time machine and strove hard to readjust it.

01:12:36.633 --> 01:12:47.953
As I did so, the shafts of the sun smote through the thunderstorm. The gray downpour was swept aside and vanished like the trailing garments of a ghost.

01:12:47.953 --> 01:12:56.973
Above me, in the intense blue of the summer sky, some faint brown shreds of cloud whirled into nothingness.

01:12:57.373 --> 01:13:13.753
The great buildings about me stood out clear and distinct, shining with the wet of the thunderstorm and picked out in white by the emulating hailstones piled along their courses.

01:13:13.753 --> 01:13:24.273
I felt naked in a strange world. I felt as perhaps a bird may feel in the clear air, knowing the hawk wings above and will swoop.

01:13:24.693 --> 01:13:33.793
My fear grew to frenzy. I took a breathing space, set my teeth, and again grabbed fiercely, whisked and knee with the machine.

01:13:33.793 --> 01:13:44.633
It gave under my desperate onset and turned over. It struck my chin violently, one hand on the saddle, the other on the lever.

01:13:45.093 --> 01:13:53.693
I stood panting heavily in the attitude to mount again. But with this recovery of prompt retreat, my courage recovered.

01:13:53.693 --> 01:13:59.733
I looked more curiously and less fearfully at this world of the remote future.

01:14:00.433 --> 01:14:09.473
In a circular opening high up in the wall of the near house, I saw a group of figures clad in rich soft robes.

01:14:09.593 --> 01:14:14.613
They had seen me and their faces were directed towards me.

01:14:14.613 --> 01:14:25.333
Then I heard voices approaching me coming through the bushes by the white sphinx, where the heads and shoulders of men running.

01:14:25.953 --> 01:14:33.553
One of these emerged in a pathway leading straight to the little lawn upon which I stood with my machine.

01:14:33.553 --> 01:14:44.433
He was a slight creature, perhaps four feet high, clad in a purple tunic. Girdled at the waist was a leather belt.

01:14:44.933 --> 01:14:56.733
Sandals or buskins, I could not clearly distinguish, which were on his feet. His legs were bare to the knees, and his head was bare.

01:14:57.133 --> 01:15:01.793
Noticing that, I noticed for the first time how warm the air was.

01:15:01.793 --> 01:15:09.073
He struck me as being a very beautiful and graceful creature, but indescribably frail.

01:15:09.713 --> 01:15:22.133
His fleshed face reminded me of the more beautiful kind of consumptive, that hectic beauty of which we used to hear so much.

01:15:22.493 --> 01:15:30.353
At the sight of him, I suddenly regained confidence. I took my hands from the machine.

01:15:46.073 --> 01:15:49.573
That's L-I-B-R-I-V-O-X dot org.

01:15:51.753 --> 01:15:53.433
This has been a TBLS3 production.

01:16:15.004 --> 01:16:18.044
That's L-I-B-R-I-V-O-X dot O-R-G.

01:16:19.344 --> 01:16:23.364
The Time Machine by H.G. Wells

01:16:24.524 --> 01:16:27.524
In another moment, we were standing face to face.

01:16:27.524 --> 01:16:31.264
I and this fragile thing out of futurity.

01:16:31.864 --> 01:16:35.464
He came straight up to me and laughed into my eyes.

01:16:35.904 --> 01:16:40.644
The absence from his bearing of any sign of fear struck me at once.

01:16:41.184 --> 01:16:44.484
Then he turned to the two others who were following him,

01:16:44.884 --> 01:16:49.144
and spoke to them in a strange and very sweet liquid tongue.

01:16:49.684 --> 01:16:56.744
There were others coming, and presently a little group of perhaps eight or ten of these exquisite creatures

01:16:56.744 --> 01:17:00.464
were about me. One of them addressed me.

01:17:00.464 --> 01:17:05.584
It came into my head, oddly enough, that my voice was too harsh and deep for them.

01:17:05.924 --> 01:17:10.224
So I shook my head, and pointing to my ears, shook it again.

01:17:10.584 --> 01:17:15.864
He came a step forward, hesitated, and then touched my hand.

01:17:16.204 --> 01:17:21.604
Then I felt the other soft little tentacles upon my back and shoulders.

01:17:22.024 --> 01:17:25.144
They wanted to make sure I was real.

01:17:25.144 --> 01:17:32.084
There was nothing in this at all alarming. Indeed, there was something in these pretty little people

01:17:32.084 --> 01:17:38.244
that inspired confidence, a graceful gentleness, a certain childlike ease.

01:17:38.824 --> 01:17:47.744
And besides, they looked so frail that I could fancy myself flinging the whole dozen of them about like nine pins.

01:17:48.044 --> 01:17:54.184
But I made a sudden motion to warn them when I saw their little pink hands filling at the Time Machine.

01:17:54.184 --> 01:18:00.444
Happily then, when it was not too late, I thought of a danger I had hitherto forgotten.

01:18:01.084 --> 01:18:08.304
And reaching over the bars of the Time Machine, I unscrewed the little levers that would set it in motion

01:18:08.304 --> 01:18:10.564
and put these in my pocket.

01:18:11.144 --> 01:18:15.304
Then I turned again to see what I could do in the way of communication.

01:18:16.364 --> 01:18:22.664
The people looking more nearly into their features, I saw some further peculiarities

01:18:22.664 --> 01:18:26.504
in their Dresden China type of prettiness.

01:18:26.744 --> 01:18:33.084
Their hair, which was uniformly curly, came to a sharp end at the neck and cheek.

01:18:33.624 --> 01:18:41.344
There was not the faintest suggestion of it on the face, and their ears were singularly minute.

01:18:41.724 --> 01:18:49.024
The mouths were small with bright red, rather thin lips, and the little chins ran to a point.

01:18:49.024 --> 01:18:54.984
The eyes were large and mild, and this may seem egotism on my part.

01:18:55.404 --> 01:19:01.704
I fancied even that there was a certain lack of the interest I might have expected in them.

01:19:02.064 --> 01:19:08.124
As they made no effort to communicate with me, but simply stood round me smiling and speaking

01:19:08.124 --> 01:19:12.704
in soft, cooing notes to each other, I began the conversation.

01:19:12.704 --> 01:19:20.304
I pointed to the Time Machine and to myself, then hesitating for a moment how to express time.

01:19:20.904 --> 01:19:22.324
I pointed to the sun.

01:19:22.704 --> 01:19:30.404
At once, a quite pretty little figure in cheered purple and white followed my gesture

01:19:30.404 --> 01:19:34.664
and then astonished me by imitating the sound of thunder.

01:19:35.484 --> 01:19:41.264
For a moment I was staggered, though the impart of his gestures was plain enough.

01:19:41.264 --> 01:19:44.384
The question had come into my mind abruptly.

01:19:44.944 --> 01:19:46.324
Were these creatures fools?

01:19:46.724 --> 01:19:49.204
You may hardly understand how it took me.

01:19:49.444 --> 01:19:56.064
You see, I had always anticipated that the people of the year eight hundred and two thousand odd

01:19:56.064 --> 01:20:00.724
would be incredibly in front of us in knowledge, art, everything.

01:20:01.284 --> 01:20:08.264
Then one of them suddenly asked me a question that showed him to be on the intellectual level

01:20:08.264 --> 01:20:11.124
of one of our five-year-old children.

01:20:11.404 --> 01:20:16.884
Asked me, in fact, if I had come from the sun in a thunderstorm.

01:20:17.764 --> 01:20:24.724
It let loose a judgment I had suspended upon their clothes, their frail light limbs and fragile features.

01:20:25.444 --> 01:20:29.284
A flow of disappointment rushed across my mind.

01:20:29.564 --> 01:20:32.944
For a moment I felt that I had built the Time Machine in vain.

01:20:32.944 --> 01:20:41.444
I nodded, pointed at the sun, and gave them such a vivid rendering of thunder clap as startled them.

01:20:41.864 --> 01:20:45.284
They all withdrew a pace or so and bowed.

01:20:45.624 --> 01:20:52.164
Then came one laughing towards me, carrying a chain of beautiful flowers altogether new to me,

01:20:52.564 --> 01:20:54.504
and put it about my neck.

01:20:54.504 --> 01:21:04.184
The idea was received with the melodious applause, and presently they were all running to and fro for flowers

01:21:04.184 --> 01:21:10.324
and laughingly flinging them upon me until I was almost smothered with blossom.

01:21:11.184 --> 01:21:18.844
You who have never seen the like can scarcely imagine what delicate and wonderful flowers

01:21:18.844 --> 01:21:21.804
countless years of culture had created.

01:21:21.804 --> 01:21:28.524
Then someone suggested that their playing should be exhibited in the nearest building,

01:21:28.924 --> 01:21:37.004
and so I was led past the sphinx of white marble which had seemed to watch me all the while

01:21:37.004 --> 01:21:44.684
with a smile at my astonishment towards a vast gray edifice of the fretted stone.

01:21:44.684 --> 01:21:54.844
As I went with them, the memory of my confidence, anticipation of a profound grave and intellectual posterity came

01:21:54.844 --> 01:21:57.424
with merriment to my mind.

01:21:58.024 --> 01:22:04.204
The buildings had a huge entry, and was altogether of the colossal dimensions.

01:22:04.684 --> 01:22:09.624
I was naturally most occupied with the growing crowd of little people,

01:22:09.624 --> 01:22:16.624
and with the big open ports that yawned before me, shadowy and mysterious,

01:22:17.104 --> 01:22:25.184
my general impression of the world I saw over their heads was a tangled waste of beautiful bushes and flowers.

01:22:25.964 --> 01:22:33.104
A long neglected and yet weedless garden I saw a number of tall spikes of strange white flowers

01:22:33.104 --> 01:22:37.564
measuring a foot perhaps across the spread of the waxen petals.

01:22:37.564 --> 01:22:42.924
They grew scattered as if wild among the vegetated shrubs,

01:22:43.324 --> 01:22:47.544
but as I say I did not examine them closely at this time.

01:22:47.944 --> 01:22:52.944
The time machine was left deserted on the turf among the rodendras.

01:22:53.424 --> 01:23:01.404
The arc of the doorway was richly carved, but naturally I did not observe the carving very narrowly,

01:23:01.404 --> 01:23:08.564
though I fancied I saw suggestions of old Phoenician decorations as I passed through,

01:23:08.644 --> 01:23:13.044
and it struck me that they were very badly broken and weather worn.

01:23:13.564 --> 01:23:18.324
Several more brightly clad people met me in the doorway, and so we entered.

01:23:18.804 --> 01:23:24.604
I dressed in the dingy 19th century garment, looking grotesque enough,

01:23:24.604 --> 01:23:32.604
garlanded with flowers and surrounded by an eddying mass of bright soft colored robes

01:23:32.604 --> 01:23:39.824
and shining white limbs in a melodious whirl of laughter and laughing speech.

01:23:41.064 --> 01:23:47.544
The big doorway opened into a proportionally great hall hung with brown.

01:23:47.544 --> 01:23:55.024
The roof was in shadow, and the windows, partially glazed with colored glass and partially unglazed,

01:23:55.404 --> 01:23:57.224
admitted a tempered light.

01:23:57.424 --> 01:24:05.844
The floor was made up of huge blocks of some very hard white metal, not plates nor slabs, blocks,

01:24:06.324 --> 01:24:12.724
and it was so much worn that I channeled along the more frequent ways.

01:24:13.544 --> 01:24:20.444
Traversely to the length were innumerable tables, more of slabs of polished stone,

01:24:20.844 --> 01:24:26.184
raised perhaps a foot from the floor, and upon these were heaps of fruits,

01:24:26.704 --> 01:24:36.364
some I recognized as a kind of hypertrenical redsberry and orange, but for the most part they were strange.

01:24:37.184 --> 01:24:41.724
Between the tables were scattered a great number of cushions.

01:24:41.724 --> 01:24:48.064
Upon these my conductors seated themselves, signing for me to do likewise.

01:24:48.504 --> 01:24:57.664
With a pretty absence of ceremony they began to eat the fruit with their hands, flinging peel and stalks,

01:24:57.664 --> 01:25:01.544
and so forth into the round openings in the sides of the tables.

01:25:02.204 --> 01:25:11.244
I was no loath to follow their example, for I felt thirsty and hungry as I did so I surveyed the hall at my leisure.

01:25:11.244 --> 01:25:16.664
And perhaps the thing that struck me most was its dilapidated look.

01:25:17.024 --> 01:25:23.304
The stained glass windows, which displayed only a geometrical pattern, were broken in many places,

01:25:23.684 --> 01:25:28.644
and the curtains that hung across the lower end were thick with dust,

01:25:28.944 --> 01:25:34.124
and it caught my eyes that the corner of the marble table near me was fractured.

01:25:34.124 --> 01:25:39.364
Nevertheless, the general effect was extremely rich and picturesque.

01:25:39.564 --> 01:25:49.544
There were perhaps a couple of hundred people dining in the hall, and most of them, seated as near to me as they could come,

01:25:50.024 --> 01:25:55.244
were watching me with interest, their little eyes shining over the fruit.

01:25:55.684 --> 01:26:02.784
They were eating, all were clad in the same soft and yet strong silky material.

01:26:02.784 --> 01:26:06.324
Fruit, by and by, was all their diet.

01:26:06.784 --> 01:26:16.784
These people of the remote future were strict vegetarians, and while I was with them, in spite of some carnal cravings,

01:26:17.344 --> 01:26:20.004
I had to be furgivorous also.

01:26:20.484 --> 01:26:28.864
Indeed, I found afterwards that horses, cattle, sheep, dogs had followed the ichthyosaurus into extinction.

01:26:28.864 --> 01:26:39.224
But the fruit were very delightful, one in particular that seemed to be in season all the time I was there.

01:26:39.484 --> 01:26:46.784
A flurry thing in a three-sided husk was especially good, and I made it my staple.

01:26:47.524 --> 01:26:57.234
At first, I was puzzled by all these strange fruit and by the strange flowers I saw, but later I began to perceive their import.

01:26:58.134 --> 01:27:04.154
However, I am telling you of my fruit dinner in the distant future now.

01:27:04.554 --> 01:27:14.314
So soon as my appetite was little checked, I demonstrated to make a resolute attempt to learn the speech of these new men of mine.

01:27:14.874 --> 01:27:17.754
Clearly, that was the next thing to do.

01:27:17.754 --> 01:27:29.874
The fruits seemed a convenient thing to begin upon, and holding one of these up, I began a series of interrogative sounds and gestures.

01:27:30.434 --> 01:27:35.534
I had some considerable difficulty in conveying my meaning.

01:27:36.014 --> 01:27:42.034
At first, my efforts met with a stare of surprise or inexhaustible laughter,

01:27:42.034 --> 01:27:49.554
but presently a fair-haired little creature seemed to grasp my intention and repeated a name.

01:27:49.974 --> 01:27:54.874
They had to chatter and explain the business at great length to each other.

01:27:55.374 --> 01:28:03.094
My first attempt to make these exquisite little sounds of their language caused an immense amount of amusement.

01:28:03.094 --> 01:28:14.834
However, I felt like a schoolmaster amidst children, and persisting and presently, I had a score of nouns and sentences at last at my command.

01:28:15.434 --> 01:28:22.094
And then I got to demonstrative pronouns and even the verb to eat.

01:28:22.734 --> 01:28:30.234
But it was slow work, and the little people soon tired and wanted to get away from my interrogations.

01:28:30.234 --> 01:28:38.254
So I determined, rather, of necessity to let them give their lessons in little doses.

01:28:38.714 --> 01:28:49.714
When they felt inclined, in very little doses, I found they were before long, for I never met people more indolent or more easily fatigued.

01:28:50.234 --> 01:28:56.734
A queer thing I soon discovered about my little hosts, and that was their lack of interest.

01:28:56.734 --> 01:29:09.954
They would come to me with eager cries of astonishment, like children, but like children, they would soon stop examining me and wander away after some other toy.

01:29:10.474 --> 01:29:13.654
The dinner and my conversational beginnings ended.

01:29:14.114 --> 01:29:20.854
I noted for the first time that almost all those who had surrounded me at first were gone.

01:29:20.854 --> 01:29:26.514
It is odd, too, how speedily I came to disregard these little people.

01:29:26.934 --> 01:29:31.094
I went out through the portal into the sunlit world again.

01:29:31.534 --> 01:29:41.154
As soon as my hunger was satisfied, I was continually meeting more of these men of the future, who would follow me a little distance,

01:29:41.154 --> 01:29:51.194
chatter and laugh about me, and having smiled and gestulated in a friendly way, leaving me again to my own devices.

01:29:52.054 --> 01:30:01.214
The calm of evening was upon the world as I emerged from the great hall, and the scene was lit by the warm glow of the setting sun.

01:30:01.874 --> 01:30:04.054
At first, things were very confusing.

01:30:04.574 --> 01:30:10.034
Everything was so entirely different from the world I had known, even the flowers.

01:30:10.034 --> 01:30:21.634
The big building I had left was situated on the slope of a broad river valley, but the Thames had shifted perhaps a mile from its present position.

01:30:22.214 --> 01:30:38.204
I resolved to mount to the summit of a crest, perhaps a mile and a half away, for which I could get a wider view of this hour planet in the year 802,701 AD.

01:30:38.204 --> 01:30:45.564
For that, I had explained was the date the little dials of my machine recorded.

01:30:45.984 --> 01:30:57.024
As I walked, I was watching for every impression that could possibly help to explain the condition of ruinous splendor in which I found the world.

01:30:57.024 --> 01:31:08.524
For ruinous it was. A little way up the hill, for instance, was a great heap of granite, pounded together by masses of aluminum,

01:31:08.524 --> 01:31:20.624
a vast labyrinth of perceptuous walls, and crumpled heaps amidst which were thick heaps of very beautiful pagoda-like plants,

01:31:20.624 --> 01:31:29.864
nettle possibly, but wonderfully tinted with brown about the leaves, and incapable of stinging.

01:31:30.224 --> 01:31:38.564
It was evidently the derelict remains of some vast structure to what end-built I could not determine.

01:31:39.064 --> 01:31:49.884
It was here that I was destined, at a later date, to have a very strange experience, the first intimation of a still stranger discovery.

01:31:49.884 --> 01:31:52.844
But of that, I will speak in its proper place.

01:31:53.704 --> 01:32:04.144
Looking round with a sudden thought from a terrace on which I rested for a while, I realized that there was no small houses to be seen.

01:32:04.624 --> 01:32:09.824
Apparently, the single house, and possibly even the household, had vanished.

01:32:09.824 --> 01:32:24.224
Here and there among the greenery were place-like buildings, but the house and the cottage, which formed such characteristic features of our own English landscape, had disappeared.

01:32:26.204 --> 01:32:32.004
Communism, said I to myself, and on the hills of that came another thought.

01:32:32.004 --> 01:32:37.024
I looked at that half-dozen little figures that were following me.

01:32:37.164 --> 01:32:51.324
Then, in a flash, I perceived that all had the same form of costume, the same soft, hairless visage, and the same garish, rotundity of limb.

01:32:51.824 --> 01:32:59.404
It may seem strange, perhaps, that I had not noticed this before, but everything was so strange.

01:32:59.404 --> 01:33:11.124
Now I saw the fact plainly enough, in costume and in all the differences of texture and bearing, that now mark off the sexes from each other.

01:33:11.444 --> 01:33:18.904
These people of the future were alike, and the children seemed to my eyes to be but the miniatures of their parents.

01:33:18.904 --> 01:33:32.664
I judged, then, that the children of that time were extremely precious physically at least, and I found, afterwards, abundant verification of my opinion.

01:33:34.504 --> 01:33:51.264
Seeing the ease and security in which these people were living, I felt that this close resembled of the sexes was, after all, what one would expect, for the strength of a man and the softness of a woman.

01:33:51.264 --> 01:34:13.564
The instuation of the family and the defenciations of occupations are more militant necessities of an age of physical force, where population is balanced and abundant much childbearing becomes an evil rather than a blessing to the state.

01:34:13.564 --> 01:34:34.964
Where violence comes, but rarely an offspring, are secure. There is less necessity, indeed. There is no necessity for an efficient family, and the specialization of the sexes, where reference to their children's needs disappears.

01:34:34.964 --> 01:34:54.624
We see some beginning of this even in our own time, and in this future age, it was complete. This, I must remind you, was my speculation at the time. Later, I was appreciate how far it fell short of the reality.

01:34:54.624 --> 01:35:15.834
While I was musing upon these things, my attention was attracted by a pretty little structure, like a well under a copula. I thought, in a transitory way, of the oddness of wells still existing, and then resumed the thread of my speculations.

01:35:15.834 --> 01:35:32.334
There were no large buildings towards the top of the hill, and as my walking powers were evidently miraculous, I was presently left alone for the first time with a strange sense of freedom and adventure.

01:35:32.334 --> 01:35:56.394
I pushed on up to the crest. There I found a seat of some yellow metal that I did not recognize, corroded in places with a kind of pinkish rust, and half smoothed in soft mass. The armrest cast and filled into the resemblance of griffon's heads.

01:35:56.394 --> 01:36:09.634
I sat down on it, and I surveyed the broad view of our old world under the sunset of that long day. It was as sweet and fair a view as I have ever seen.

01:36:09.634 --> 01:36:29.594
The sun had already gone below the horizon, and the west was flaming gold, touched with some horizontal bars of purple and crimson. Below was the valley of thames, in which the river lay like a band of burnished steel.

01:36:29.594 --> 01:36:53.884
I have already spoken of the great places dotted about among the vegetated greenery, some in ruins and some still occupied. Here and there rose a white or silvery figure in the waste gardens of the earth. Here and there came the sharp vertical line of some cupula or obelisk.

01:36:53.884 --> 01:37:05.704
There were no hedges, no signs of propertary rights, no evidence of agriculture. The whole earth had become a garden.

01:37:05.704 --> 01:37:26.424
So watching, I began to put my interpretation upon the things I had seen, and as it shaped itself to me that evening, my interpretation was something in this way. Afterwards I found I had got only a half truth, or only a glimpse of one facet of the truth.

01:37:26.424 --> 01:37:44.304
It seemed to me that I had happened upon humanity, upon the wane. The ready sunset set me thinking of the sunset of mankind. For the first time I began to realize an odd consequence of the social effort in which we are at present engaged.

01:37:44.304 --> 01:38:08.884
And yet come to think it is a logical consequence enough. Strength is the outcome of need. Security sets a premium on feebleness. The work of amelioration, the conditions of life, the true civilizing process that makes life more and more secure had gone steadily onto a climax.

01:38:08.884 --> 01:38:25.624
One triumph of a united humanity over nature had followed another. Things that are now mere dreams had become projects deliberately put in hands and carried forward, and the harvest was what I saw.

01:38:25.624 --> 01:38:47.884
After all, the sanitation and the agriculture of today are still in the rudimentary stage. The science of our time has attacked but a little department of the field of human disease, but even so it spreads its operations very steadily and persistently.

01:38:47.884 --> 01:39:05.464
Our agriculture and horticulture destroy a weed just here and there, and cultivate perhaps a score or so of wholesome plants, leaving the greater number to fight out a balance as they can.

01:39:05.464 --> 01:39:30.144
We improve our favorite plants and animals, and how few they are. Gradually, by selective breeding now, a new and better peach, now a speedless grape, now a sweeter and larger flower, now a more convenient breed of cattle.

01:39:30.144 --> 01:39:44.604
We improve them gradually, because our ideals are vague and tentative, and our knowledge is very limited, because nature, too, is shy and slow in our clumsy hands.

01:39:44.604 --> 01:40:04.064
Someday all this will be better organized, and still better. That is the drift of the current in spite of the eddies. The whole world will be intelligent, educated, and cooperating. Things will move faster and faster towards the subjection of nature.

01:40:04.064 --> 01:40:14.264
In the end, wisely and carefully, we shall readjust the balance of animal and vegetable life to suit our human needs.

01:40:14.264 --> 01:40:25.884
This adjustment, I say, must have been done and done well. Done, indeed, for all time, in the space of time across which my machine had leaped.

01:40:25.884 --> 01:40:47.244
The air was free from gnats, the earth from weeds or fungi. Everywhere were fruits and sweet and delightful flowers. Brilliant butterflies flew hither and thither. The idea of preventive medicine was attained. Diseases had been stamped out.

01:40:47.244 --> 01:41:05.004
I saw no evidence of any contagious diseases during all my stay, and I shall have to tell you later that even the process of purification and decay had been profoundly affected by these changes.

01:41:05.004 --> 01:41:20.184
Social triumphs, too, had been affected. I saw mankind housed in splendid shelters, gloriously closed, and, as yet, I had found them engaged in no toil.

01:41:20.184 --> 01:41:46.404
There were no signs of struggle, neither social nor economical struggle. The shop, the advertisement, traffic, all the commerce which constitutes the body of our world was gone. It was natural on that golden evening that I should jump at the idea of a social paradise.

01:41:46.404 --> 01:42:03.444
The difficulty of increasing population had been met, I guessed, and population had ceased to increase. But with this change in condition comes inevitably adaptation to the change.

01:42:03.444 --> 01:42:33.424
What, unless biological science is a mass of errors, is the cause of human intelligence and vigor, hardship and freedom, conditions under which the active, strong, and subtle survive, and the weaker go to the wall, conditions that put a premium upon the loyal alliance of capable men upon self-resistant patients.

01:42:33.444 --> 01:42:57.084
And decision, and the institution of the family, and the emotions that arise therein, the fierce jealousy, the tenderness for offspring, parental self-devotion, all found their justification and support in the imminent dangers of the young.

01:42:57.084 --> 01:43:25.204
Now, where are these imminent dangers? There is a sentiment arising, and it will grow again, convule, jealousy against fierce maternity, against passion of all sorts, unnecessary things now, and things that make us uncomfortable, savage, survivors, dissenters in a refined and pleasant life.

01:43:25.204 --> 01:43:41.424
I thought of the cycle, slightness of the people, their lack of intelligence, and those big, abundant ruins, and it strengthened my belief in a perfect conquest of nature.

01:43:41.424 --> 01:44:00.104
For after the battle comes quiet. Humanity had been strong, energetic, and intelligent, and had used all its abundant vitality to alter the conditions under which it lived.

01:44:00.104 --> 01:44:19.424
And now came the reaction of the altered conditions. Under the new conditions of perfect comfort and security, that restless energy, that with us is strength, would become weakness.

01:44:19.424 --> 01:44:37.124
Even in our own time, certain tendencies and desires, once necessary to survival, are a constant source of failure, physical courage, and the love of battle.

01:44:37.124 --> 01:44:55.324
For instance, our no great help may even be hindrances to a civilized man, and in a state of physical balance and security power, intelligence as well as physical, would be out of place.

01:44:55.324 --> 01:45:14.184
For countless years I judged there had been no danger of war or solitary violence, no danger from wild beasts, nor wasting disease to require strength of constitution, no need of toil.

01:45:14.184 --> 01:45:36.264
For such a life, what we should call the weak, are used as well equipped as the strong, are indeed no longer weak. Better equipped indeed they are, for the strong would be fretted by an energy for which there was no outlet.

01:45:36.264 --> 01:45:57.904
No doubt the exquisite beauty of the buildings I saw was the outcome of the last surging of the now purposeless energy of mankind before it settled down into perfect harmony with the conditions under which it lived.

01:45:57.904 --> 01:46:17.164
The flourish of that triumph which began the last great peace this has ever been the fate of energy and security it takes to art and to erraticism, and then came linger and decay.

01:46:17.164 --> 01:46:38.124
Even this artistic impetus would at least die away had almost died in the time I saw. To adorn themselves with flowers, to dance, to sing in the sunlight, so much was left of the artistic spirit and no more.

01:46:38.124 --> 01:46:58.504
Even that would fade in the end into a contended inactivity. We are kept keen on the grindstone of pain and necessity, and it seemed to me that here was the hateful grindstone broken at last.

01:46:58.504 --> 01:47:25.944
As I stood there in the gathering dark, I thought that in this simple explanation I had mastered the problem of the world, mastered the whole secret of these delicious people, possibly the checks they had devised for the increase of population had succeeded too well and their numbers had rather diminished.

01:47:25.944 --> 01:47:39.044
Then kept stationary, that would account for the abundant ruins, very simple was my explanation, and plausible enough as most wrong theories are.

01:48:10.575 --> 01:48:15.915
As I stood there musing over this too perfect

01:48:15.915 --> 01:48:22.155
triumph of man, the full moon, yellow and gibbous, came up out of an overflow of silver

01:48:22.155 --> 01:48:28.635
light in the northeast. The bright little figures ceased to move about below. A noiseless

01:48:28.635 --> 01:48:34.395
owl flitted by, and I shivered with the chill of the night. I determined to descend and

01:48:34.395 --> 01:48:39.975
find where I could sleep. I looked for the building I knew. Then my eye travelled along

01:48:39.975 --> 01:48:45.415
the figure of the white sphinx upon the pedestal of bronze, growing distinct as the light of

01:48:45.415 --> 01:48:50.515
the rising moon grew brighter. I could see the silver birch against it. There was the

01:48:50.515 --> 01:48:55.175
tangle of rhododendron bushes, black in the pale light, and there was the little lawn.

01:48:55.835 --> 01:49:00.535
I looked at the lawn again. A queer doubt chilled my complacency.

01:49:01.055 --> 01:49:08.575
No, said I stoutly to myself, that was not the lawn. But it was the lawn, for the white

01:49:08.575 --> 01:49:14.095
leprous face of the sphinx was towards it. Can you imagine what I felt as this conviction

01:49:14.095 --> 01:49:19.415
came home to me? But you cannot. The time machine was gone.

01:49:20.275 --> 01:49:25.895
At once, like a lash across the face, came the possibility of losing my own age, of being

01:49:25.895 --> 01:49:31.635
left helpless in this strange new world. The bare thought of it was an actual physical

01:49:31.635 --> 01:49:36.655
sensation. I could feel it grip me at the throat and stop my breathing. In another moment

01:49:36.655 --> 01:49:42.435
I was in a passion of fear and running with great leaping strides down the slope. Once

01:49:42.435 --> 01:49:47.435
I fell headlong and cut my face, I lost no time in stanching the blood, but jumped up

01:49:47.435 --> 01:49:50.735
and ran on, with a warm trickle down my cheek and chin.

01:49:51.195 --> 01:49:55.655
All the time I ran, I was saying to myself, they may have moved it a little, pushed it

01:49:55.655 --> 01:50:00.955
under the bushes out of the way. Nevertheless I ran with all my might, all the time, with

01:50:00.955 --> 01:50:06.355
the certainty that sometimes comes with excessive dread. I knew that such assurance was folly,

01:50:06.355 --> 01:50:12.075
knew instinctively that the machine was removed out of my reach. My breath came with pain.

01:50:12.515 --> 01:50:16.575
I suppose I covered the whole distance from the hillcrest to the little lawn two miles

01:50:16.575 --> 01:50:22.795
perhaps in ten minutes, and I am not a young man. I cursed aloud as I ran, at my confident

01:50:22.795 --> 01:50:29.035
folly in leaving the machine, wasting a good breath thereby. I cried aloud, and none answered.

01:50:29.375 --> 01:50:33.215
Not a creature seemed to be stirring in that moonlit world.

01:50:33.795 --> 01:50:40.075
When I reached the lawn, my worst fears were realized. Not a trace of the thing was to

01:50:40.075 --> 01:50:45.415
be seen. I felt faint and cold when I faced the empty space among the black tangle of

01:50:45.415 --> 01:50:50.975
bushes. I ran round it furiously, as if the thing might be hidden in a corner, and then

01:50:50.975 --> 01:50:57.935
stopped abruptly, with my hands clutching my hair. Above me towered the sphinx, upon

01:50:57.935 --> 01:51:04.755
the bronze pedestal, white, shining, leprous, in the light of the rising moon. It seemed

01:51:04.755 --> 01:51:10.955
to smile in mockery of my dismay. I might have consoled myself by imagining the little

01:51:10.955 --> 01:51:15.635
people had put the mechanism in some shelter for me, had I not felt assured of their physical

01:51:15.635 --> 01:51:22.785
and intellectual inadequacy. That is what dismayed me. The sense of some hitherto unsuspected

01:51:23.325 --> 01:51:29.785
power, through whose intervention my invention had vanished. Yet for one thing I felt assured,

01:51:30.285 --> 01:51:35.925
unless some other age had produced its exact duplicate, the machine could not have moved

01:51:35.925 --> 01:51:41.385
in time. The attachment of the levers, I will show you the method later, prevented anyone

01:51:41.385 --> 01:51:47.445
from tampering with it in that way when they were removed. It had moved, and was hid only

01:51:47.445 --> 01:51:51.245
in space. But then, where could it be?

01:51:52.105 --> 01:51:57.245
I think I must have had a kind of a frenzy. I remember running violently in and out among

01:51:57.245 --> 01:52:02.405
the moonlit bushes all round the sphinx, and startling some white animal that in the dim

01:52:02.405 --> 01:52:07.645
light I took for a small deer. I remember, too, late that night beating the bushes with

01:52:07.645 --> 01:52:14.265
my clenched fist until my knuckles were gashed and bleeding from the broken twigs. Then sobbing

01:52:14.265 --> 01:52:19.405
and raving in my anguish of mind, I went down to the great building of stone. The big

01:52:19.405 --> 01:52:25.745
hall was dark, silent, and deserted. I slipped on the uneven floor and fell over one of the

01:52:25.745 --> 01:52:32.125
malachite tables, almost breaking my shin. I lit a match and went on past the dusty curtains

01:52:32.125 --> 01:52:37.765
of which I have told you. There I found a second great hall covered with cushions upon

01:52:37.765 --> 01:52:42.545
which perhaps a score or so of the little people were sleeping. I have no doubt they

01:52:42.545 --> 01:52:47.305
found my second appearance strange enough, coming quite suddenly out of the quiet darkness

01:52:47.305 --> 01:52:52.605
with inarticulate noises and the sputter and flair of a match, for they had forgotten about

01:52:52.605 --> 01:52:58.185
matches. Where is my time machine? I began bawling like an angry child, laying hands

01:52:58.185 --> 01:53:03.705
upon them and shaking them up together. It must have been very queer to them. Some laughed.

01:53:03.885 --> 01:53:09.025
Most of them looked sorely frightened. When I saw them standing round me, it came into

01:53:09.025 --> 01:53:13.785
my head that I was doing as foolish a thing as it was possible for me to do under the

01:53:13.785 --> 01:53:18.965
circumstances in trying to revive the sensation of fear, for reasoning from their daylight

01:53:18.965 --> 01:53:22.125
behavior, I thought that fear must be forgotten.

01:53:23.365 --> 01:53:28.045
Abruptly I dashed down the match and, knocking one of the people over in my course, went

01:53:28.045 --> 01:53:33.885
blundering across the big dining hall again, out under the moonlight. I heard cries of

01:53:33.885 --> 01:53:38.865
terror and their little feet running and stumbling this way and that. I do not remember all I

01:53:38.865 --> 01:53:44.265
did as the moon crept up in the sky. I suppose it was the unexpected nature of my loss that

01:53:44.265 --> 01:53:50.445
maddened me. I felt hopelessly cut off from my own kind, a strange animal in an unknown

01:53:50.445 --> 01:53:56.865
world. I must have raved to and fro, screaming and crying upon God and fate. I have a memory

01:53:56.865 --> 01:54:03.185
of horrible fatigue as the long night of despair wore away, of looking in this impossible place

01:54:03.185 --> 01:54:09.065
and that, of groping among moonlit ruins and touching strange creatures in the black shadows,

01:54:09.465 --> 01:54:16.045
at last of lying on the ground near the sphinx and weeping with absolute wretchedness. I

01:54:16.045 --> 01:54:22.305
had nothing left but misery. Then I slept, and when I woke again it was full day and

01:54:22.305 --> 01:54:27.805
a couple of sparrows were hopping round me on the turf within reach of my arm. I sat

01:54:27.805 --> 01:54:32.805
up in the freshness of the morning, trying to remember how I had got there and why I

01:54:32.805 --> 01:54:38.565
had such a profound sense of desertion and despair. Then things came clear in my mind.

01:54:38.765 --> 01:54:44.765
With a plain reasonable daylight I could look my circumstances fairly in the face. I saw

01:54:44.765 --> 01:54:50.045
the wild folly of my frenzy overnight and I could reason with myself. Suppose the worst,

01:54:50.225 --> 01:54:56.645
I said. Suppose the machine altogether lost, perhaps destroyed. It behooves me to be calm

01:54:56.645 --> 01:55:01.485
and patient, to learn the way of the people, to get a clear idea of the method of my loss

01:55:01.485 --> 01:55:06.845
and the means of getting materials and tools, so that in the end, perhaps, I may make another.

01:55:07.085 --> 01:55:13.925
That would be my only hope, perhaps, but better than despair. And after all, it was a beautiful

01:55:13.925 --> 01:55:20.845
and curious world. But probably the machine had only been taken away. Still I must be

01:55:20.845 --> 01:55:27.205
calm and patient, find its hiding place, and recover it by force or cunning. And with that

01:55:27.205 --> 01:55:32.845
I scrambled to my feet and looked about me, wondering where I could bathe. I felt weary,

01:55:33.325 --> 01:55:39.105
stiff and travel-soiled. The freshness of the morning made me desire an equal freshness.

01:55:39.245 --> 01:55:44.365
I had exhausted my emotion. Indeed, as I went about my business, I found myself wondering

01:55:44.365 --> 01:55:49.285
at my intense excitement overnight. I made a careful examination of the ground about

01:55:49.285 --> 01:55:55.025
the little lawn. I wasted some time in futile questionings, conveyed as well as I was able

01:55:55.025 --> 01:55:59.865
to such of the little people as came by. They all failed to understand my gestures.

01:56:00.465 --> 01:56:05.985
Some were simply stolid. Some thought it was a jest and laughed at me. I had the hardest

01:56:05.985 --> 01:56:12.425
task in the world to keep my hands off their pretty laughing faces. It was a foolish impulse,

01:56:12.465 --> 01:56:18.505
but the devil begotten of fear and blind anger was ill-curbed and still eager to take advantage

01:56:18.505 --> 01:56:24.625
of my perplexity. The turf gave better counsel. I found a groove ripped in it, about midway

01:56:24.625 --> 01:56:29.385
between the pedestal of the sphinx and the marks of my feet, where, on arrival, I had

01:56:29.385 --> 01:56:34.765
struggled with the overturned machine. There were other signs of removal about, with queer

01:56:34.765 --> 01:56:41.165
narrow footprints like those I could imagine made by a sloth. This directed my closer attention

01:56:41.165 --> 01:56:47.165
to the pedestal. It was, as I think I have said, of bronze. But it was not a mere block,

01:56:47.305 --> 01:56:53.545
but highly decorated with deep-framed panels on either side. I went and wrapped at these.

01:56:53.885 --> 01:57:00.205
The pedestal was hollow. Examining the panels with care, I found them discontinuous with

01:57:00.205 --> 01:57:05.905
the frames. There were no handles or keyholes, but possibly the panels, if they were doors,

01:57:05.965 --> 01:57:12.245
as I supposed, opened from within. One thing was clear enough in my mind. It took no very

01:57:12.245 --> 01:57:18.525
great mental effort to infer that my time-machine was inside that pedestal, but how it got there

01:57:18.525 --> 01:57:24.405
was a different problem. I saw the heads of two orange-clad people coming through the

01:57:24.405 --> 01:57:30.285
bushes and under some blossom-covered apple trees towards me. I turned smiling to them

01:57:30.285 --> 01:57:35.925
and beckoned them to me. They came, and then, pointing to the bronze pedestal, I tried

01:57:35.925 --> 01:57:42.125
to intimate my wish to open it. But at my first gesture towards this, they behaved very

01:57:42.125 --> 01:57:47.845
oddly. I don't know how to convey their expression to you. Suppose you were to use a grossly

01:57:47.845 --> 01:57:53.365
improper gesture to a delicate-minded woman. It is how she would look. They went off as

01:57:53.365 --> 01:57:59.405
if they had received the last possible insult. I tried a sweet-looking little chap in white

01:57:59.405 --> 01:58:05.325
next, with exactly the same result. Somehow his manner made me feel ashamed of myself.

01:58:05.985 --> 01:58:11.505
But as you know, I wanted the time-machine, and I tried him once more. As he turned off

01:58:11.505 --> 01:58:16.485
like the others, my temper got the better of me. In three strides I was after him, had

01:58:16.485 --> 01:58:21.905
him by the loose part of his robe round the neck, and began dragging him towards the sphinx.

01:58:22.605 --> 01:58:29.085
Then I saw the horror and repugnance of his face, and all of a sudden I let him go. But

01:58:29.085 --> 01:58:35.225
I was not beaten yet. I banged with my fist at the bronze panels. I thought I heard something

01:58:35.225 --> 01:58:40.845
stir inside. To be explicit, I thought I heard a sound like a chuckle. But I must have been

01:58:40.845 --> 01:58:46.125
mistaken. Then I got a big pebble from the river, and came and hammered till I had flattened

01:58:46.125 --> 01:58:51.605
a coil in the decorations, and the verdigris came off in powdery flakes. The delicate

01:58:51.605 --> 01:58:56.345
little people must have heard me hammering in gusty outbreaks a mile away on either hand,

01:58:56.605 --> 01:59:01.845
but nothing came of it. I saw a crowd of them upon the slopes, looking furtively at me.

01:59:02.185 --> 01:59:09.305
At last, hot and tired, I sat down to watch the place. But I was too restless to watch

01:59:09.305 --> 01:59:15.605
long. I am too occidental for a long vigil. I could work at a problem for years, but to

01:59:15.605 --> 01:59:22.085
wait inactive for twenty-four hours—that is another matter. I got up after a time,

01:59:22.265 --> 01:59:25.645
and began walking aimlessly through the bushes towards the hill again.

01:59:26.585 --> 01:59:31.465
Patience, I said to myself. If you want your machine again, you must leave that sphinx

01:59:31.465 --> 01:59:36.545
alone. If they mean to take your machine away, it's little good you're wrecking their bronze

01:59:36.545 --> 01:59:42.425
panels. And if they don't, you will get it back as soon as you can ask for it. To sit

01:59:42.425 --> 01:59:49.265
among all those unknown things before a puzzle like that is hopeless. That way lies monomania.

01:59:49.605 --> 01:59:55.825
Face this world. Learn its ways. Watch it. Be careful of two hasty guesses at its meaning.

01:59:56.285 --> 01:59:59.565
In the end, you will find clues to it all.

01:59:59.865 --> 02:00:04.825
Then suddenly the humor of the situation came into my mind, the thought of the years I had

02:00:04.825 --> 02:00:10.385
spent in study and toil to get into the future age, and now my passion of anxiety to get

02:00:10.385 --> 02:00:15.705
out of it. I had made myself the most complicated and the most hopeless trap that ever a man

02:00:15.705 --> 02:00:22.185
devised. Although it was at my own expense, I could not help myself. I laughed aloud.

02:00:23.305 --> 02:00:29.285
Going through the big palace, it seemed to me that the little people avoided me. It may

02:00:29.285 --> 02:00:34.145
have been my fancy, or it may have had something to do with my hammering at the gates of bronze,

02:00:34.145 --> 02:00:40.425
yet I felt tolerably sure of the avoidance. I was careful, however, to show no concern

02:00:40.425 --> 02:00:45.705
and to abstain from any pursuit of them, and in the course of a day or two things got back

02:00:45.705 --> 02:00:50.485
to the old footing. I made what progress I could in the language, and in addition I pushed

02:00:50.485 --> 02:00:57.105
my explorations here and there. Either I missed some subtle point or their language was excessively

02:00:57.105 --> 02:01:03.725
simple. Almost exclusively composed of concrete substantives and verbs, there seemed to be

02:01:03.725 --> 02:01:09.885
few, if any, abstract terms or little use of figurative language. Their sentences were

02:01:09.885 --> 02:01:15.965
usually simple and of two words, and I failed to convey or understand any but the simplest

02:01:15.965 --> 02:01:21.645
propositions. I determined to put the thought of my time-machine and the mystery of the

02:01:21.645 --> 02:01:27.905
bronze doors under the sphinx as much as possible in a corner of memory, until my growing knowledge

02:01:27.905 --> 02:01:33.185
would lead me back to them in a natural way. Yet a certain feeling, you may understand,

02:01:33.185 --> 02:01:37.665
tethered me in a circle of a few miles round the point of my arrival.

02:01:38.665 --> 02:01:43.845
So far as I could see, all the world displayed the same exuberant richness as the Thames

02:01:43.845 --> 02:01:50.245
valley. From every hill I climbed I saw the same abundance of splendid buildings, endlessly

02:01:50.245 --> 02:01:56.345
varied in material and style, the same clustering thickets of evergreens, the same blossom-laden

02:01:56.345 --> 02:02:02.545
trees and tree ferns. Here and there water shone like silver, and beyond, the land rose

02:02:02.545 --> 02:02:09.645
into blue undulating hills, and so faded into the serenity of the sky. A peculiar feature

02:02:09.645 --> 02:02:15.025
which presently attracted my attention was the presence of certain circular wells, several

02:02:15.025 --> 02:02:21.185
as it seemed to me of very great depth. One lay by the path up the hill, which I had followed

02:02:21.185 --> 02:02:26.425
during my first walk. Like the others it was rimmed with bronze, curiously wrought and

02:02:26.425 --> 02:02:31.845
protected by a little cupola from the rain. Sitting by the side of these wells and peering

02:02:31.845 --> 02:02:38.645
down into the shafted darkness, I could see no gleam of water, nor could I start any reflection

02:02:38.645 --> 02:02:45.845
with a lighted match. But in all of them I heard a certain sound, a thud, thud, thud,

02:02:46.485 --> 02:02:51.845
like the beating of some big engine. And I discovered from the flaring of my matches

02:02:51.845 --> 02:02:58.005
that a steady current of air set down the shafts. Further, I threw a scrap of paper

02:02:58.005 --> 02:03:04.405
into the throat of one, and instead of fluttering slowly down, it was at once sucked swiftly

02:03:04.405 --> 02:03:10.645
out of sight. After a time, too, I came to connect these wells with tall towers standing

02:03:10.645 --> 02:03:15.745
here and there upon the slopes, for above them there was often just a flicker in the

02:03:15.745 --> 02:03:21.765
air as one sees on a hot day above a sun-scorched beach. Putting things together, I reached

02:03:21.765 --> 02:03:27.905
a strong suggestion of an extensive system of subterranean ventilation, whose true import

02:03:27.905 --> 02:03:33.565
was difficult to imagine. I was at first inclined to associate it with the sanitary

02:03:33.565 --> 02:03:38.725
apparatus of these people. It was an obvious conclusion, but it was absolutely wrong.

02:03:39.465 --> 02:03:44.725
And here I must admit that I learned very little of drains and bells and modes of conveyance

02:03:44.725 --> 02:03:49.805
and the like conveniences during my time in this real future. In some of these visions

02:03:49.805 --> 02:03:55.465
of utopias and coming times which I have read, there is a vast amount of detail about building

02:03:55.465 --> 02:04:00.325
and social arrangements and so forth. But while such details are easy enough to obtain

02:04:00.325 --> 02:04:05.305
when the whole world is contained in one's imagination, they are altogether inaccessible

02:04:05.305 --> 02:04:11.465
to a real traveler amid such realities as I found here. Conceive the tale of London,

02:04:11.745 --> 02:04:17.605
which a negro fresh from Central Africa would take back to his tribe. What would he know

02:04:17.605 --> 02:04:23.025
of railway companies, of social movements, of telephone and telegraph wires, of the parcels

02:04:23.025 --> 02:04:28.005
of delivery company and postal orders and the like? Yet we at least should be willing

02:04:28.005 --> 02:04:33.585
enough to explain these things to him, and even of what he knew, how much could he make

02:04:33.585 --> 02:04:39.825
his untravelled friend either apprehend or believe? Then think how narrow the gap between

02:04:39.825 --> 02:04:45.305
a negro and a white man of our own times, and how wide the interval between myself and

02:04:45.305 --> 02:04:50.785
these of the Golden Age. I was sensible of much, which was unseen and which contributed

02:04:50.785 --> 02:04:56.825
to my comfort but save for a general impression of automatic organization. I fear I can convey

02:04:56.825 --> 02:05:01.705
very little of the difference to your mind. In the matter of Sepulchre, for instance,

02:05:01.765 --> 02:05:07.045
I could see no signs of crematoria nor anything suggestive of tombs, but it occurred to me

02:05:07.045 --> 02:05:12.445
that possibly there might be cemeteries or crematoria somewhere beyond the range of my

02:05:12.445 --> 02:05:18.685
explorings. This again was a question I deliberately put to myself, and my curiosity was at first

02:05:18.685 --> 02:05:23.745
entirely defeated upon the point. The thing puzzled me, and I was led to make a further

02:05:23.745 --> 02:05:30.625
remark which puzzled me still more, that aged and infirm among this people there were none.

02:05:31.265 --> 02:05:36.505
I must confess that my satisfaction with my first theories of an automatic civilization

02:05:36.505 --> 02:05:43.025
and a decadent humanity did not long endure, yet I could think of no other. Let me put

02:05:43.025 --> 02:05:48.785
my difficulties. The several big palaces I had explored were mere living places, great

02:05:48.785 --> 02:05:54.305
dining halls, and sleeping apartments. I could find no machinery, no appliances of

02:05:54.305 --> 02:06:00.345
any kind, yet these people were clothed in pleasant fabrics that must at times need renewal,

02:06:00.605 --> 02:06:07.105
and their sandals, though undecorated, were fairly complex specimens of metalwork. Somehow

02:06:07.105 --> 02:06:13.165
such things must be made, and the little people displayed no vestige of a creative tendency.

02:06:13.465 --> 02:06:19.165
There were no shops, no workshops, no sign of importations among them. They spent all

02:06:19.165 --> 02:06:24.145
their time in playing gently, in bathing in the river, in making love in a half- playful

02:06:24.145 --> 02:06:31.585
fashion, in eating fruit and sleeping. I could not see how things were kept going. Then again

02:06:31.585 --> 02:06:37.685
about the time machine. Something. I knew not what had taken it into the hollow pedestal

02:06:37.685 --> 02:06:44.585
of the white sphinx. Why? For the life of me I could not imagine. Those waterless wells

02:06:44.585 --> 02:06:52.285
too, those flickering pillars. I felt I lacked a clue. I felt, how shall I put it, suppose

02:06:52.285 --> 02:06:58.245
you found an inscription with sentences here and there in excellent plain English, and

02:06:58.245 --> 02:07:04.185
perplated therewith others made up of words, of letters even, absolutely unknown to you.

02:07:04.525 --> 02:07:13.085
Well on the third day of my visit, that was how the world of 802,701 presented itself

02:07:13.085 --> 02:07:20.045
to me. That day too I made a friend of a sort. It happened that as I was watching some of

02:07:20.045 --> 02:07:24.685
the little people bathing in a shallow, one of them was seized with a cramp and began

02:07:24.685 --> 02:07:30.165
drifting downstream. The main current ran rather swiftly, but not too strongly for even

02:07:30.165 --> 02:07:35.685
a moderate swimmer. It will give you an idea, therefore, of the strange deficiency in these

02:07:35.685 --> 02:07:41.385
creatures when I tell you that none made the slightest attempt to rescue the weakly crying

02:07:41.385 --> 02:07:46.925
little thing which was drowning before their eyes. When I realized this, I hurriedly slipped

02:07:46.925 --> 02:07:52.945
off my clothes and wading in at a point lower down, I caught the poor mite and drew her

02:07:52.945 --> 02:07:58.805
safe to land. A little rubbing of the limbs soon brought her round, and I had the satisfaction

02:07:58.805 --> 02:08:04.145
of seeing she was all right before I left her. I had got to such a low estimate of her

02:08:04.145 --> 02:08:10.885
kind that I did not expect any gratitude from her. In that, however, I was wrong.

02:08:11.585 --> 02:08:16.645
This happened in the morning. In the afternoon I met my little woman, as I believe it was,

02:08:16.965 --> 02:08:21.765
as I was returning towards my centre from an exploration, and she received me with cries

02:08:21.765 --> 02:08:28.265
of delight and presented me with a big garland of flowers, evidently made for me and me alone.

02:08:29.265 --> 02:08:36.285
The thing took my imagination. Very possibly, I had been feeling desolate. At any rate,

02:08:36.525 --> 02:08:41.465
I did my best to display my appreciation of the gift. We were soon seated together in

02:08:41.465 --> 02:08:48.365
a little stone arbour, engaged in conversation, chiefly of smiles. The creature's friendliness

02:08:48.365 --> 02:08:53.925
affected me exactly as a child's might have done. We passed each other flowers, and she

02:08:53.925 --> 02:09:01.265
kissed my hands. I did the same to hers. Then I tried talk, and found that her name was

02:09:01.265 --> 02:09:06.425
Weena, which, though I don't know what it meant, somehow seemed appropriate enough.

02:09:06.725 --> 02:09:12.985
That was the beginning of a queer friendship which lasted a week, and ended, as I will

02:09:12.985 --> 02:09:13.525
tell you.

02:09:14.245 --> 02:09:20.805
She was exactly like a child. She wanted to be with me always. She tried to follow me

02:09:20.805 --> 02:09:26.065
everywhere, and on my next journey out and about, it went to my heart to tire her down

02:09:26.065 --> 02:09:31.985
and leave her, at last, exhausted and calling after me rather plaintively. But the problems

02:09:31.985 --> 02:09:37.745
of the world had to be mastered. I had not, I said to myself, come into the future to

02:09:37.745 --> 02:09:44.385
carry on a miniature flirtation. Yet her distress when I left her was very great. Her expostulations

02:09:44.385 --> 02:09:49.605
at the parting were sometimes frantic, and I think altogether I had as much trouble as

02:09:49.605 --> 02:09:56.025
comfort from her devotion. Nevertheless, she was, somehow, a very great comfort. I thought

02:09:56.025 --> 02:10:01.505
it was mere childish affection that made her cling to me. Until it was too late, I did

02:10:01.505 --> 02:10:07.425
not clearly know what I had inflicted upon her when I left her, nor until it was too

02:10:07.425 --> 02:10:13.665
late did I clearly understand what she was to me. For by merely seeming fond of me and

02:10:13.665 --> 02:10:20.165
showing in her weak, futile way that she cared for me, the little doll of a creature presently

02:10:20.165 --> 02:10:25.525
gave my return to the neighborhood of the white sphinx almost the feeling of coming

02:10:25.525 --> 02:10:32.065
home, and I would watch for her tiny figure of white and gold so soon as I came over the

02:10:32.065 --> 02:10:39.805
It was from her, too, that I learned that fear had not yet left the world. She was fearless

02:10:39.805 --> 02:10:45.445
enough in the daylight, and she had the oddest confidence in me, for once, in a foolish moment,

02:10:45.725 --> 02:10:52.765
I made threatening grimaces at her, and she simply laughed at them. But she dreaded the

02:10:52.765 --> 02:11:01.345
dark, dreaded shadows, dreaded black things. Darkness to her was the one thing dreadful.

02:11:01.345 --> 02:11:07.625
It was a singularly passionate emotion, and it set me thinking and observing. I discovered

02:11:07.625 --> 02:11:12.425
then, among other things, that these little people gathered into the great houses after

02:11:12.425 --> 02:11:18.745
dark and slept in droves. To enter upon them without a light was to put them into a tumult

02:11:18.745 --> 02:11:25.445
of apprehension. I never found one out of doors or sleeping alone within doors after

02:11:25.445 --> 02:11:32.425
dark. Yet I was still such a blockhead that I missed the lesson of that fear, and in spite

02:11:32.425 --> 02:11:39.585
of Weiner's distress, I insisted upon sleeping away from these slumbering multitudes. It

02:11:39.585 --> 02:11:45.165
troubled her greatly, but in the end her odd affection for me triumphed, and for five of

02:11:45.165 --> 02:11:49.805
the nights of our acquaintance, including the last night of all, she slept with her

02:11:49.805 --> 02:11:56.165
head pillowed on my arm. But my story slips away from me as I speak of her. It must have

02:11:56.165 --> 02:12:00.945
been the night before her rescue that I was awakened about dawn. I had been restless,

02:12:01.145 --> 02:12:06.585
dreaming most disagreeably that I was drowned, and that sea-anemones were feeling over my

02:12:06.585 --> 02:12:12.365
face with their soft palps. I woke with a start, and with an odd fancy that some greyish

02:12:12.365 --> 02:12:17.785
animal had just rushed out of the chamber. I tried to get to sleep again, but I felt

02:12:17.785 --> 02:12:23.685
restless and uncomfortable. It was that dim grey hour when things are just creeping out

02:12:23.685 --> 02:12:29.345
of darkness, when everything is colourless and clear-cut, and yet unreal. I got up and

02:12:29.345 --> 02:12:34.605
went down into the great hall, and saw out upon the flagstones in front of the palace.

02:12:34.985 --> 02:12:40.945
I thought I could make a virtue of necessity and see the sunrise. The moon was setting,

02:12:41.125 --> 02:12:46.625
and the dying moonlight and the first pallor of dawn were mingled in a ghastly half-light.

02:12:46.965 --> 02:12:54.185
The bushes were inky black, the ground a sombre grey, the sky colourless and cheerless, and

02:12:54.185 --> 02:13:01.145
up the hill I thought I could see ghosts. There, several times, as I scanned the slope,

02:13:01.505 --> 02:13:07.885
I saw white figures. Twice I fancied I saw a solitary white ape-like creature running

02:13:07.885 --> 02:13:13.165
rather quickly up the hill, and once near the ruins I saw a leash of them carrying some

02:13:13.165 --> 02:13:20.485
dark body. They moved hastily. I did not see what became of them. It seemed that they vanished

02:13:20.485 --> 02:13:26.685
among the bushes. The dawn was still indistinct, you must understand. I was feeling that chill,

02:13:26.845 --> 02:13:31.725
uncertain, early-morning feeling you may have known. I doubted my eyes.

02:13:32.845 --> 02:13:38.525
As the eastern sky grew brighter and the light of the day came on, and its vivid colouring

02:13:38.525 --> 02:13:44.205
turned upon the world once more, I scanned the view keenly, but I saw no vestige of my

02:13:44.205 --> 02:13:47.165
white figures. They were mere creatures of the half-light.

02:13:47.625 --> 02:13:51.125
They must have been ghosts, I said. I wonder whence they dated.

02:13:51.645 --> 02:13:57.345
For a queer notion of Grant Allen's came into my head and amused me. If each generation

02:13:57.345 --> 02:14:02.485
die and leave ghosts, he argued, the world at last will get overcrowded with them. On

02:14:02.485 --> 02:14:07.145
that theory they would have grown innumerable some eight hundred thousand years hence, and

02:14:07.145 --> 02:14:12.945
it was no great wonder to see four at once. But the jest was unsatisfying, and I was thinking

02:14:12.945 --> 02:14:19.485
of these figures all the morning, until Weena's rescue drove them out of my head. I associated

02:14:19.485 --> 02:14:24.485
them in some indefinite way with the white animal I had startled in my first passionate

02:14:24.485 --> 02:14:30.485
search for the time-machine, but Weena was a pleasant substitute. Yet all the same they

02:14:30.485 --> 02:14:34.825
were soon destined to take far deadlier possession of my mind.

02:14:35.625 --> 02:14:41.505
I think I have said how much hotter than our own was the weather of this golden age. I

02:14:41.505 --> 02:14:46.785
cannot account for it. It may be that the sun was hotter, or the earth nearer the sun.

02:14:47.205 --> 02:14:52.545
It is usual to assume that the sun will go on cooling steadily in the future. But people,

02:14:52.845 --> 02:14:57.885
unfamiliar with such speculations as those of the younger Darwin, forget that the planets

02:14:57.885 --> 02:15:04.025
must ultimately fall back one by one into the parent body. As these catastrophes occur,

02:15:04.025 --> 02:15:09.745
the sun will blaze with renewed energy, and it may be that some inner planet had suffered

02:15:09.745 --> 02:15:15.545
this fate. Whatever the reason, the fact remains that the sun was very much hotter than we

02:15:15.545 --> 02:15:21.505
know it. Well, one very hot morning, my fourth, I think, as I was seeking shelter from the

02:15:21.505 --> 02:15:26.525
heat and glare in a colossal ruin near the great house where I slept and fed, there happened

02:15:26.525 --> 02:15:32.485
this strange thing. Clamoring among these heaps of masonry, I found a narrow gallery

02:15:32.485 --> 02:15:38.765
whose end and side windows were blocked by fallen masses of stone. By contrast, with

02:15:38.765 --> 02:15:44.965
the brilliancy outside, it seemed at first impenetrably dark to me. I entered it, groping,

02:15:45.025 --> 02:15:51.105
for the change from light to blackness made spots of color swim before me. Suddenly I

02:15:51.105 --> 02:15:58.205
halted spellbound. A pair of eyes, luminous by reflection against the daylight without,

02:15:58.205 --> 02:16:05.865
out was watching me out of the darkness. The old, instinctive dread of wild beasts came

02:16:05.865 --> 02:16:11.525
upon me. I clenched my hands and steadfastly looked into the glaring eyeballs. I was afraid

02:16:11.525 --> 02:16:16.185
to turn. Then the thought of the absolute security in which humanity appeared to be

02:16:16.185 --> 02:16:22.305
living came to my mind, and then I remembered that strange terror of the dark. Overcoming

02:16:22.305 --> 02:16:28.765
my fear to some extent, I advanced a step and spoke. I will admit that my voice was

02:16:28.765 --> 02:16:35.385
harsh and ill-controlled. I put out my hand and touched something soft. At once the eyes

02:16:35.385 --> 02:16:40.305
darted sideways and something white ran past me. I turned with my heart in my mouth and

02:16:40.305 --> 02:16:46.345
saw a queer little ape-like figure, its head held down in a peculiar manner, running across

02:16:46.345 --> 02:16:52.285
the sunlit space behind me. It blundered against a block of granite, staggered aside, and in

02:16:52.285 --> 02:16:58.885
a black shadow beneath another pile of ruined masonry. My impression of it is, of course,

02:16:59.165 --> 02:17:06.565
imperfect, but I know it was a dull white, and had strange large grayish-red eyes, also

02:17:06.565 --> 02:17:12.705
that there was flaxen hair on its head and down its back. But, as I say, it went too

02:17:12.705 --> 02:17:18.485
fast for me to see distinctly. I cannot even say whether it ran on all fours or only with

02:17:18.485 --> 02:17:23.925
its forearms held very low. After an instant's pause, I followed it into the second heap

02:17:23.925 --> 02:17:30.425
of ruins. I could not find it at first, but after a time in the profound obscurity I came

02:17:30.425 --> 02:17:35.645
upon one of those round well-like openings of which I have told you half closed by a

02:17:35.645 --> 02:17:41.785
fallen pillar. A sudden thought came to me. Could this thing have vanished down the shaft?

02:17:41.785 --> 02:17:49.025
I lit a match, and looking down I saw a small, white, moving creature with large, bright

02:17:49.025 --> 02:17:55.785
eyes which regarded me steadfastly as it retreated. It made me shudder. It was so like a human

02:17:55.785 --> 02:18:01.805
spider. It was clamouring down the wall, and now I saw for the first time a number of metal

02:18:01.805 --> 02:18:07.125
foot and hand rests forming a kind of ladder down the shaft. Then the light burned my fingers

02:18:07.125 --> 02:18:12.505
and fell out of my hand, going out as it dropped. And when I had lit another, the little monster

02:18:12.505 --> 02:18:19.665
had disappeared. I do not know how long I sat peering down that well. It was not for

02:18:19.665 --> 02:18:25.825
some time that I could succeed in persuading myself that the thing I had seen was human.

02:18:26.485 --> 02:18:33.365
But gradually the truth dawned on me, that man had not remained one species, but had

02:18:33.365 --> 02:18:38.525
differentiated into two distinct animals, that my graceful children of the upper world

02:18:38.525 --> 02:18:44.805
were not the sole descendants of our generation, but that this bleached, obscene, nocturnal

02:18:44.805 --> 02:18:49.845
thing which had flashed before me was also heir to all the ages.

02:18:51.045 --> 02:18:57.225
I thought of the flickering pillars, and of my theory of an underground ventilation. I

02:18:57.225 --> 02:19:04.625
began to suspect their true import. And what, I wondered, was this lemur doing in my scheme

02:19:04.625 --> 02:19:09.925
of a perfectly balanced organization? How was it related to the indolent serenity of

02:19:09.925 --> 02:19:15.285
the beautiful upper-worlders? And what was hidden down there, at the foot of that shaft?

02:19:15.565 --> 02:19:21.005
I sat upon the edge of the well, telling myself that at any rate there was nothing to fear,

02:19:21.255 --> 02:19:28.425
and that there I must descend for the solution of my difficulties. And with all, I was absolutely

02:19:28.425 --> 02:19:30.005
afraid to go.

02:19:30.645 --> 02:19:35.825
As I hesitated, two of the beautiful upper-world people came running in their amorous sport

02:19:35.825 --> 02:19:41.545
across the daylight in the shadow. The male pursued the female, flinging flowers at her

02:19:41.545 --> 02:19:47.865
as he ran. They seemed distressed to find me, my arm against the overturned pillar peering

02:19:47.865 --> 02:19:53.105
down the well. Apparently it was considered bad form to remark these apertures, for when

02:19:53.105 --> 02:19:57.425
I pointed to this one and tried to frame a question about it in their tongue, they were

02:19:57.425 --> 02:20:02.945
still more visibly distressed and turned away. But they were interested by my matches, and

02:20:02.945 --> 02:20:08.025
I struck some to amuse them. I tried them again about the well, and again I failed.

02:20:08.365 --> 02:20:13.365
So presently I left them, meaning to go back to Weena and see what I could get from her.

02:20:13.665 --> 02:20:18.865
But my mind was already in revolution, my guesses and impressions were slipping and

02:20:18.865 --> 02:20:24.725
sliding to a new adjustment. I had now a clue to the import of these wells, to the ventilating

02:20:24.725 --> 02:20:29.785
towers, to the mystery of the ghosts, to say nothing of a hint at the meaning of the bronze

02:20:29.785 --> 02:20:35.305
gates and the fate of the time-machine. And very vaguely there came a suggestion towards

02:20:35.305 --> 02:20:41.265
the solution of the economic problem that had puzzled me. Here was the new view. Plainly,

02:20:41.265 --> 02:20:47.185
this second species of man was subterranean. There were three circumstances in particular

02:20:47.185 --> 02:20:52.765
which made me think that its rare emergence above ground was the outcome of a long-continued

02:20:52.765 --> 02:20:58.265
underground habit. In the first place there was the bleached look common in most animals

02:20:58.265 --> 02:21:03.505
that live largely in the dark. The white fish of the Kentucky Caves, for instance. Then

02:21:03.505 --> 02:21:09.985
those large eyes with that capacity for reflecting light are common features of nocturnal things,

02:21:09.985 --> 02:21:16.425
witness the owl and the cat. And last of all, that evident confusion in the sunshine, that

02:21:16.425 --> 02:21:21.825
hasty, yet fumbling, awkward flight towards dark shadow, and that peculiar carriage of

02:21:21.825 --> 02:21:27.525
the head while in the light, all reinforced the theory of an extreme sensitiveness of

02:21:27.525 --> 02:21:34.365
the retina. Beneath my feet, then, the earth must be tunneled enormously, and these tunnelings

02:21:34.365 --> 02:21:39.485
were the habitat of the new race. The presence of ventilating shafts and wells along the

02:21:39.485 --> 02:21:44.745
hill slopes, everywhere, in fact, except along the river valley, showed how universal

02:21:44.745 --> 02:21:51.585
were its ramifications. What so natural, then, as to assume that it was in this artificial

02:21:51.585 --> 02:21:56.885
underworld that such work as was necessary to the comfort of the daylight race was done?

02:21:57.165 --> 02:22:04.045
The notion was so plausible that I at once accepted it, and went on to assume the how

02:22:04.045 --> 02:22:09.405
of this splitting of the human species. I dare say you will anticipate the shape of

02:22:09.405 --> 02:22:17.105
my theory, though for myself I very soon felt that it fell far short of the truth. At first,

02:22:17.585 --> 02:22:22.445
proceeding from the problems of our own age, it seemed clear as daylight to me that the

02:22:22.445 --> 02:22:27.665
gradual widening of the present merely temporary and social difference between the capitalist

02:22:27.665 --> 02:22:33.665
and the labourer was the key to the whole position. No doubt it will seem grotesque

02:22:33.665 --> 02:22:39.625
enough to you, and wildly incredible, and yet even now there are existing circumstances

02:22:39.625 --> 02:22:45.485
to point that way. There is a tendency to utilize underground space for the less ornamental

02:22:45.485 --> 02:22:50.745
purposes of civilization. There is the Metropolitan Railway in London, for instance. There are

02:22:50.745 --> 02:22:56.425
new electric railways. There are subways. There are underground workrooms and restaurants,

02:22:56.545 --> 02:23:02.305
and they increase and multiply. Evidently, I thought, this tendency had increased till

02:23:02.305 --> 02:23:08.005
industry had gradually lost its birthright in the sky. I mean that it had gone deeper

02:23:08.005 --> 02:23:13.765
and deeper into larger and ever larger underground factories, spending a still increasing amount

02:23:13.765 --> 02:23:19.705
of its time therein till in the end, even now, does not an East End worker live in such

02:23:19.705 --> 02:23:24.225
artificial conditions as practically to be cut off from the natural surface of the earth?

02:23:24.685 --> 02:23:29.805
Again, the exclusive tendency of richer people do, no doubt, to the increasing refinement

02:23:29.805 --> 02:23:35.365
of their education and the widening gulf between them and the rude violence of the poor is

02:23:35.365 --> 02:23:40.385
already leading to the closing in their interest of considerable portions of the surface of

02:23:40.385 --> 02:23:46.685
the land. About London, for instance, perhaps half the prettier country is shut in against

02:23:46.685 --> 02:23:52.625
intrusion, and this same widening gulf, which is due to the length and expense of the higher

02:23:52.625 --> 02:23:58.285
educational process and the increased facilities for and temptations towards refined habits

02:23:58.285 --> 02:24:04.225
on the part of the rich, will make that exchange between class and class, that promotion by

02:24:04.225 --> 02:24:09.045
intermarriage which at present retards the splitting of our species along the lines of

02:24:09.045 --> 02:24:16.385
social stratification, less and less frequent. So, in the end, above ground you must have

02:24:16.385 --> 02:24:22.925
the haves, pursuing pleasure and comfort and beauty, and below ground the have-nots, the

02:24:22.925 --> 02:24:27.485
workers getting continually adapted to the conditions of their labor. Once they were

02:24:27.485 --> 02:24:32.045
there, they would no doubt have to pay rent and not a little of it for the ventilation

02:24:32.045 --> 02:24:38.825
of their caverns, and if they refused, they would starve or be suffocated for arrears.

02:24:38.825 --> 02:24:44.825
Such of them as were so constituted as to be miserable and rebellious would die, and

02:24:44.825 --> 02:24:49.645
in the end, the balance being permanent, the survivors would become as well adapted to

02:24:49.645 --> 02:24:54.365
the conditions of underground life and as happy in their way as the upper world people

02:24:54.365 --> 02:25:00.685
were to theirs, as it seemed to me the refined beauty and the atoliated pallor followed naturally

02:25:00.685 --> 02:25:07.145
enough. The great triumph of humanity I had dreamed of took a different shape in my mind.

02:25:07.525 --> 02:25:13.885
It had been no such triumph of moral education and general cooperation as I had imagined.

02:25:14.305 --> 02:25:20.745
Instead, I saw a real aristocracy, armed with a perfected science and working to a logical

02:25:20.745 --> 02:25:26.265
conclusion the industrial system of today. Its triumph had not been simply a triumph

02:25:26.265 --> 02:25:31.985
over nature, but a triumph over nature and the fellow man. This, I must warn you, was

02:25:31.985 --> 02:25:37.445
my theory at the time. I had no convenient cistern in the pattern of the utopian books.

02:25:37.685 --> 02:25:42.425
My explanation may be absolutely wrong. I still think it is the most plausible one,

02:25:42.645 --> 02:25:47.605
but even on this supposition the balanced civilization that was at last attained must

02:25:47.605 --> 02:25:53.785
have long since passed its zenith and was now far fallen into decay. The too-perfect

02:25:53.785 --> 02:25:59.705
security of the upper-worlders had led them to a slow movement of degeneration, to a general

02:25:59.705 --> 02:26:06.025
dwindling in size, strength and intelligence. That I could see clearly enough already. What

02:26:06.025 --> 02:26:11.685
had happened to the undergrounders I did not yet suspect, but from what I had seen of the

02:26:11.685 --> 02:26:17.085
Morlocks that by the way was the name by which these creatures were called, I could imagine

02:26:17.085 --> 02:26:22.425
that the modification of the human type was even far more profound than among the Eloi,

02:26:22.625 --> 02:26:29.425
the beautiful race that I already knew. Then came troublesome doubts. Why had the Morlocks

02:26:29.425 --> 02:26:35.225
taken my time-machine? For I felt sure it was they who had taken it. Why too, if the

02:26:35.225 --> 02:26:40.485
Eloi were masters, could they not restore the machine to me? And why were they so terribly

02:26:40.485 --> 02:26:46.665
afraid of the dark? I proceeded, as I have said, to question Weena about this underworld,

02:26:46.965 --> 02:26:52.765
but here again I was disappointed. At first she would not understand my questions, and

02:26:52.765 --> 02:26:57.945
presently she refused to answer them. She shivered, as though the topic was unendurable,

02:26:58.325 --> 02:27:04.905
and when I pressed her, perhaps a little harshly, she burst into tears. They were the only tears,

02:27:04.905 --> 02:27:11.545
except my own, I ever saw in that golden age. When I saw them, I ceased abruptly to trouble

02:27:11.545 --> 02:27:17.145
about the Morlocks, and was only concerned in banishing these signs of the human inheritance

02:27:17.145 --> 02:27:25.265
from Weena's eyes, and very soon she was smiling and clapping her hands, while I solemnly burned

02:27:25.265 --> 02:27:26.025
a match.

02:28:05.511 --> 02:28:10.531
It may seem odd to you, but it was two days

02:28:10.531 --> 02:28:15.791
before I could follow up the newfound clue in what was manifestly the proper way. I felt

02:28:15.791 --> 02:28:21.171
a peculiar shrinking from those pallid bodies. They were just the half-bleached color of

02:28:21.171 --> 02:28:26.931
the worms and things one sees preserved in spirit in a zoological museum, and they were

02:28:26.931 --> 02:28:32.691
filthily cold to the touch. Probably my shrinking was largely due to the sympathetic influence

02:28:32.691 --> 02:28:37.771
of the Eloi, whose disgust of the Morlocks I now began to appreciate.

02:28:38.491 --> 02:28:44.131
The next night I did not sleep well. Probably my health was a little disordered. I was oppressed

02:28:44.131 --> 02:28:49.731
with perplexity and doubt. Once or twice I had a feeling of intense fear for which I

02:28:49.731 --> 02:28:55.411
could perceive no definite reason. I remember creeping noiselessly into the great hall where

02:28:55.411 --> 02:29:00.671
the little people were sleeping in the moonlight. That night Weena was among them, and feeling

02:29:00.671 --> 02:29:06.711
reassured by their presence. It occurred to me even then that in the course of a few days

02:29:06.711 --> 02:29:12.811
the moon must pass through its last quarter and the nights grow dark, when the appearances

02:29:12.811 --> 02:29:18.711
of these unpleasant creatures from below, these whitened lemurs, this new vermin that

02:29:18.711 --> 02:29:25.091
had replaced the old, might be more abundant. On both these days I had the restless feeling

02:29:25.091 --> 02:29:31.171
of one who shirks an inevitable duty. I felt assured that the time machine was only to

02:29:31.171 --> 02:29:37.291
be recovered by boldly penetrating these underground mysteries, yet I could not face the mystery.

02:29:37.631 --> 02:29:44.651
If only I had a companion it would have been different, but I was so horribly alone, and

02:29:44.651 --> 02:29:50.451
even to clamor down into the darkness of the well appalled me. I don't know if you will

02:29:50.451 --> 02:29:55.891
understand my feeling, but I never felt quite safe at my back.

02:29:55.891 --> 02:30:02.631
It was this restlessness, this insecurity perhaps, that drove me further and further

02:30:02.631 --> 02:30:08.511
afield in my exploring expeditions. Going to the southwestward towards the rising country

02:30:08.511 --> 02:30:14.411
that is now called Combe Wood, I observed far off in the direction of nineteenth century

02:30:14.411 --> 02:30:20.831
Banstead a vast green structure, different in character from any I had hitherto seen.

02:30:20.831 --> 02:30:27.591
It was larger than the largest of the palaces or ruins I knew, and the façade had an oriental

02:30:27.591 --> 02:30:33.031
look, the face of it having the luster as well as the pale green tint, a kind of bluish

02:30:33.031 --> 02:30:39.951
green, of a certain type of Chinese porcelain. This difference in aspect suggested a difference

02:30:39.951 --> 02:30:46.451
in use, and I was minded to push on and explore. But the day was growing late, and I had come

02:30:46.451 --> 02:30:51.391
upon the sight of the place after a long and tiring circuit, so I resolved to hold

02:30:51.391 --> 02:30:56.531
over the adventure for the following day, and I returned to the welcome and the caresses

02:30:56.531 --> 02:31:02.411
of little Weena. But next morning I perceived clearly enough that my curiosity regarding

02:31:02.411 --> 02:31:07.951
the palace of green porcelain was a piece of self-deception, to enable me to shirk by

02:31:07.951 --> 02:31:14.451
another day an experience I dreaded. I resolved I would make the descent without further waste

02:31:14.451 --> 02:31:19.591
of time, and started out in the early morning towards a well, near the ruins of granite

02:31:19.591 --> 02:31:25.831
and aluminum. Little Weena ran with me, she danced beside me to the well, but when she

02:31:25.831 --> 02:31:31.731
saw me lean over the mouth and look downward, she seemed strangely disconcerted.

02:31:32.151 --> 02:31:37.051
Goodbye, little Weena, I said, kissing her, and then putting her down, I began to feel

02:31:37.051 --> 02:31:42.731
over the parapet for the climbing hooks. Rather hastily, I may as well confess, for I feared

02:31:42.731 --> 02:31:49.351
my courage might leak away. At first she watched me in amazement, then she gave the most piteous

02:31:49.351 --> 02:31:54.451
cry and running to me, she began to pull at me with her little hands. I think her opposition

02:31:54.451 --> 02:31:59.751
nerve me rather to proceed. I shook her off, perhaps a little roughly, and in another moment

02:31:59.751 --> 02:32:05.771
I was in the throat of the well. I saw her agonized face over the parapet and smiled

02:32:05.771 --> 02:32:12.031
to reassure her. Then I had to look down at the unstable hooks to which I clung. I had

02:32:12.031 --> 02:32:17.471
to clamor down a shaft of perhaps two hundred yards. The descent was affected by means of

02:32:17.471 --> 02:32:21.851
metallic bars projecting from the sides of the well, and these being adapted to the needs

02:32:21.851 --> 02:32:26.991
of a creature much smaller and lighter than myself. I was speedily cramped and fatigued

02:32:26.991 --> 02:32:32.451
by the descent, and not simply fatigued. One of the bars bent suddenly under my weight

02:32:32.451 --> 02:32:37.851
and almost swung me off into the blackness beneath. For a moment I hung by one hand,

02:32:37.851 --> 02:32:43.191
and after that experience I did not dare to rest again, though my arms and back were presently

02:32:43.191 --> 02:32:47.551
acutely painful. I went on clamoring down the sheer descent with as quick a motion as

02:32:47.551 --> 02:32:53.551
possible. Glancing upward, I saw the aperture, a small blue disk in which a star was visible,

02:32:53.871 --> 02:32:59.731
while little Weena's head showed as a round black projection. The thudding sound of a

02:32:59.731 --> 02:33:06.151
machine below grew louder and more oppressive. Everything save that little disk above was

02:33:06.151 --> 02:33:12.651
profoundly dark, and when I looked up again, Weena had disappeared. I was in an agony

02:33:12.651 --> 02:33:17.431
of discomfort. I had some thought of trying to go up the shaft again and leave the underworld

02:33:17.431 --> 02:33:23.251
alone, but even while I turned this over in my mind, I continued to descend. At last,

02:33:23.291 --> 02:33:28.451
with intense relief, I saw dimly coming up, a foot to the right of me, a slender loophole

02:33:28.451 --> 02:33:33.951
in the wall. Swinging myself in, I found it was the aperture of a narrow horizontal tunnel

02:33:33.951 --> 02:33:40.891
in which I could lie down and rest. It was not too soon my arms ached, my back was cramped,

02:33:40.991 --> 02:33:46.711
and I was trembling with the prolonged terror of a fall. Besides this, the unbroken darkness

02:33:46.711 --> 02:33:53.191
had had a distressing effect upon my eyes. The air was full of the throb and hum of machinery

02:33:53.191 --> 02:33:59.351
pumping air down the shaft. I do not know how long I lay. I was roused by a soft hand

02:33:59.351 --> 02:34:04.151
touching my face. Starting up in the darkness, I snatched at my matches, and hastily striking

02:34:04.151 --> 02:34:09.011
one I saw three stooping white creatures similar to the one I had seen above ground in the

02:34:09.011 --> 02:34:13.531
ruin, hastily retreating before the light, living as they did in what appeared to me

02:34:13.531 --> 02:34:19.411
in penetrable darkness. Their eyes were abnormally large and sensitive, just as are the pupils

02:34:19.411 --> 02:34:24.511
of the abysmal fishes, and they reflected the light in the same way. I have no doubt

02:34:24.511 --> 02:34:28.911
they could see me in that rayless obscurity, and they did not seem to have any fear of

02:34:28.911 --> 02:34:33.811
me apart from the light. But so soon as I struck a match in order to see them, they

02:34:33.811 --> 02:34:38.931
fled incontinently, vanishing into dark gutters and tunnels, from which their eyes glared

02:34:38.931 --> 02:34:43.971
at me in the strangest fashion. I tried to call to them, but the language they had was

02:34:43.971 --> 02:34:49.391
apparently different from that of the overworld people, so that I was needs left to my own

02:34:49.391 --> 02:34:54.471
unaided efforts, and the thought of flight before exploration was even then in my mind.

02:34:54.471 --> 02:35:00.351
But I said to myself, You are in for it now. And feeling my way along the tunnel, I found

02:35:00.351 --> 02:35:05.891
the noise of machinery grow louder. Presently the walls fell away from me, and I came to

02:35:05.891 --> 02:35:12.191
a large open space, and, striking another match, saw that I had entered a vast arched

02:35:12.191 --> 02:35:17.371
cavern, which stretched into utter darkness beyond the range of my light. The view I had

02:35:17.371 --> 02:35:22.011
of it was as much as one could see in the burning of a match. Necessarily my memory

02:35:22.011 --> 02:35:28.411
is vague. Great shapes like big machines rose out of the dimness, and cast grotesque black

02:35:28.411 --> 02:35:34.631
shadows in which dim spectral moorlocks sheltered from the glare. The place, by the by, was

02:35:34.631 --> 02:35:40.411
very stuffy and oppressive, and the faint halitus of freshly shed blood was in the air.

02:35:40.911 --> 02:35:46.931
Some way down the central vista was a little table of white metal, laid with what seemed

02:35:46.931 --> 02:35:53.851
a meal. The moorlocks at any rate were carnivorous. Even at the time I remember wondering what

02:35:53.851 --> 02:36:00.431
large animal could have survived to furnish the red joint I saw. It was all very indistinct,

02:36:00.691 --> 02:36:06.071
the heavy smell, the big unmeaning shapes, the obscene figures lurking in the shadows

02:36:06.071 --> 02:36:11.191
and only waiting for the darkness to come at me again. Then the match burned down and

02:36:11.191 --> 02:36:15.411
stung my fingers and fell, a wriggling red spot in the blackness.

02:36:16.211 --> 02:36:21.891
I have thought since how particularly ill-equipped I was for such an experience. When I had started

02:36:21.891 --> 02:36:26.231
with the time machine I had started with the absurd assumption that the men of the future

02:36:26.231 --> 02:36:31.751
would certainly be infinitely ahead of ourselves in all their appliances. I had come without

02:36:31.751 --> 02:36:38.171
arms, without medicine, without anything to smoke. At times I missed tobacco frightfully,

02:36:38.411 --> 02:36:44.551
even without enough matches. If only I had thought of a Kodak! I could have flashed that

02:36:44.551 --> 02:36:50.471
glimpse of the underworld in a second and examined it at leisure. But as it was I stood

02:36:50.471 --> 02:36:55.791
there with only the weapons and the powers that nature had endowed me with, hands, feet,

02:36:55.911 --> 02:37:01.791
and teeth, these, and four safety-matches that still remained to me. I was afraid to

02:37:01.791 --> 02:37:07.171
push my way in among all this machinery in the dark, and it was only with my last glimpse

02:37:07.171 --> 02:37:12.271
of light I discovered that my store of matches had run low. It had never occurred to me

02:37:12.271 --> 02:37:16.931
until that moment that there was any need to economize them, and I had wasted almost

02:37:16.931 --> 02:37:22.731
half the box in astonishing the upper-worlders to whom fire was a novelty. Now, as I say,

02:37:22.751 --> 02:37:29.251
I had four left, and while I stood in the dark a hand touched mine, lank fingers came

02:37:29.251 --> 02:37:35.851
feeling over my face, and I was sensible of a peculiar, unpleasant odor. I fancied I

02:37:35.851 --> 02:37:41.031
heard the breathing of a crowd of those dreadful little beings about me. I felt the box of

02:37:41.031 --> 02:37:46.671
matches in my hand being gently disengaged and other hands behind me plucking at my clothing.

02:37:47.531 --> 02:37:54.011
The sense of these unseen creatures examining me was indescribably unpleasant. The sudden

02:37:54.011 --> 02:38:00.191
realization of my ignorance of their ways of thinking and doing came home to me very

02:38:00.191 --> 02:38:05.191
vividly in the darkness. I shouted at them as loudly as I could. They started away, and

02:38:05.191 --> 02:38:10.431
even then I could feel them approaching me again. They clutched at me more boldly, whispering

02:38:10.431 --> 02:38:15.471
odd sounds to each other. I shivered violently and shouted again rather discordantly. This

02:38:15.471 --> 02:38:19.771
time they were not so seriously alarmed, and they made a queer laughing noise as they came

02:38:19.771 --> 02:38:24.851
back at me. I will confess I was horribly frightened. I determined to strike another

02:38:24.851 --> 02:38:29.631
match and escape under the protection of its glare. I did so, and eking out the flicker

02:38:29.631 --> 02:38:33.811
with a scrap of paper from my pocket, I made good my retreat to the narrow tunnel.

02:38:33.811 --> 02:38:38.731
But I had scarce entered this when my light was blown out, and in the blackness I could

02:38:38.731 --> 02:38:43.411
hear the Morlocks rustling like wind among leaves and pattering like rain as they hurried

02:38:43.411 --> 02:38:47.771
after me. In a moment I was clutched by several hands, and there was no mistaking that they

02:38:47.771 --> 02:38:51.831
were trying to haul me back. I struck another light and waved it in their dazzled faces.

02:38:52.111 --> 02:38:57.711
You can scarce imagine how nauseatingly inhuman they looked, those pale, chinless faces and

02:38:57.711 --> 02:39:02.831
great lidless pinkish-grey eyes, as they stared in their blindness and bewilderment.

02:39:02.831 --> 02:39:07.411
But I did not stay to look. I promise you I retreated again, and when my second match

02:39:07.411 --> 02:39:11.691
had ended I struck my third. It had almost burned through when I reached the opening

02:39:11.691 --> 02:39:16.291
into the shaft. I lay down on the edge, for the throb of the great pump below made me

02:39:16.291 --> 02:39:21.371
giddy. Then I felt sideways for the projecting hooks, and as I did so my feet were grasped

02:39:21.371 --> 02:39:27.071
from behind, and I was violently tugged backward. I lit my last match, and it incontinently

02:39:27.071 --> 02:39:32.231
went out. But I had my hand on the climbing bars now, and, kicking violently, I disengaged

02:39:32.231 --> 02:39:36.731
myself from the clutches of the moorlocks, and was speedily clamouring up the shaft while

02:39:36.731 --> 02:39:41.991
they stared peering and blinking up at me. All but one little wretch who followed me for

02:39:41.991 --> 02:39:45.111
some way, and well nigh secured my boot as a trophy.

02:39:45.831 --> 02:39:51.851
That climb seemed interminable to me. With the last twenty or thirty feet of it a deadly

02:39:51.851 --> 02:39:57.111
nausea came upon me. I had the greatest difficulty in keeping my hold. The last few yards was

02:39:57.111 --> 02:40:02.151
a frightful struggle against this faintness. Several times my head swam, and I felt all

02:40:02.151 --> 02:40:07.611
the sensations of falling. At last, however, I got over the well-mouth somehow, and staggered

02:40:07.611 --> 02:40:14.531
out of the ruin into the blinding sunlight. I fell upon my face. Even the soil smelt

02:40:14.531 --> 02:40:22.911
sweet and clean. Then I remember Weena kissing my hands and ears, and the voices of others

02:40:22.911 --> 02:40:28.151
among the alloy. Then, for a time, I was insensible.

02:40:57.261 --> 02:41:00.281
Now indeed I seemed in a worse case than before.

02:41:00.741 --> 02:41:05.861
Hitherto, except during my night's anguish at the loss of the Time-Machine, I had felt

02:41:05.861 --> 02:41:08.301
a sustaining hope of ultimate escape.

02:41:08.781 --> 02:41:11.721
But that hope was staggered by these new discoveries.

02:41:12.381 --> 02:41:17.681
Hitherto I had merely thought myself impeded by the childish simplicity of the little people

02:41:17.681 --> 02:41:21.901
and by some unknown forces which I had only to understand to overcome.

02:41:22.481 --> 02:41:28.761
But there was an altogether new element in the sickening quality of the Morlocks, a something

02:41:28.761 --> 02:41:30.221
inhuman and malign.

02:41:30.621 --> 02:41:32.341
Instinctively I loathed them.

02:41:32.861 --> 02:41:37.021
Before I had felt as a man might feel who had fallen into a pit.

02:41:37.521 --> 02:41:40.881
My concern was with the pit and how to get out of it.

02:41:41.061 --> 02:41:46.141
Now I felt like a beast in a trap, whose enemy would come upon him soon.

02:41:46.781 --> 02:41:49.201
The enemy I dreaded may surprise you.

02:41:49.801 --> 02:41:51.861
It was the darkness of the new moon.

02:41:52.501 --> 02:41:57.441
Weena had put this into my head by some at first incomprehensible remarks about the Dark

02:41:57.441 --> 02:41:57.801
Knights.

02:41:57.801 --> 02:42:03.101
It was not now such a very difficult problem to guess what the coming Dark Knights might

02:42:03.101 --> 02:42:03.501
mean.

02:42:04.261 --> 02:42:05.921
The moon was on the wane.

02:42:06.081 --> 02:42:08.881
Each night there was a longer interval of darkness.

02:42:09.261 --> 02:42:14.321
And I now understood to some slight degree at least the reason of the fear of the little

02:42:14.321 --> 02:42:16.021
upper world people for the dark.

02:42:16.681 --> 02:42:22.481
I wondered vaguely what foul villainy it might be that the Morlocks did under the new moon.

02:42:22.961 --> 02:42:26.861
I felt pretty sure now that my second hypothesis was all wrong.

02:42:27.461 --> 02:42:32.681
The upper world people might once have been the favored aristocracy and the Morlocks their

02:42:32.681 --> 02:42:36.081
mechanical servants, but that had long since passed away.

02:42:36.741 --> 02:42:41.741
The two species that had resulted from the evolution of man were sliding down toward

02:42:41.741 --> 02:42:45.301
or had already arrived at an altogether new relationship.

02:42:45.881 --> 02:42:51.121
The Eloi, like the Carolingian kings, had decayed to a mere beautiful futility.

02:42:51.601 --> 02:42:54.181
They still possessed the earth on sufferance.

02:42:54.181 --> 02:43:00.321
Since the Morlocks, subterranean for innumerable generations, had come at last to find the

02:43:00.321 --> 02:43:06.181
daylit surface intolerable, and the Morlocks made their garments I inferred and maintained

02:43:06.181 --> 02:43:11.981
them in their habitual needs perhaps through the survival of an old habit of service, they

02:43:11.981 --> 02:43:18.101
did it as a standing horse paws with his foot or as a man enjoys killing animals for sport,

02:43:18.621 --> 02:43:22.741
because ancient and departed necessities had impressed it on the organism.

02:43:23.381 --> 02:43:27.601
But, clearly, the old order was already in part reversed.

02:43:28.401 --> 02:43:31.781
The nemesis of the delicate ones was creeping on apace.

02:43:32.081 --> 02:43:37.741
Ages ago, thousands of generations ago, a man had thrust his brother man out of the

02:43:37.741 --> 02:43:41.681
ease and the sunshine, and now that brother was coming back changed.

02:43:42.301 --> 02:43:46.401
Already the Eloi had begun to learn one old lesson anew.

02:43:46.761 --> 02:43:51.701
They were becoming reacquainted with fear, and suddenly there came into my head the memory

02:43:51.701 --> 02:43:53.941
of the meat I had seen in the underworld.

02:43:54.481 --> 02:43:59.701
It seemed odd how it floated into my mind, not stirred up, as it were by the current

02:43:59.701 --> 02:44:04.161
of my meditations, but coming in almost like a question from the outside.

02:44:04.841 --> 02:44:06.741
I tried to recall the form of it.

02:44:06.881 --> 02:44:11.921
I had a vague sense of something familiar, but I could not tell what it was at the time.

02:44:12.521 --> 02:44:17.141
Still, however helpless the little people in the presence of their mysterious fear,

02:44:17.541 --> 02:44:19.261
I was differently constituted.

02:44:19.801 --> 02:44:25.221
I came out of this age of ours, this ripe prime of the human race, when fear does not

02:44:25.221 --> 02:44:28.261
paralyze and mystery has lost its terrors.

02:44:28.501 --> 02:44:30.481
I at least would defend myself.

02:44:30.981 --> 02:44:35.801
Without further delay, I determined to make myself arms and a fastness where I might sleep.

02:44:36.521 --> 02:44:41.281
With that refuge as a base, I could face this strange world with some of the confidence

02:44:41.281 --> 02:44:45.681
I had lost in realizing to what creatures night by night I lay exposed.

02:44:46.441 --> 02:44:50.261
I felt I could never sleep again until my bed was secure from them.

02:44:50.661 --> 02:44:54.781
I shuddered with horror to think how they must already have examined me.

02:44:55.761 --> 02:45:01.021
I wandered during the afternoon along the valley of the Thames, but found nothing that

02:45:01.021 --> 02:45:03.741
commended itself to my mind as inaccessible.

02:45:04.281 --> 02:45:08.801
All the buildings and trees seemed easily practicable to such dexterous climbers as

02:45:08.801 --> 02:45:11.941
the Morlocks, to judge by their wells must be.

02:45:12.661 --> 02:45:17.981
Then the tall pinnacles of the Palace of Green Porcelain and the polished gleam of its walls

02:45:17.981 --> 02:45:23.581
came back to my memory, and in the evening, taking Weena like a child upon my shoulder,

02:45:24.001 --> 02:45:26.161
I went up the hills toward the southwest.

02:45:26.721 --> 02:45:31.681
The distance I had reckoned was seven or eight miles, but it must have been nearer eighteen.

02:45:32.341 --> 02:45:37.581
I had first seen the place on a moist afternoon when distances are deceptively diminished.

02:45:38.061 --> 02:45:43.241
In addition, the heel of one of my shoes was loose and a nail was working through the sole.

02:45:43.841 --> 02:45:47.841
They were comfortable old shoes I wore about indoors, so that I was lame.

02:45:48.721 --> 02:45:54.841
And it was already long past sunset when I came inside of the palace, silhouetted black

02:45:54.841 --> 02:45:56.921
against the pale yellow of the sky.

02:45:58.081 --> 02:46:03.401
Weena had been hugely delighted when I began to carry her, but after a while she desired

02:46:03.401 --> 02:46:09.101
me to let her down, and ran along by the side of me, occasionally darting off on either

02:46:09.101 --> 02:46:11.261
hand to pick flowers to stick in my pockets.

02:46:11.801 --> 02:46:16.881
My pockets had always puzzled Weena, but at the last, she had concluded that they were

02:46:16.881 --> 02:46:19.681
an eccentric kind of vase for floral decoration.

02:46:20.401 --> 02:46:23.061
At least she utilized them for that purpose.

02:46:23.501 --> 02:46:28.381
And that reminds me, in changing my jacket I found...

02:46:28.381 --> 02:46:34.021
The time-traveller paused, put his hand into his pocket, and silently placed two withered

02:46:34.021 --> 02:46:38.721
flowers not unlike very large white mallows upon the little table.

02:46:39.241 --> 02:46:40.601
Then he resumed his narrative.

02:46:41.481 --> 02:46:46.301
As the hush of evening crept over the world and we proceeded over the hillcrest toward

02:46:46.301 --> 02:46:50.741
Wimbledon, Weena grew tired and wanted to return to the house of Greystone.

02:46:51.241 --> 02:46:57.201
But I pointed out the distant pinnacles of the palace of green porcelain to her and contrived

02:46:57.201 --> 02:47:01.541
to make her understand that we were seeking a refuge there from her fear.

02:47:02.181 --> 02:47:06.381
You know that great pause that comes upon things before the dusk?

02:47:06.521 --> 02:47:08.361
Even the breeze stops in the trees.

02:47:09.021 --> 02:47:13.381
To me, there was always an air of expectation about that evening stillness.

02:47:13.701 --> 02:47:19.201
The sky was clear, remote, and empty save for a few horizontal bars far down on the

02:47:19.201 --> 02:47:19.541
sunset.

02:47:20.181 --> 02:47:23.801
Well, that night the expectation took the color of my fears.

02:47:24.081 --> 02:47:28.501
In that darkling calm my senses seemed preternaturally sharpened.

02:47:28.501 --> 02:47:33.841
I fancied I could even feel the hollowness of the ground beneath my feet, could indeed

02:47:33.841 --> 02:47:39.381
almost see through it the moorlocks on their ant-hill going hither and thither and waiting

02:47:39.381 --> 02:47:40.141
for the dark.

02:47:40.921 --> 02:47:45.881
In my excitement I fancied that they would receive my invasion of their burrows as a

02:47:45.881 --> 02:47:47.081
declaration of war.

02:47:47.561 --> 02:47:50.141
And why had they taken my time-machine?

02:47:50.841 --> 02:47:55.441
So we went on in the quiet, and the twilight deepened into night.

02:47:55.901 --> 02:48:00.381
The clear blue of the distance faded, and one star after another came out.

02:48:00.881 --> 02:48:03.261
The ground grew dim and the trees black.

02:48:03.981 --> 02:48:06.581
Weena's fear and her fatigue grew upon her.

02:48:07.101 --> 02:48:12.401
I took her in my arms and talked to her and caressed her, then as the darkness grew deeper

02:48:12.401 --> 02:48:17.421
she put her arms around my neck and, closing her eyes, tightly pressed her face against

02:48:17.421 --> 02:48:18.121
my shoulder.

02:48:18.641 --> 02:48:24.421
So we went down a long slope into a valley, and there in the dimness I almost walked into

02:48:24.421 --> 02:48:25.121
a little river.

02:48:25.921 --> 02:48:31.681
This I waited and went up the opposite side of the valley, past a number of sleeping houses,

02:48:32.181 --> 02:48:36.521
and by a statue, a faun or some such figure, minus the head.

02:48:37.221 --> 02:48:38.761
Here too were acacias.

02:48:39.841 --> 02:48:45.521
So far I had seen nothing of the moorlocks, but it was yet early in the night, and the

02:48:45.521 --> 02:48:48.741
darker hours before the old moon rose were still to come.

02:48:49.841 --> 02:48:55.281
From the brow of the next hill I saw a thick wood spreading wide and black before me.

02:48:55.781 --> 02:48:57.201
I hesitated at this.

02:48:57.761 --> 02:49:01.641
I could see no end to it, either to the right or the left.

02:49:02.201 --> 02:49:05.281
Feeling tired, my feet in particular were very sore.

02:49:05.741 --> 02:49:10.421
I carefully lowered Weena from my shoulder as I halted and sat down upon the turf.

02:49:10.861 --> 02:49:16.501
I could no longer see the palace of green porcelain, and I was in doubt of my direction.

02:49:17.141 --> 02:49:21.081
I looked into the thickness of the wood and thought of what it might hide.

02:49:21.701 --> 02:49:27.381
Under that dense tangle of branches one would be out of sight of the stars, even were there

02:49:27.381 --> 02:49:32.881
no other lurking danger, a danger I did not care to let my imagination loose upon.

02:49:33.441 --> 02:49:38.661
There would still be all the roots to stumble over and the tree-balls to strike against.

02:49:38.661 --> 02:49:44.101
I was very tired, too, after the excitements of the day, so I decided that I would not

02:49:44.101 --> 02:49:47.141
face it, but would pass the night upon the open hill.

02:49:47.681 --> 02:49:50.421
Weena, I was glad to find, was fast asleep.

02:49:50.981 --> 02:49:55.681
I carefully wrapped her in my jacket and sat down beside her to wait for the moonrise.

02:49:56.421 --> 02:50:01.941
The hillside was quiet and deserted, but from the black of the wood there came now and then

02:50:01.941 --> 02:50:03.441
a stir of living things.

02:50:04.361 --> 02:50:07.381
Above me shone the stars, for the night was very clear.

02:50:07.381 --> 02:50:11.061
I felt a certain sense of friendly comfort in their twinkling.

02:50:12.021 --> 02:50:14.681
All the old constellations had gone from the sky.

02:50:15.081 --> 02:50:21.161
However, that slow movement which is imperceptible in a hundred human lifetimes had long since

02:50:21.161 --> 02:50:27.641
rearranged them in unfamiliar groupings, but the Milky Way, it seemed to me, was still

02:50:27.641 --> 02:50:31.261
the same tattered streamer of stardust as of yore.

02:50:31.261 --> 02:50:37.241
Southward, as I judged it, was a very bright red star that was new to me.

02:50:37.501 --> 02:50:43.521
It was even more splendid than our own green Sirius, and amid all these scintillating points

02:50:43.521 --> 02:50:48.881
of light one bright planet shone kindly and steadily like the face of an old friend.

02:50:49.721 --> 02:50:54.541
Looking at these stars suddenly dwarfed my own troubles and all the gravities of terrestrial

02:50:54.541 --> 02:50:55.001
life.

02:50:55.401 --> 02:51:00.701
I thought of their unfathomable distance and the slow inevitable drift of their movements

02:51:00.701 --> 02:51:03.561
out of the unknown past into the unknown future.

02:51:03.961 --> 02:51:07.721
I thought of the great processional cycle that the Pole of the Earth describes.

02:51:08.221 --> 02:51:14.601
Only forty times had that silent revolution occurred during all the years that I had traversed.

02:51:14.661 --> 02:51:20.341
And during these few revolutions, all the activity, all the traditions, the complex

02:51:20.341 --> 02:51:26.401
organizations, the nations, languages, literatures, aspirations, even the mere memory of man as

02:51:26.401 --> 02:51:29.161
I knew him, had been swept out of existence.

02:51:29.941 --> 02:51:36.201
Instead were these frail creatures whom had forgotten their high ancestry and the white

02:51:36.201 --> 02:51:38.321
things of which I went in terror.

02:51:39.021 --> 02:51:43.561
Then I thought of the great fear that was between the two species, and for the first

02:51:43.561 --> 02:51:48.661
time with a sudden shiver came the clear knowledge of what the meat I had seen might be.

02:51:48.941 --> 02:51:50.441
Yet it was too horrible.

02:51:51.481 --> 02:51:56.421
I looked at little Weena sleeping beside me, her face white and star-like under the stars,

02:51:57.001 --> 02:51:59.121
and forthwith dismissed the thought.

02:52:00.001 --> 02:52:05.281
Through that long night I held my mind off the Morlocks as well as I could, and whiled

02:52:05.281 --> 02:52:10.681
away the time by trying to fancy I could find signs of the old constellations in their new confusion.

02:52:11.421 --> 02:52:14.841
The sky kept very clear except for a hazy cloud or so.

02:52:15.221 --> 02:52:16.821
No doubt I dozed at times.

02:52:17.141 --> 02:52:22.841
Then as my vigil wore on came the faintness in the eastward sky, like the reflection of

02:52:22.841 --> 02:52:27.541
some colourless fire, and the old moon rose, thin and peaked and white.

02:52:28.441 --> 02:52:35.221
And close behind, and overtaking it, and overflowing it, the dawn came, pale at first, then growing

02:52:35.221 --> 02:52:36.201
pink and warm.

02:52:36.701 --> 02:52:38.401
No Morlocks had approached us.

02:52:38.801 --> 02:52:41.701
Indeed, I had seen none upon the hill that night.

02:52:42.421 --> 02:52:47.501
And in the confidence of renewed day it almost seemed to me that my fear had been unreasonable.

02:52:48.181 --> 02:52:53.641
I stood up and found my foot with the loose heel swollen at the ankle and painful under

02:52:53.641 --> 02:52:58.081
the heel, so I sat down again, took off my shoes, and flung them away.

02:52:59.301 --> 02:53:05.181
I awakened Weena, and we went down into the wood, now green and pleasant instead of black

02:53:05.181 --> 02:53:06.121
and forbidding.

02:53:06.421 --> 02:53:09.221
We found some fruit wherewith to break our fast.

02:53:09.741 --> 02:53:14.921
We soon met others of the dainty ones, laughing and dancing in the sunlight, as though there

02:53:14.921 --> 02:53:17.441
was no such thing in nature as the night.

02:53:18.061 --> 02:53:21.161
And then I thought once more of the meat that I had seen.

02:53:21.961 --> 02:53:27.241
I felt assured now of what it was, and from the bottom of my heart I pitied this last

02:53:27.241 --> 02:53:29.981
feeble rill from the great flood of humanity.

02:53:30.621 --> 02:53:36.301
Clearly, at some time in the long ago of human decay the Morlocks' food had run short.

02:53:36.901 --> 02:53:40.061
Possibly they had lived on rats and such like vermin.

02:53:40.501 --> 02:53:46.241
Even now man is far less discriminating and exclusive in his food than he was, far less

02:53:46.241 --> 02:53:47.221
than any monkey.

02:53:48.721 --> 02:53:55.521
His prejudice against human flesh is no deep-seated instinct, and so these inhuman sons of men.

02:53:56.481 --> 02:54:00.061
I tried to look at the thing in a scientific spirit.

02:54:00.561 --> 02:54:05.841
After all, they were less human and more remote than our cannibal ancestors of three or four

02:54:05.841 --> 02:54:11.641
thousand years ago, and the intelligence that would have made this state of things a torment

02:54:11.641 --> 02:54:12.381
had gone.

02:54:12.981 --> 02:54:14.661
Why should I trouble myself?

02:54:15.261 --> 02:54:21.201
These Eloi were mere fatted cattle which the ant-like Morlock preserved and preyed upon

02:54:21.201 --> 02:54:26.421
probably saw to the breeding of, and there was Weena dancing at my side.

02:54:27.461 --> 02:54:32.881
Then I tried to preserve myself from the horror that was coming upon me by regarding it as

02:54:32.881 --> 02:54:35.441
rigorous punishment of human selfishness.

02:54:36.181 --> 02:54:41.661
Man had been content to live in ease and delight upon the labors of his fellow man, and had

02:54:41.661 --> 02:54:47.141
taken necessity as his watchword and excuse, and in the fullness of time necessity had

02:54:47.141 --> 02:54:48.221
come home to him.

02:54:48.701 --> 02:54:54.661
I even tried a Carlisle-like scorn of this wretched aristocracy and decay, but this attitude

02:54:54.661 --> 02:54:55.921
of mine was impossible.

02:54:56.581 --> 02:55:01.601
However great their intellectual degradation, the Eloi had kept too much of the human form

02:55:01.601 --> 02:55:07.421
not to claim my sympathy, and to make me perforce a sharer in their degradation and their fear.

02:55:08.421 --> 02:55:12.601
I had at that time very vague ideas as to the course I should pursue.

02:55:13.241 --> 02:55:18.521
My first was to secure some safe place of refuge and to make myself such arms of metal

02:55:18.521 --> 02:55:20.361
or stone as I could contrive.

02:55:20.921 --> 02:55:22.601
That necessity was immediate.

02:55:23.221 --> 02:55:28.301
In the next place I hoped to procure some means of fire so that I should have the weapon

02:55:28.301 --> 02:55:33.341
of a torch at hand, for nothing I knew would be more efficient against these moorlocks.

02:55:34.081 --> 02:55:39.341
Then I wanted to arrange some contrivance to break open the doors of bronze under the

02:55:39.341 --> 02:55:40.101
white sphinx.

02:55:40.481 --> 02:55:42.501
I had in mind a battering ram.

02:55:42.961 --> 02:55:48.141
I had a persuasion that if I could enter those doors and carry a blaze of light before me,

02:55:48.341 --> 02:55:50.881
I should discover the time machine and escape.

02:55:51.321 --> 02:55:55.001
I could not imagine the moorlocks were strong enough to move it far away.

02:55:55.641 --> 02:55:58.761
Weena, I had resolved to bring with me to our time.

02:55:59.541 --> 02:56:04.441
And turning such schemes over in my mind, I pursued our way toward the building which

02:56:04.441 --> 02:56:06.461
my fancy had chosen as our dwelling.

02:56:27.980 --> 02:56:33.200
The Time Machine by H. G. Wells.

02:56:40.380 --> 02:56:46.500
I found the Palace of Green Porcelain, when we approached it about noon, deserted and

02:56:46.500 --> 02:56:47.520
falling into ruin.

02:56:48.420 --> 02:56:53.760
Only ragged vestiges of glass remained in its windows, and great sheets of the green

02:56:53.760 --> 02:56:56.920
facing had fallen away from the corroded metallic framework.

02:56:57.940 --> 02:57:04.340
It lay very high upon a turfy down, and looking northeastward before I entered it I was surprised

02:57:04.340 --> 02:57:09.900
to see a large estuary, or even creek, where I judged Wandsworth and Battersea must once

02:57:09.900 --> 02:57:10.560
have been.

02:57:11.180 --> 02:57:16.820
I thought then, though I never followed up on the thought, of what might have happened,

02:57:17.100 --> 02:57:20.280
or might be happening, to the living things in the sea.

02:57:22.220 --> 02:57:28.600
The material of the palace proved on examination to be indeed porcelain, and along the face

02:57:28.600 --> 02:57:31.680
of it I saw an inscription in some unknown character.

02:57:32.480 --> 02:57:39.220
I thought, rather foolishly, that Weena might help me to interpret this, but I only learned

02:57:39.220 --> 02:57:42.540
that the bare idea of writing had never entered her head.

02:57:43.000 --> 02:57:50.220
She always seemed to me, I fancy, more human than she was, perhaps because her affection

02:57:50.220 --> 02:57:51.240
was so human.

02:57:53.340 --> 02:57:59.460
Within the big valves of the door, which were open and broken, we found, instead of the

02:57:59.460 --> 02:58:03.440
customary hall, a long gallery lit by many side windows.

02:58:04.360 --> 02:58:07.120
At the first glance I was reminded of a museum.

02:58:08.500 --> 02:58:13.760
The tiled floor was thick with dust, and a remarkable array of miscellaneous objects

02:58:13.760 --> 02:58:15.820
was shrouded in the same gray covering.

02:58:15.820 --> 02:58:23.020
Then I perceived, standing strange and gaunt in the centre of the hall, what was clearly

02:58:23.020 --> 02:58:24.900
the lower part of a huge skeleton.

02:58:26.120 --> 02:58:31.060
I recognized by the oblique feet that it was some extinct creature after the fashion of

02:58:31.060 --> 02:58:31.920
the Megatherium.

02:58:32.940 --> 02:58:38.560
The skull and the upper bones lay beside it in the thick dust, and in one place where

02:58:38.560 --> 02:58:43.020
rainwater had dropped through a leak in the roof the thing itself had been worn away.

02:58:43.960 --> 02:58:48.520
Further in the gallery was the huge skeleton barrel of a brontosaurus.

02:58:49.660 --> 02:58:51.940
My museum hypothesis was confirmed.

02:58:53.120 --> 02:58:58.860
Going towards the side I found what appeared to be sloping shelves, and clearing away the

02:58:58.860 --> 02:59:03.320
thick dust I found the old familiar glass cases of our own time.

02:59:04.180 --> 02:59:08.560
But they must have been airtight to judge from the fair preservation of some of their

02:59:08.560 --> 02:59:09.060
contents.

02:59:10.960 --> 02:59:14.840
Clearly we stood among the ruins of some latter-day South Kensington.

02:59:16.320 --> 02:59:21.920
Here, apparently, was the paleontological section, and a very splendid array of fossils

02:59:21.920 --> 02:59:27.600
it must have been, though the inevitable process of decay that had been staved off for a time,

02:59:27.620 --> 02:59:33.100
and had, through the extinction of bacteria and fungi, lost ninety-nine hundredths of

02:59:33.100 --> 02:59:39.640
its force, was nevertheless, with extreme sureness, if with extreme slowness, at work

02:59:39.640 --> 02:59:41.100
again upon all its treasures.

02:59:42.260 --> 02:59:47.920
Here and there I found traces of the little people in the shape of rare fossils broken

02:59:47.920 --> 02:59:51.380
to pieces, or threaded in strings upon reeds.

02:59:52.160 --> 02:59:57.800
And the cases had in some instances been bodily removed—by the Morlocks, as I judged.

02:59:58.840 --> 03:00:00.420
The place was very silent.

03:00:01.040 --> 03:00:03.260
The thick dust deadened our footsteps.

03:00:04.700 --> 03:00:09.940
Weena, who had been rolling a sea urchin down the sloping glass of a case, presently came,

03:00:10.200 --> 03:00:15.020
as I stared about me, and very quietly took my hand and stood beside me.

03:00:16.180 --> 03:00:21.400
And at first I was so much surprised by this ancient monument of an intellectual age that

03:00:21.400 --> 03:00:23.840
I gave no thought to the possibilities it presented.

03:00:24.620 --> 03:00:29.220
Even my preoccupation about the time machine receded a little from my mind.

03:00:30.720 --> 03:00:35.560
To judge from the size of the place, this palace of green porcelain had a great deal

03:00:35.560 --> 03:00:40.460
more in it than a gallery of paleontology, possibly historical galleries.

03:00:41.020 --> 03:00:42.920
It might be even a library.

03:00:44.600 --> 03:00:50.660
To me, at least in my present circumstances, these would be vastly more interesting than

03:00:50.660 --> 03:00:53.400
this spectacle of old-time geology in decay.

03:00:55.000 --> 03:00:59.080
Exploring, I found another short gallery running transversely to the first.

03:00:59.980 --> 03:01:05.240
This appeared to be devoted to minerals, and the sight of a block of sulphur set my mind

03:01:05.240 --> 03:01:06.460
running on gunpowder.

03:01:07.020 --> 03:01:11.640
But I could find no saltpeter—indeed, no nitrates of any kind.

03:01:12.740 --> 03:01:15.600
Doubtless, they had Deliquest ages ago.

03:01:16.210 --> 03:01:19.800
Yet the sulphur hung in my mind and set up a train of thinking.

03:01:20.740 --> 03:01:26.060
As for the rest of the contents of that gallery, though on the whole they were the best preserved

03:01:26.060 --> 03:01:28.760
of all I saw, I had little interest.

03:01:29.600 --> 03:01:35.140
I am no specialist in mineralogy, and I went on down a very ruinous aisle running parallel

03:01:35.140 --> 03:01:36.600
to the first hall I had entered.

03:01:38.200 --> 03:01:43.640
Apparently this section had been devoted to natural history, but everything had long since

03:01:43.640 --> 03:01:44.860
passed out of recognition.

03:01:45.940 --> 03:01:51.760
A few shriveled and blackened vestiges of what had once been stuffed animals, desiccated

03:01:51.760 --> 03:01:58.060
mummies in jars that once held spirit, a brown dust of departed plants—that was all.

03:01:59.040 --> 03:02:04.200
I was sorry for that, because I should have been glad to trace the patent readjustments

03:02:04.200 --> 03:02:07.500
by which the conquest of animated nature had been attained.

03:02:08.600 --> 03:02:15.380
Then we came to a gallery of simply colossal proportions, but singularly ill-lit, the floor

03:02:15.380 --> 03:02:19.040
of it running downward at a slight angle from the end at which I entered.

03:02:20.320 --> 03:02:26.900
At intervals white globes hung from the ceiling, many of them cracked and smashed, which suggested

03:02:26.900 --> 03:02:29.420
that originally the place had been artificially lit.

03:02:30.480 --> 03:02:36.020
Here I was more in my element, for rising on either side of me were the huge bulks of

03:02:36.020 --> 03:02:42.560
big machines, all greatly corroded and many broken down, but some still fairly complete.

03:02:43.800 --> 03:02:49.280
You know I have a certain weakness for mechanism, and I was inclined to linger among these.

03:02:49.920 --> 03:02:54.720
The more so as for the most part they had the interest of puzzles, and I could make

03:02:54.720 --> 03:02:57.660
only the vaguest guesses at what they were for.

03:02:58.580 --> 03:03:04.180
I fancied that if I could solve their puzzles I could find myself in possession of powers

03:03:04.180 --> 03:03:06.160
that might be of use against the Morlocks.

03:03:07.980 --> 03:03:14.420
Suddenly Weena came very close to my side, so suddenly that she startled me. Had it not

03:03:14.420 --> 03:03:18.560
been for her I do not think I should have noticed that the floor of the gallery sloped

03:03:18.560 --> 03:03:26.300
at all. It may be, of course, that the floor did not slope, but that the museum was built

03:03:26.300 --> 03:03:27.540
into the side of a hill.

03:03:29.000 --> 03:03:35.340
The end I had come in at was quite above ground, and was lit by rare slit-like windows. As

03:03:35.340 --> 03:03:40.120
you went down the length the ground came up against these windows, until at last there

03:03:40.120 --> 03:03:45.720
was a pit-like the area of a London house before each, and only a narrow line of daylight

03:03:45.720 --> 03:03:46.320
at the top.

03:03:47.420 --> 03:03:53.200
I went slowly along, puzzling about the machines, and had been too intent upon them to notice

03:03:53.200 --> 03:03:58.780
the gradual diminution of light, until Weena's increasing apprehensions drew my attention.

03:03:59.880 --> 03:04:06.840
Then I saw that the gallery ran down at last into a thick darkness. I hesitated, and then,

03:04:07.040 --> 03:04:12.540
as I looked round me, I saw that the dust was less abundant, and its surface less even.

03:04:13.700 --> 03:04:19.780
Further away, towards the dimness, it appeared to be broken by a number of small narrow footprints.

03:04:20.640 --> 03:04:27.060
My sense of the immediate presence of the Morlocks revived at that. I felt that I was

03:04:27.060 --> 03:04:33.080
wasting my time in the academic examination of machinery. I called to mind that it was

03:04:33.080 --> 03:04:38.700
already far advanced in the afternoon, and that I still had no weapon, no refuge, and

03:04:38.700 --> 03:04:44.220
no means of making a fire. And then down in the remote blackness of the gallery I heard

03:04:44.220 --> 03:04:49.100
peculiar pattering, and the same odd noises I had heard down the well.

03:04:50.560 --> 03:04:57.000
I took Weena's hand. Then, struck with a sudden idea, I leapt her and turned to a machine

03:04:57.000 --> 03:05:03.620
from which projected a lever, not unlike those in the signal box. Clambering upon the stand

03:05:03.620 --> 03:05:10.500
and grasping this lever in my hands, I put all my weight upon it sideways. Suddenly Weena,

03:05:10.500 --> 03:05:13.640
deserted in the central aisle, began to whimper.

03:05:14.340 --> 03:05:19.200
I had judged the strength of the lever pretty correctly, for it snapped after a minute's

03:05:19.200 --> 03:05:24.480
strain, and I rejoined her with a mace in my hand, more than sufficient, I judged, for

03:05:24.480 --> 03:05:29.760
any Morlock skull I might encounter. And I longed very much to kill a Morlock or so,

03:05:30.340 --> 03:05:35.940
very inhuman, you may think, to want to go killing one's own descendants. But it was

03:05:35.940 --> 03:05:42.260
impossible, somehow, to feel any humanity in the things. Only my disinclination to leave

03:05:42.260 --> 03:05:47.380
Weena, and a persuasion that if I began to slake my thirst for murder my time machine

03:05:47.380 --> 03:05:52.360
might suffer, restrained me from going straight down the gallery and killing the brutes I

03:05:52.360 --> 03:05:52.700
heard.

03:05:54.380 --> 03:06:00.540
Well, mace in one hand and Weena in the other, I went out of that gallery and into another

03:06:00.540 --> 03:06:05.860
and still larger one, which at the first glance reminded me of a military chapel hung with

03:06:05.860 --> 03:06:12.360
tattered flags. The brown and charred rags that hung from the sides of it I presently

03:06:12.360 --> 03:06:18.720
recognized as the decaying vestiges of books. They had long since dropped to pieces, and

03:06:18.720 --> 03:06:24.440
every semblance of print had left them. But here and there were warped boards and cracked

03:06:24.440 --> 03:06:31.360
metallic clasps that told the tale well enough. Had I been a literary man I might, perhaps,

03:06:31.660 --> 03:06:38.380
have moralized upon the futility of all ambition. But as it was, the thing that struck me with

03:06:38.380 --> 03:06:43.440
keenest force was the enormous waste of labour to which this sombre wilderness of rotting

03:06:43.440 --> 03:06:49.620
paper testified. At the time I will confess that I thought chiefly of the philosophical

03:06:49.620 --> 03:06:53.880
transactions and my own seventeen papers upon physical optics.

03:06:56.960 --> 03:07:02.980
Then, going up a broad staircase, we came to what may once have been a gallery of technical

03:07:02.980 --> 03:07:10.000
chemistry, and here I had not a little hope of useful discoveries. Except at one end,

03:07:10.080 --> 03:07:15.500
where the roof had collapsed, this gallery was well preserved. I went eagerly to every

03:07:15.500 --> 03:07:22.220
unbroken case, and at last, in one of the really airtight cases, I found a box of matches.

03:07:23.140 --> 03:07:28.600
Very eagerly I tried them. They were perfectly good. They were not even damp.

03:07:29.480 --> 03:07:30.800
I turned to Weena.

03:07:31.740 --> 03:07:37.200
"'Dance!' I cried to her in her own tongue. For now I had a weapon indeed against the

03:07:37.200 --> 03:07:43.480
horrible creatures we feared. And so, in that derelict museum upon the thick, soft carpeting

03:07:43.480 --> 03:07:50.040
of dust, to Weena's huge delight, I solemnly performed a kind of composite dance, whistling

03:07:50.040 --> 03:07:57.200
the land of the leel, as cheerfully as I could. In part it was a modest can-can, in part a

03:07:57.200 --> 03:08:04.120
step-dance, in part a skirt-dance, so far as my tail-coat permitted, and in part original.

03:08:04.800 --> 03:08:09.000
For I am naturally inventive, as you know.'

03:08:09.860 --> 03:08:16.060
Now, I still think that for this box of matches to have escaped the wear of time for immemorial

03:08:16.060 --> 03:08:23.420
years was a most strange, as for me it was a most fortunate, thing. Yet, oddly enough,

03:08:23.760 --> 03:08:30.860
I found a far unlikelier substance, and that was camphor. I found it in a sealed jar that

03:08:30.860 --> 03:08:37.880
by chance, I suppose, had been really hermetically sealed. I fancied at first that it was paraffin

03:08:37.880 --> 03:08:43.900
wax, and smashed the glass accordingly. But the odour of the camphor was unmistakable.

03:08:44.640 --> 03:08:50.080
In the universal decay this volatile substance had chanced to survive, perhaps through many

03:08:50.080 --> 03:08:55.640
thousands of centuries. It reminded me of a sepia painting I had once seen done from

03:08:55.640 --> 03:09:00.820
the ink of a fossil belemite that must have perished and become fossilized millions of

03:09:00.820 --> 03:09:07.260
years ago. I was about to throw it away, but I remembered that it was inflammable, and burned

03:09:07.260 --> 03:09:13.520
with a good bright flame, was, in fact, an excellent candle, and I put it in my pocket.

03:09:14.700 --> 03:09:20.880
I found no explosives, however, nor any means of breaking down the bronze doors. As yet

03:09:20.880 --> 03:09:26.680
my iron crowbar was the most hopeful thing that I had chanced upon. Nevertheless, I left

03:09:26.680 --> 03:09:28.280
that gallery greatly elated.

03:09:29.980 --> 03:09:35.020
I cannot tell you all the story of that long afternoon. It would require a great effort

03:09:35.020 --> 03:09:41.140
of memory to recall my explorations in at all the proper order. I remember a long gallery

03:09:41.140 --> 03:09:47.180
of rusting stands of arms, and how I hesitated between my crowbar and a hatchet or a sword.

03:09:47.920 --> 03:09:53.360
I could not carry both, however, and my bar of iron promised best against the bronze gates.

03:09:54.580 --> 03:10:01.720
There were numbers of guns, pistols and rifles. The most were masses of rust, but many were

03:10:01.720 --> 03:10:08.420
of some new metal, and still fairly sound. But any cartridges or powder there may once

03:10:08.420 --> 03:10:14.640
have been had rotted into dust. One corner I saw was charred and shattered, perhaps,

03:10:14.640 --> 03:10:21.200
I thought, by an explosion among the specimens. In another place was a vast array of idols

03:10:21.200 --> 03:10:27.360
— Polynesian, Mexican, Grecian, Phoenician — every country on earth, I should think.

03:10:27.870 --> 03:10:34.120
And here, yielding to an irresistible impulse, I wrote my name upon the nose of a steatite

03:10:34.120 --> 03:10:38.060
monster from South America that particularly took my fancy.

03:10:39.740 --> 03:10:46.120
As the evening drew on, my interest waned. I went through gallery after gallery — dusty,

03:10:46.800 --> 03:10:53.600
silent, often ruinous, the exhibits sometimes mere heaps of rust and lignite, sometimes

03:10:53.600 --> 03:11:00.000
pressure. In one place I suddenly found myself near the model of a tin mine, and then, by

03:11:00.000 --> 03:11:07.780
the merest accident, I discovered in an air-tight case two dynamite cartridges. I shouted Eureka!

03:11:08.100 --> 03:11:17.200
and smashed the case with joy. Then came a doubt. I hesitated. Then, selecting a little

03:11:17.200 --> 03:11:23.940
side-gallery, I made my essay. I never felt such a disappointment as I did in waiting

03:11:23.940 --> 03:11:32.600
five, ten, fifteen minutes for an explosion that never came. Of course, the things were

03:11:32.600 --> 03:11:38.720
dummies, as I might have guessed from their presence. I really believe that had they not

03:11:38.720 --> 03:11:45.280
been so, I should have rushed off incontinently and blown sphinx, bronze doors, and, as it

03:11:45.280 --> 03:11:50.300
proved, my chances of finding the time machine all together into nonexistence.

03:11:51.680 --> 03:11:57.440
It was after that, I think, that we came to a little open court within the palace. It

03:11:57.440 --> 03:12:04.640
was turfed and had three fruit trees, so we rested and refreshed ourselves. Towards sunset

03:12:04.640 --> 03:12:10.560
I began to consider our position. Night was creeping upon us, and my inaccessible hiding

03:12:10.560 --> 03:12:16.760
place still had to be found. But that troubled me very little now. I had in my possession

03:12:16.760 --> 03:12:22.960
a thing that was, perhaps, the best of all defenses against the Morlocks. I had matches.

03:12:23.640 --> 03:12:29.540
I had the camphor in my pocket, too, if a blaze were needed. It seemed to me that the

03:12:29.540 --> 03:12:38.840
best thing we could do would be to pass the night in the open, protected by a fire. In

03:12:38.840 --> 03:12:46.000
that case, as yet, I had only my iron mace. But now, with my growing knowledge, I felt

03:12:46.000 --> 03:12:52.580
very differently towards those bronze doors. Up to this I had refrained from forcing them,

03:12:52.800 --> 03:12:57.520
largely because of the mystery on the other side. They had never impressed me as being

03:12:57.520 --> 03:13:03.460
very strong, and I hoped to find my bar of iron not altogether inadequate for the work.

03:13:38.718 --> 03:13:42.038
THE TIME MACHINE by H. G. Wells

03:13:47.718 --> 03:13:48.358
THE TIME MACHINE by H. G. Wells

03:13:48.358 --> 03:13:53.098
We emerged from the palace while the sun was still in part above the horizon.

03:13:54.358 --> 03:14:06.218
I was determined to reach the White Spinks early the next morning, and ear the dusk I purposed pushing through the woods that had stopped me on the previous journey.

03:14:07.018 --> 03:14:16.858
My plan was to go as far as possible that night, and then, building a fire, to sleep in the protection of its glare.

03:14:18.218 --> 03:14:27.738
Accordingly, as we went along, I gathered any sticks or dried grass I saw, and presently had my arms full of such litter.

03:14:28.518 --> 03:14:44.618
Thus loaded, our progress was slower than I had anticipated, and besides Weena was tired, and I began to suffer from sleepiness too, so that it was full night before we reached the wood.

03:14:45.738 --> 03:15:01.338
Upon the shrubby hill of its edge Weena would have stopped, fearing the darkness before us, but a singular sense of impending calamity, that should indeed have served me as a warning, drove me onward.

03:15:02.218 --> 03:15:14.618
I had been without sleep for a night and two days, and I was feverish and irritable. I felt sleep coming upon me, and the moorlocks with it.

03:15:15.598 --> 03:15:25.438
While we hesitated, among the black bushes behind us, and dim against their blackness, I saw three crouching figures.

03:15:26.578 --> 03:15:33.398
There was scrub and long grass all about us, and I did not feel safe from their insidious approach.

03:15:34.218 --> 03:15:48.818
The forest, I calculated, was rather less than a mile across. If we could get through it to the bare hillside, there, as it seemed to me, was an altogether safer resting place.

03:15:49.578 --> 03:15:57.598
I thought that, with my matches and my camphor, I could contrive to keep my path illuminated through the woods.

03:15:58.678 --> 03:16:07.038
Yet, it was evident that if I was to flourish matches with my hands, I should have to abandon my firewood.

03:16:08.318 --> 03:16:11.938
So, rather reluctantly, I put it down.

03:16:12.998 --> 03:16:18.178
And then it came into my head that I would amaze our friends behind by lighting it.

03:16:18.818 --> 03:16:28.678
I was to discover the atrocious folly of this proceeding, but it came to my mind as an ingenious move for covering our retreat.

03:16:29.858 --> 03:16:38.758
I don't know if you have ever thought what a rare thing flame must be in the absence of man and in a temperate climate.

03:16:39.758 --> 03:16:49.898
The sun's heat is rarely strong enough to burn, even when it is focused by dewdrops, as it sometimes decays in more tropical districts.

03:16:51.158 --> 03:16:55.998
Lightning may blast and blacken, but it rarely gives rise to widespread fire.

03:16:57.498 --> 03:17:05.798
Deaking vegetation may occasionally smolder with the heat of its fermentation, but this rarely results in flame.

03:17:06.598 --> 03:17:13.018
In this decadence, too, the art of fire-making had been forgotten on the earth.

03:17:13.978 --> 03:17:20.878
The red tongs that went licking up my heap of wood were an altogether new and strange thing to Weena.

03:17:22.678 --> 03:17:25.478
She wanted to run to it and play with it.

03:17:26.538 --> 03:17:31.418
I believe she would have cast herself into it had I not restrained her.

03:17:31.418 --> 03:17:38.038
But I caught her up, and in spite of her struggle, plunged boldly before me into the wood.

03:17:39.878 --> 03:17:43.038
For a little way the glare of my fire lit the path.

03:17:44.038 --> 03:17:58.018
Looking back presently, I could see through the crowded stems that from my heap of sticks the blaze had spread to some bushes adjacent, and a curved line of fire was creeping up the grass of the hill.

03:17:58.978 --> 03:18:03.738
I laughed at that and turned again to the dark trees before me.

03:18:04.618 --> 03:18:08.678
It was very black, and Weena clung to me convulsively.

03:18:09.638 --> 03:18:17.298
But there was still, as my eyes grew accustomed to the darkness, sufficient light for me to avoid the stems.

03:18:18.958 --> 03:18:29.078
Overhead it was simply black, except where a gap of remote, thin blue sky shone down upon us here and there.

03:18:30.478 --> 03:18:35.478
I struck none of my matches because I had no hand-free.

03:18:36.818 --> 03:18:40.238
Upon my left arm I carried my little one.

03:18:41.058 --> 03:18:44.278
In my right hand I had my iron bar.

03:18:45.718 --> 03:19:00.278
For some way I heard nothing but the crackling twigs under my feet, the faint rustle of the breeze above, and my own breathing, and the throb of the blood vessels in my ears.

03:19:01.918 --> 03:19:05.798
Then I seemed to know of a pattering about me.

03:19:06.598 --> 03:19:08.058
I pushed on grimly.

03:19:09.138 --> 03:19:11.658
The pattering grew more distinct.

03:19:11.658 --> 03:19:18.438
And then I caught the same queer sound and voices I had heard in the underworld.

03:19:19.798 --> 03:19:25.358
There were evidently several of the Morlocks, and they were closing in upon me.

03:19:26.678 --> 03:19:33.558
Indeed, in another minute I felt a tug at my coat, then something at my arm.

03:19:34.878 --> 03:19:38.478
And Weena shivered violently and became quite still.

03:19:39.478 --> 03:19:41.438
It was time for a match.

03:19:42.398 --> 03:19:45.378
But to get one I must put her down.

03:19:46.398 --> 03:19:59.498
I did so, and as I fumbled with my pocket a struggle began in the darkness about my knees, perfectly silent on her part and with the same peculiar cooing sounds from the Morlocks.

03:20:00.858 --> 03:20:06.898
Soft little hands, too, were creeping over my coat and back, touching even my neck.

03:20:07.598 --> 03:20:10.238
Then the match scratched and fizzed.

03:20:10.738 --> 03:20:15.818
I held it flaring, and saw the white backs of the Morlocks in flight amid the crease.

03:20:17.078 --> 03:20:24.158
I hastily took a lump of camphor from my pocket, and prepared to light it as soon as the match should wane.

03:20:25.338 --> 03:20:27.278
Then I looked at Weena.

03:20:28.178 --> 03:20:34.098
She was lying clutching my feet, and quite motionless, with her face to the ground.

03:20:35.758 --> 03:20:38.378
With a sudden fright I stooped to her.

03:20:39.318 --> 03:20:41.198
She seemed scarcely to breathe.

03:20:42.378 --> 03:20:53.478
I lit the block of camphor and flung it to the ground, and as it split and flared up and drove back the Morlocks and the shadows, I knelt down and lifted her.

03:20:53.478 --> 03:20:58.798
The wood behind seemed full of the stir and murmur of a great company.

03:21:00.438 --> 03:21:02.438
She seemed to have fainted.

03:21:03.178 --> 03:21:06.918
I put her carefully upon my shoulder and rose to push on.

03:21:08.058 --> 03:21:11.258
And then there came a horrible realization.

03:21:12.798 --> 03:21:18.738
In maneuvering with my matches and Weena, I had turned myself about several times,

03:21:18.738 --> 03:21:25.358
and now I had not the faintest idea in what direction lay my path.

03:21:26.298 --> 03:21:31.218
For all I knew, I might be facing back towards the palace of green porcelain.

03:21:32.258 --> 03:21:34.238
I found myself in a cold sweat.

03:21:35.158 --> 03:21:37.198
I had to think rapidly what to do.

03:21:38.438 --> 03:21:42.538
I determined to build a fire and encamp where we were.

03:21:42.538 --> 03:21:54.778
I put Weena, still motionless, down upon a turfy ball, and very hastily, as my first lump of camphor waned, I began collecting sticks and leaves.

03:21:56.118 --> 03:22:02.158
Here and there, out of the darkness round me, the Morlocks' eyes shone like carbuncles.

03:22:04.518 --> 03:22:06.658
The camphor flickered and went out.

03:22:07.498 --> 03:22:15.698
I let the match, and as I did so, two white forms that had been approaching Weena dashed hastily away.

03:22:16.978 --> 03:22:24.438
One was so blinded by the light that he came straight for me, and I felt his bones grind under the blow of my fist.

03:22:25.458 --> 03:22:30.758
He gave a whoop of dismay, staggered a little way, and fell down.

03:22:31.658 --> 03:22:36.578
I lit another piece of camphor, and went on gathering my bonfire.

03:22:37.858 --> 03:22:48.418
Presently, I noticed how dry was some of the foliage above me, for since my arrival on the time machine, a matter of a week, no rain had fallen.

03:22:49.658 --> 03:22:57.158
So instead of casting about among the trees for fallen twigs, I began leaping up and dragging down branches.

03:22:57.938 --> 03:23:06.218
Very soon, I had a choking smoky fire of green wood and dry sticks, and could economize my camphor.

03:23:07.498 --> 03:23:11.498
Then, I turned to where Weena lay beside my iron mace.

03:23:12.378 --> 03:23:17.258
I tried what I could to revive her, but she lay like one dead.

03:23:18.358 --> 03:23:22.798
I could not even satisfy myself whether or not she breathed.

03:23:24.578 --> 03:23:31.918
Now, the smoke of the fire beat over towards me, and it must have made me heavy of a sudden.

03:23:33.678 --> 03:23:38.598
Moreover, the vapor of camphor was in the air.

03:23:39.978 --> 03:23:43.658
My fire would not need replenishing for an hour or so.

03:23:44.358 --> 03:23:49.218
I felt very weary after my exertion, and sat down.

03:23:49.218 --> 03:23:55.618
The wood, too, was full of a slumberous murmur that I did not understand.

03:23:56.958 --> 03:24:05.518
I seemed just to nod and open my eyes, but all was dark, and the moorlocks had their hands upon me.

03:24:06.358 --> 03:24:14.798
Flinging off their clinging fingers, I hastily felt in my pocket for the matchbox, and it had gone.

03:24:15.618 --> 03:24:18.278
Then they gripped and closed with me again.

03:24:18.798 --> 03:24:21.278
In a moment, I knew what had happened.

03:24:22.038 --> 03:24:28.198
I had slept, and my fire had gone out, and the bitterness of death came over my soul.

03:24:29.558 --> 03:24:33.558
The forest seemed full of the smell of burning wood.

03:24:34.758 --> 03:24:39.738
I was caught by the neck, by the hair, by the arms, and poured down.

03:24:39.738 --> 03:24:47.278
It was indescribably horrible in the darkness to feel all these soft creatures heaped upon me.

03:24:48.058 --> 03:24:51.738
I felt as if I was in a monstrous spider's web.

03:24:52.658 --> 03:24:55.318
I was overpowered and went down.

03:24:56.878 --> 03:24:59.638
I felt little teeth nipping at my neck.

03:25:00.478 --> 03:25:04.958
I rolled over, and as I did so, my hand came against my iron liver.

03:25:05.838 --> 03:25:06.998
It gave me strength.

03:25:06.998 --> 03:25:17.058
I struggled up, shaking the human rats from me, and, holding the barge short, I thrust where I judged their faces might be.

03:25:17.998 --> 03:25:26.458
I could feel this succulent giving of flesh and bone under my blows, and for a moment I was free.

03:25:27.958 --> 03:25:33.898
The strange exultation that so often seems to accompany hard fighting came upon me.

03:25:33.898 --> 03:25:41.018
I knew that both I and Weena were lost, but I determined to make the Morlocks pay for their meat.

03:25:42.338 --> 03:25:47.318
I stood with my back to a tree, swinging the iron bar before me.

03:25:48.138 --> 03:25:51.838
The whole wood was full of the stir and cries of them.

03:25:53.158 --> 03:25:54.258
A minute passed.

03:25:55.498 --> 03:26:02.078
Their voices seemed to rise to a higher pitch of excitement, and their movements grew faster.

03:26:03.078 --> 03:26:06.558
Yet none came within reach.

03:26:07.898 --> 03:26:10.878
I stood glaring at the blackness.

03:26:12.238 --> 03:26:14.038
Then suddenly came hope.

03:26:15.258 --> 03:26:17.038
What if the Morlocks were afraid?

03:26:18.618 --> 03:26:22.358
Enclosed on the heels of that came a strange thing.

03:26:23.918 --> 03:26:27.018
The darkness seemed to grow luminous.

03:26:28.018 --> 03:26:32.238
Very dimly I began to see the Morlocks about me.

03:26:33.118 --> 03:26:35.638
Three battered at my feet.

03:26:36.718 --> 03:26:50.138
And then I recognized with incredulous surprise that the others were running in an incessant stream, as it seemed, from behind me and away through the wood in front.

03:26:51.338 --> 03:26:56.398
And their backs seemed no longer white, but reddish.

03:26:57.878 --> 03:27:08.238
As I stood agape, I saw a little red spark go drifting across a gap of starlight between the branches, and vanish.

03:27:10.018 --> 03:27:21.238
And at that I understood the smell of burning wood, the slumbrous murmur that was growing now into a gusty roar, the red glow, and the Morlocks' flight.

03:27:22.578 --> 03:27:32.538
Stepping out from behind my tree and looking back, I saw, through the black pillars of the nearer trees, the flames of the burning forest.

03:27:33.638 --> 03:27:36.898
It was my first fire coming after me.

03:27:37.838 --> 03:27:42.438
With that I looked for Weena, but she was gone.

03:27:43.678 --> 03:27:50.598
The hissing and crackling behind me, the explosive thud as each fresh tree burst into flame.

03:27:51.238 --> 03:27:53.318
Left little time for reflection.

03:27:54.758 --> 03:27:58.658
My iron bar still gripped. I followed in the Morlocks' path.

03:27:59.618 --> 03:28:00.958
It was a close race.

03:28:01.778 --> 03:28:11.478
Once, the flames gripped forward so swiftly on my right, as I ran, that I was outflanked and had to strike off to the left.

03:28:12.318 --> 03:28:24.518
But at last, I emerged into a small open space, and as I did so, a Morlock came blundering towards me, and passed me, and went on straight into the fire.

03:28:26.138 --> 03:28:34.518
And now, I was to see the most weird and horrible thing, I think, of all that I beheld in that future age.

03:28:35.418 --> 03:28:40.118
This whole space was as bright as day with the reflection of the fire.

03:28:41.478 --> 03:28:47.458
In the center was a hillock, or tumulus, surmounted by a scorched hearth-thorn.

03:28:47.898 --> 03:28:58.638
Behind this was another arm of the burning forest, with yellow tongues already writhing from it, completely encircling the space with a fence of fire.

03:28:59.798 --> 03:29:11.678
Upon the hillside were some thirty or forty Morlocks, dazzled by the light and heat, and blundering hither and thither against each other in their bewilderment.

03:29:12.758 --> 03:29:24.818
At first, I did not realize their blindness, and struck furiously at them with my bar, in a frenzy of fear, as they approached me, killing one and crippling several more.

03:29:25.498 --> 03:29:40.758
But when I had watched the gestures of one of them groping under the haltern against the red sky, and heard their moans, I was assured of their absolute helplessness and misery in the glare, and I struck no more of them.

03:29:41.978 --> 03:29:50.338
Yet, every now and then, one would come straight towards me, setting loose a quivering horror that made me quick to elude him.

03:29:50.338 --> 03:29:58.958
At one time, the flames died down somewhat, and I feared the foul creatures would presently be able to see me.

03:29:59.518 --> 03:30:04.958
I was thinking of beginning the fight by killing some of them before this should happen.

03:30:05.978 --> 03:30:10.578
But the fire burst out again, brightly, and I stayed my hand.

03:30:11.558 --> 03:30:17.098
I walked about the hill among them, and avoided them, looking for some trace of Weiner.

03:30:18.158 --> 03:30:19.518
But Weiner was gone.

03:30:20.338 --> 03:30:36.298
At last, I sat down on the summit of the hillock, and watched this strange, incredible company of blind things groping to and fro, and making uncanny noises to each other, as the glare of the fire beat on them.

03:30:36.298 --> 03:30:50.958
The coiling a brush of smoke streamed across the sky, and through the rare tatters of that red canopy, remote as though they belonged to another universe, shone the little stars.

03:30:52.658 --> 03:31:00.878
Two or three moorlocks came blundering into me, and I drove them off with blows of my fists, trembling as I did so.

03:31:01.778 --> 03:31:06.438
For the most part of that night, I was persuaded it was a nightmare.

03:31:07.478 --> 03:31:10.958
I bit myself and screamed in a passionate desire to awake.

03:31:11.818 --> 03:31:19.298
I beat the ground with my hands, and got up and sat down again, and wandered here and there, and again sat down.

03:31:20.498 --> 03:31:26.218
Then, I would fall to rubbing my eyes, and calling upon God to let me awake.

03:31:27.258 --> 03:31:33.698
Thrice, I saw moorlocks put their heads down in a kind of agony, and rush into the flames.

03:31:34.878 --> 03:31:53.458
But, at last, above the subsiding red of the fire, above the stringing masses of black smoke, and the whitening and lockening tree stumps, and the diminishing numbers of these dim creatures, came the white light of day.

03:31:54.578 --> 03:31:59.498
I searched again for traces of Weena, but there were none.

03:32:00.618 --> 03:32:05.038
It was plain that they had left her poor little body in the forest.

03:32:06.618 --> 03:32:14.298
I cannot describe how it relieved me to think that it had escaped the awful fate to which it seemed destined.

03:32:15.298 --> 03:32:23.118
As I thought of that, I was almost moved to begin a massacre of the helpless abominations about me.

03:32:23.898 --> 03:32:25.438
But I contained myself.

03:32:26.418 --> 03:32:31.678
The Haluk, as I have said, was a kind of island in the forest.

03:32:32.398 --> 03:32:38.918
From its summit, I could now make out, through a haze of smoke, the palace of green porcelain.

03:32:39.318 --> 03:32:43.028
And from that, I could get my bearings for the white sphinx.

03:32:43.998 --> 03:32:52.498
And so, leaving the remnant of these damned souls still going hither and thither, and moaning, as the day grew clearer,

03:32:53.348 --> 03:33:01.718
I tied some grass about my feet, and limped on, across smoking ashes, and among black stems,

03:33:02.658 --> 03:33:08.278
that still pulsated internally with spire, towards the hiding place of the time machine.

03:33:09.718 --> 03:33:15.558
I walked slowly, for I was almost exhausted, as well as lame,

03:33:16.318 --> 03:33:21.378
and I felt the intensest wretchedness for the horrible death of little Weena.

03:33:22.498 --> 03:33:25.878
It seemed an overwhelming calamity.

03:33:26.998 --> 03:33:34.498
Now, in this old familiar room, it is more like the sorrows of a dream than an actual loss.

03:33:35.878 --> 03:33:42.758
But that morning, it left me absolutely lonely again, terribly alone.

03:33:44.198 --> 03:33:50.798
I began to think of this house of mine, of this fireside, of some of you,

03:33:50.798 --> 03:33:55.358
and with such thoughts came a longing that was pain.

03:33:56.918 --> 03:34:04.878
But, as I walked over the smoking ashes under the bright morning sky, I made a discovery.

03:34:05.858 --> 03:34:09.738
In my trouser pocket were still some loose matches.

03:34:11.978 --> 03:34:15.678
The box must have leaked before it was lost.

03:34:50.302 --> 03:34:54.682
The Time Machine by H.G. Wells

03:34:57.242 --> 03:35:04.942
About eight or nine in the morning, I came to the same seat of yellow metal from which I had viewed the world upon the evening of my arrival.

03:35:06.262 --> 03:35:11.902
I thought of my hasty conclusions upon that evening and could not refrain from laughing bitterly at my confidence.

03:35:12.822 --> 03:35:22.822
Here was the same beautiful scene, the same abundant foliage, the same splendid palaces and magnificent ruins, the same silver river running between its fertile banks.

03:35:24.202 --> 03:35:28.842
The gay robes of the beautiful people moved hither and thither among the trees.

03:35:29.822 --> 03:35:36.242
Some were bathing in exactly the place where I had saved Weena, and that suddenly gave me a keen stab of pain.

03:35:37.642 --> 03:35:46.622
And like blots upon the landscape, rosa cupulas above the waves to the underworld, I understood now what all the beauty of the overworld people covered.

03:35:47.682 --> 03:35:52.922
A very pleasant was their day, as pleasant as the day of the cattle in the field.

03:35:53.882 --> 03:36:00.122
Like the cattle, they knew of no enemies and provided against no needs, and their end was the same.

03:36:02.642 --> 03:36:06.482
I grieved to think how brief the dream of the human intellect had been.

03:36:06.962 --> 03:36:12.222
It had committed suicide. It had set itself steadfastly towards comfort and ease.

03:36:12.802 --> 03:36:16.702
A balanced society with security and permanency is its watchword.

03:36:17.982 --> 03:36:21.242
It had attained its hopes to come to this at last.

03:36:22.482 --> 03:36:26.462
Once, life and property must have reached almost absolute safety.

03:36:28.082 --> 03:36:32.962
The rich had been assured of his wealth and comfort, the toilers assured of his life and work.

03:36:32.962 --> 03:36:42.422
No doubt in that perfect world there had been no unemployed problem, no social question left unsolved, and a great quiet had followed.

03:36:44.262 --> 03:36:52.702
It is a law of nature we overlook, that intellectual versatility is a compensation for change, danger, and trouble.

03:36:54.282 --> 03:36:59.142
An animal, perfectly in harmony with its environment, is a perfect mechanism.

03:36:59.922 --> 03:37:04.862
Nature never appeals to intelligence until habit and instinct are useless.

03:37:06.662 --> 03:37:10.822
There is no intelligence, or there is no change, and no need of change.

03:37:11.462 --> 03:37:16.822
Only those animals partake of intelligence that have to meet a huge variety of needs and dangers.

03:37:18.702 --> 03:37:27.522
So, as I see it, the upper world man had drifted towards his feeble prettiness, and the underworld to mere mechanical industry.

03:37:28.582 --> 03:37:34.882
But that perfect state had lacked one thing, even for mechanical perfection, absolute permanency.

03:37:36.202 --> 03:37:42.902
Apparently, as time went on, the feeding of the underworld, however it was affected, had become disjointed.

03:37:43.862 --> 03:37:50.302
Mother Necessity, who had been staved off for a few thousand years, came back again, and she began below.

03:37:51.122 --> 03:37:58.862
The underworld being in contact with machinery, which, however perfect, still needs some little thought outside habit,

03:37:59.582 --> 03:38:06.262
had probably retained, perforce, rather more initiative, if less of every other human character, than the upper.

03:38:07.702 --> 03:38:12.022
And when other meat failed them, they turned to what old habit had hitherto forbidden.

03:38:13.122 --> 03:38:20.842
So I say I saw it in my last view of the world, of 800 and 2,701.

03:38:22.402 --> 03:38:25.522
It may be as wrong an explanation as mortal wit could invent.

03:38:26.422 --> 03:38:30.422
It is how the thing shaped itself to me, and as that I give it to you.

03:38:32.702 --> 03:38:39.002
After the fatigues, excitements, and terrors of the past days, and in spite of my grief,

03:38:39.002 --> 03:38:43.902
the seat, and the tranquil view, and the warm sunlight were very pleasant.

03:38:45.342 --> 03:38:49.462
I was very tired and sleepy, and soon my theorizing passed into dozing.

03:38:50.162 --> 03:38:57.802
Catching myself at that, I took my own hint, and spreading myself out upon the turf, out a long and refreshing sleep.

03:39:00.002 --> 03:39:02.162
I awoke a little before sunsetting.

03:39:02.902 --> 03:39:08.062
I now felt safe against being caught napping by the moorlocks, and stretching myself.

03:39:08.062 --> 03:39:11.242
I came on down the hill towards the white sphinx.

03:39:11.702 --> 03:39:16.522
I had my crowbar in one hand, and the other hand played with the matches in my pocket.

03:39:17.562 --> 03:39:20.082
And now came an almost unexpected thing.

03:39:20.762 --> 03:39:25.542
As I approached the pedestal of the sphinx, I found the bronze valves were open.

03:39:25.862 --> 03:39:27.522
They had slid down into grooves.

03:39:28.682 --> 03:39:31.862
At that I stopped short before them, hesitating to enter.

03:39:32.682 --> 03:39:37.842
Within was a small apartment, and on a raised place in the corner of this was a time machine.

03:39:38.942 --> 03:39:47.622
I had the small levers in my pocket, so, here, after all my elaborate preparations for the siege of the white sphinx, was a meek surrender.

03:39:49.002 --> 03:39:52.842
I threw my iron bar away, almost sorry not to use it.

03:39:54.302 --> 03:39:57.642
A sudden thought came into my head as I stooped towards the portal.

03:39:57.642 --> 03:40:02.742
For once, at least, I grasped the mental operations of the moorlocks.

03:40:03.682 --> 03:40:09.222
Suppressing a strong inclination to laugh, I stepped through the bronze frame and up to the time machine.

03:40:10.062 --> 03:40:12.702
I was surprised to find it had been carefully oiled and cleaned.

03:40:13.622 --> 03:40:20.742
I've suspected since that the moorlocks had even partially taken it to pieces, while trying in their dim way to grasp its purpose.

03:40:22.502 --> 03:40:29.542
Now, as I stood and examined it, finding a pleasure in the mere touch of the contrivance, the thing I had expected happened.

03:40:30.202 --> 03:40:34.102
The bronze panel suddenly slid up and struck the frame with a clang.

03:40:34.602 --> 03:40:40.082
I was in the dark, trapped. So the moorlocks thought. At that I chuckled gleefully.

03:40:41.262 --> 03:40:44.602
I could already hear their murmuring laughter as they came towards me.

03:40:44.822 --> 03:40:47.242
Very calmly, I tried to strike the match.

03:40:47.242 --> 03:40:50.762
I had only to fix on the levers and depart them like a ghost.

03:40:51.682 --> 03:40:54.042
But I had overlooked one little thing.

03:40:54.522 --> 03:40:59.062
The matches were of that abominable kind, the light only on the box.

03:41:00.702 --> 03:41:02.962
You may imagine how all my calm vanished.

03:41:03.602 --> 03:41:05.422
The little brutes were close upon me.

03:41:06.282 --> 03:41:07.382
One touched me.

03:41:08.022 --> 03:41:14.202
I made a sweeping blow in the dark at them with the levers, and began to scramble into the saddle of the machine.

03:41:15.342 --> 03:41:18.182
Then came one hand upon me, and then another.

03:41:18.922 --> 03:41:26.622
Then I had simply to fight against the persistent fingers from my levers, and at the same time feel for the studs over which these fitted.

03:41:28.502 --> 03:41:31.402
One, indeed, they almost got away from me.

03:41:31.922 --> 03:41:35.522
As it slipped from my hand, I had to butt in the dark with my head.

03:41:36.202 --> 03:41:39.402
I could hear the moorlock's skull ring, to recover it.

03:41:40.062 --> 03:41:44.362
It was a nearer thing than the fight in the forest, I think, this last scramble.

03:41:46.222 --> 03:41:48.942
But at last the lever was fitted and pulled over.

03:41:49.462 --> 03:41:51.122
The clinging hands slipped from me.

03:41:51.402 --> 03:41:53.502
The darkness presently fell from my eyes.

03:41:54.102 --> 03:41:59.162
I found myself in the same gray light and tumult I've already described.

03:42:30.209 --> 03:42:35.029
I have already told you of the sickness and confusion that comes with time traveling.

03:42:35.029 --> 03:42:41.969
And this time I was not seated properly in the saddle, but sideways and in an unstable fashion.

03:42:42.709 --> 03:42:49.469
For an indefinite time I clung to the machine as it swayed and vibrated, quite unheating how I went.

03:42:49.969 --> 03:42:54.809
And when I brought myself to look at the dials again I was amazed to find where I had arrived.

03:42:55.749 --> 03:43:03.949
One dial records days, and another thousands of days, another millions of days, and another thousands of millions.

03:43:05.549 --> 03:43:11.709
Now, instead of reversing the levers, I had pulled them over so as to go forward with them.

03:43:12.369 --> 03:43:21.829
And when I came to look at these indicators I found that the thousands hand was sweeping round as fast as the seconds hand of a watch, into futurity.

03:43:23.029 --> 03:43:26.829
As I drove on a peculiar change crept over the appearance of things.

03:43:27.609 --> 03:43:30.109
The palpitating grayness grew darker.

03:43:30.389 --> 03:43:36.149
Then, though I was still traveling with prodigious velocity, the blinking succession of day and night,

03:43:36.489 --> 03:43:43.029
which was usually indicative of a slower pace, returned and grew more and more marked.

03:43:43.529 --> 03:43:45.629
This puzzled me very much at first.

03:43:46.189 --> 03:43:49.289
The alternations of night and day grew slower and slower.

03:43:49.509 --> 03:43:55.449
And so did the passage of the sun across the sky, until they seemed to stretch through centuries.

03:43:56.709 --> 03:44:05.029
At last the steady twilight brooded over the earth, a twilight only broken now and then when a comet glared across the darkling sky.

03:44:06.169 --> 03:44:12.249
The band of light that had indicated the sun had long since disappeared, for the sun had ceased to set.

03:44:13.309 --> 03:44:17.829
It simply rose and fell in the west, and grew ever broader and more red.

03:44:18.909 --> 03:44:20.809
All trace of the moon had vanished.

03:44:21.529 --> 03:44:28.009
The circling of the stars, growing slower and slower, had given place to creeping points of light.

03:44:29.209 --> 03:44:36.209
At last, some time before I stopped, the sun, red and very large, halted motionless upon the horizon,

03:44:36.689 --> 03:44:42.569
a vast dome glowing with a dull heat, and now and then suffering a momentary extinction.

03:44:44.049 --> 03:44:48.069
At one time it had for a little while glowed more brilliantly again,

03:44:48.069 --> 03:44:51.549
but it speedily reverted to its sullen red heat.

03:44:53.809 --> 03:44:59.409
I perceived by this slowing down of its rising and setting that the work of the tidal drag was done.

03:44:59.749 --> 03:45:06.749
The earth had come to rest with one face to the sun, even as in our own time the moon faces the earth.

03:45:08.249 --> 03:45:14.549
Very cautiously, for I remembered my former headlong fall, I began to reverse my motion.

03:45:14.549 --> 03:45:20.449
Slower and slower went the circling hands, until the thousands one seemed motionless,

03:45:20.709 --> 03:45:24.249
and the daily one was no longer a mere mist upon its scale.

03:45:24.829 --> 03:45:29.609
Still slower, until the dim outlines of a desolate beach grew visible.

03:45:32.009 --> 03:45:35.709
I stopped very gently and sat upon the time machine, looking round.

03:45:36.349 --> 03:45:40.269
The sky was no longer blue, northeastward it was inky black,

03:45:40.269 --> 03:45:44.949
and out of the blackness shone brightly and steadily the pale white stars.

03:45:45.829 --> 03:45:49.169
Overhead it was a deep Indian red and starless,

03:45:49.469 --> 03:45:52.949
and southeastward it grew brighter to a glowing scarlet,

03:45:53.389 --> 03:45:59.029
where, cut by the horizon, lay the huge hull of the sun, red and motionless.

03:46:01.009 --> 03:46:03.889
The rocks about me were of a harsh reddish color,

03:46:04.189 --> 03:46:09.389
and all the trace of life that I could see at first was the intensely green vegetation

03:46:09.389 --> 03:46:13.469
that covered every projecting point on their southeastern face.

03:46:14.169 --> 03:46:19.369
It was the same rich green that one sees on forest moss or on the lichen in caves,

03:46:19.789 --> 03:46:23.409
plants which, like these, grow in a perpetual twilight.

03:46:23.809 --> 03:46:26.029
The machine was standing on a sloping beach.

03:46:26.309 --> 03:46:32.679
The sea stretched away to the southwest to rise into a bright horizon against the wan sky.

03:46:33.449 --> 03:46:37.849
There were no breakers and no waves, for not a breath of wind was stirring.

03:46:37.849 --> 03:46:42.569
Only a slight oily swell rose and fell like a gentle breathing

03:46:42.569 --> 03:46:46.409
and showed that the eternal sea was still moving and living.

03:46:47.169 --> 03:46:50.289
And along the margin, where the water sometimes broke,

03:46:50.669 --> 03:46:55.809
was a thick incrustation of salt, pink under the lurid sky.

03:46:57.109 --> 03:47:02.289
There was a sense of oppression in my head, and I noticed that I was breathing very fast.

03:47:02.769 --> 03:47:07.189
The sensation reminded me of my only experience of mountaineering,

03:47:07.189 --> 03:47:12.389
and from that, I judged the air to be more rarified than it is now.

03:47:13.089 --> 03:47:17.209
Far away up the desolate slope, I heard a harsh scream and saw a thing

03:47:17.209 --> 03:47:21.849
like a huge white butterfly go slanting and fluttering up into the sky

03:47:21.849 --> 03:47:25.789
and circling, disappear over some low hillocks beyond.

03:47:26.769 --> 03:47:32.989
The sound of its voice was so dismal that I shivered and seated myself more firmly upon the machine.

03:47:33.709 --> 03:47:36.769
Looking round me again, I saw that, quite near,

03:47:37.169 --> 03:47:42.149
what I had taken to be a reddish mass of rock was moving slowly towards me.

03:47:42.769 --> 03:47:46.289
Then I saw the thing was really a monstrous crab-like creature.

03:47:47.049 --> 03:47:50.069
Can you imagine a crab as large as yonder table,

03:47:50.329 --> 03:47:55.189
with its many legs moving slowly and uncertainly, its big claws swaying,

03:47:55.369 --> 03:47:59.449
its long antennae like Carter's whips, waving and feeling,

03:47:59.449 --> 03:48:04.349
and its stocked eyes gleaming at you on either side of its metallic front.

03:48:05.129 --> 03:48:08.789
Its back was corrugated and ornamented with ungainly bosses,

03:48:09.169 --> 03:48:12.469
and a greenish incrustation blotched it here and there.

03:48:13.489 --> 03:48:18.669
I could see the many palps of its complicated mouth flickering and feeling as it moved.

03:48:19.469 --> 03:48:23.289
As I stared at this sinister apparition crawling towards me,

03:48:23.469 --> 03:48:27.049
I felt a tickling on my cheek as though a fly had lighted there.

03:48:27.049 --> 03:48:31.169
I tried to brush it away, but in a moment it returned,

03:48:31.249 --> 03:48:33.629
and almost immediately came another by my ear.

03:48:33.729 --> 03:48:36.389
I struck at this and caught something thread-like.

03:48:36.869 --> 03:48:39.209
It was drawn swiftly out of my hand.

03:48:39.649 --> 03:48:44.149
With a frightful qualm, I turned and saw that I had grasped the antenna

03:48:44.149 --> 03:48:47.829
of another monster crab that stood just behind me.

03:48:48.149 --> 03:48:51.229
Its evil eyes were wriggling on their stalks,

03:48:51.229 --> 03:48:53.449
and its mouth was all alive with appetite,

03:48:53.449 --> 03:48:59.489
and its vast ungainly claws smeared with an algal slime were descending upon me.

03:48:59.889 --> 03:49:02.129
In a moment, my hand was on the lever,

03:49:02.289 --> 03:49:05.589
and I had placed a month between myself and these monsters.

03:49:06.409 --> 03:49:11.589
But I was still on the same beach, and I saw them distinctly now as soon as I stopped.

03:49:12.829 --> 03:49:16.829
Dozens of them seemed to be crawling here and there in the somber light

03:49:16.829 --> 03:49:19.569
among the foliated sheets of intense green.

03:49:20.449 --> 03:49:25.609
I cannot convey the sense of abominable desolation that hung over the world.

03:49:26.089 --> 03:49:30.929
The red eastern sky, the northward blackness, the salt-dead sea,

03:49:31.349 --> 03:49:35.549
the stony beach crawling with these foul, slow-stirring monsters,

03:49:35.969 --> 03:49:39.629
the uniform poisonous-looking green of the lichenous plants,

03:49:40.049 --> 03:49:45.009
the thin air that hurts one's lungs, all contributed to an appalling effect.

03:49:45.009 --> 03:49:49.529
I moved on a hundred years, and there was the same red sun,

03:49:49.929 --> 03:49:54.149
a little larger, a little duller, the same dying sea,

03:49:54.349 --> 03:49:59.009
the same chill air, and the same crowd of earthy crustacea

03:49:59.009 --> 03:50:02.749
creeping in and out among the green weed and the red rocks.

03:50:03.189 --> 03:50:08.729
And in the westward sky I saw a curved pale line like a vast new moon.

03:50:10.569 --> 03:50:16.349
So I travelled, stopping ever and again in great strides of a thousand years or more,

03:50:16.429 --> 03:50:19.109
drawn on by the mystery of the earth's fate,

03:50:19.549 --> 03:50:25.009
watching with a strange fascination the sun grow larger and duller in the westward sky

03:50:25.249 --> 03:50:27.929
and the life of the old earth ebb away.

03:50:29.049 --> 03:50:31.869
At last, more than thirty million years hence,

03:50:32.309 --> 03:50:38.349
the huge red-hot dome of the sun had come to obscure nearly a tenth part of the darkling heavens,

03:50:39.009 --> 03:50:44.109
then I stopped once more, for the crawling multitude of crabs had disappeared

03:50:44.109 --> 03:50:49.509
and the red beach, save for its livid green liverworts and lichens, seemed lifeless.

03:50:50.749 --> 03:50:55.689
And now it was flecked with white. A bitter cold assailed me.

03:50:55.909 --> 03:50:59.309
Rare white flakes ever and again came eddying down.

03:50:59.689 --> 03:51:04.989
To the northeastward the glare of the snow lay under the starlight of the sable sky,

03:51:04.989 --> 03:51:09.109
and I could see an undulating crest of hillocks pinkish-white.

03:51:10.809 --> 03:51:15.469
There were fringes of ice along the sea margin, with drifting masses further out,

03:51:15.729 --> 03:51:21.969
but the main expanse of that salt ocean all bloody under the eternal sunset was still unfrozen.

03:51:23.489 --> 03:51:27.429
I looked about me to see if any traces of animal life remained.

03:51:28.369 --> 03:51:32.529
A certain indefinable apprehension still kept me in the saddle of the machine.

03:51:32.529 --> 03:51:37.329
But I saw nothing moving in earth or sky or sea.

03:51:37.849 --> 03:51:42.569
The green slime on the rocks alone testified that life was not extinct.

03:51:43.309 --> 03:51:48.049
A shallow sand bank had appeared in the sea and the water had receded from the beach.

03:51:49.429 --> 03:51:54.349
I fancied I saw some black object flopping about upon this bank,

03:51:54.809 --> 03:52:00.609
but it became motionless as I looked at it, and I judged that my eye had been deceived

03:52:00.609 --> 03:52:03.529
and that the black object was merely a rock.

03:52:04.069 --> 03:52:10.149
The stars in the sky were intensely bright and seemed to me to twinkle very little.

03:52:13.269 --> 03:52:17.889
Suddenly I noticed that the circular westward outline of the sun had changed,

03:52:18.269 --> 03:52:21.729
that a concavity, a bay, had appeared in the curve.

03:52:22.089 --> 03:52:23.649
I saw this grow larger.

03:52:24.249 --> 03:52:29.029
For a minute perhaps I stared aghast at this blackness that was creeping over the day,

03:52:29.029 --> 03:52:32.489
and then I realized that an eclipse was beginning.

03:52:32.949 --> 03:52:37.149
Either the moon or the planet Mercury was passing across the sun's disk.

03:52:37.829 --> 03:52:40.029
Naturally at first I took it to be the moon,

03:52:40.329 --> 03:52:43.649
but there is much to incline me to believe that what I really saw

03:52:43.649 --> 03:52:48.169
was the transit of an inner planet passing very near to the earth.

03:52:50.569 --> 03:52:55.809
The darkness grew apace, a cold wind began to blow and freshening gusts from the east,

03:52:55.809 --> 03:52:58.949
and the showering white flakes in the air increased in number.

03:52:59.489 --> 03:53:01.889
From the edge of the sea came a ripple and whisper.

03:53:02.969 --> 03:53:06.009
Beyond these lifeless sounds the world was silent.

03:53:08.029 --> 03:53:11.949
Silent? It would be hard to convey the stillness of it.

03:53:12.629 --> 03:53:17.549
All the sounds of man, the bleeding of sheep, the cries of birds, the hum of insects,

03:53:18.029 --> 03:53:22.689
the stir that makes the background of our lives, all that was over.

03:53:24.249 --> 03:53:28.229
As the darkness thickened the eddying flakes grew more abundant,

03:53:28.349 --> 03:53:32.009
dancing before my eyes and the cold of the air more intense.

03:53:32.749 --> 03:53:37.209
At last, one by one, swiftly, one after the other,

03:53:37.449 --> 03:53:40.989
the white peaks of the distant hills vanished into blackness.

03:53:41.809 --> 03:53:44.009
The breeze rose to a moaning wind.

03:53:44.409 --> 03:53:48.289
I saw the black central shadow of the eclipse sweeping towards me.

03:53:48.609 --> 03:53:51.429
In another moment the pale stars alone were visible.

03:53:52.029 --> 03:53:54.429
All else was rayless obscurity.

03:53:54.769 --> 03:53:57.409
The sky was absolutely black.

03:53:59.329 --> 03:54:02.049
A horror of this great darkness came upon me.

03:54:02.269 --> 03:54:07.569
The cold that smote to my marrow and the pain I felt in breathing overcame me.

03:54:07.869 --> 03:54:10.929
I shivered and a deadly nausea seized me.

03:54:11.229 --> 03:54:15.629
Then, like a red-hot bow in the sky, appeared the edge of the sun.

03:54:16.409 --> 03:54:18.749
I got off the machine to recover myself.

03:54:18.749 --> 03:54:22.409
I felt giddy and incapable of facing the return journey.

03:54:23.029 --> 03:54:29.029
As I stood sick and confused I saw again the moving thing upon the shoal.

03:54:29.109 --> 03:54:34.689
There was no mistake now that it was a moving thing against the red water of the sea.

03:54:35.069 --> 03:54:38.569
It was a round thing, the size of a football perhaps.

03:54:39.149 --> 03:54:43.449
Or it may be bigger, and tentacles trailed down from it,

03:54:43.549 --> 03:54:47.069
and it seemed black against the weltering blood-red water,

03:54:47.069 --> 03:54:49.389
and it was hopping fitfully about.

03:54:50.189 --> 03:54:51.929
Then I felt I was fainting,

03:54:52.369 --> 03:54:57.989
but a terrible dread of lying helpless in that remote and awful twilight sustained me

03:54:57.989 --> 03:54:59.949
while I clambered upon the saddle.

03:55:22.169 --> 03:55:23.569
Thank you.

03:55:50.344 --> 03:55:51.204
So I came back.

03:55:51.204 --> 03:55:55.024
For a long time I must have been insensible upon the machine.

03:55:55.644 --> 03:55:59.084
The blinking secession of the days and nights was resumed.

03:55:59.564 --> 03:56:01.044
The sun got golden again.

03:56:01.344 --> 03:56:02.304
The sky blue.

03:56:03.364 --> 03:56:05.624
I breathed with greater freedom.

03:56:06.224 --> 03:56:09.644
The fluctuating contours of the land ebbed and flowed.

03:56:09.984 --> 03:56:12.504
The hands spun backward upon the dials.

03:56:13.464 --> 03:56:16.604
At last I saw, again, the dim shadows of houses,

03:56:17.124 --> 03:56:19.584
the evidences of decadent humanity.

03:56:20.724 --> 03:56:24.504
These, too, changed and passed, and others came.

03:56:25.044 --> 03:56:29.064
Presently, when the million dial was at zero, I slackened speed.

03:56:30.004 --> 03:56:33.604
I began to recognize our petty and familiar architecture.

03:56:34.144 --> 03:56:37.244
The thousands hand ran back to the starting point.

03:56:37.564 --> 03:56:40.224
The night and day flapped slower and slower.

03:56:41.324 --> 03:56:44.624
Then the old walls of the laboratory came round me.

03:56:44.904 --> 03:56:47.604
Very gently now I slowed the mechanism down.

03:56:48.504 --> 03:56:51.044
I saw one little thing that seemed odd to me.

03:56:51.324 --> 03:56:56.044
I think I have told you that when I set out, before my velocity came very high,

03:56:56.504 --> 03:57:01.184
Mrs. Watchett had walked across the room traveling as it seemed to me like a rocket.

03:57:01.704 --> 03:57:06.864
As I returned, I passed again, across that minute when she traversed the laboratory,

03:57:07.304 --> 03:57:12.644
but now her every motion appeared to be the exact inversion of her previous ones.

03:57:13.404 --> 03:57:18.744
The door at the lower end opened and she glided quietly up the laboratory back foremost

03:57:18.744 --> 03:57:23.164
and disappeared behind the door by which she had previously entered.

03:57:24.304 --> 03:57:28.784
Just before that, I seemed to see Hillier for a moment, but he passed like a flash.

03:57:30.144 --> 03:57:35.824
Then I stopped the machine and saw about me again the old familiar laboratory,

03:57:36.224 --> 03:57:39.544
my tools, my appliances, just as I had left them.

03:57:40.104 --> 03:57:43.684
I got off the thing very shakily and sat down upon my bench.

03:57:44.544 --> 03:57:47.164
For several minutes, I trembled violently.

03:57:48.684 --> 03:57:50.104
Then I became calmer.

03:57:50.744 --> 03:57:54.604
Around me was my old workshop again, exactly as it had been.

03:57:55.084 --> 03:57:58.224
I might have slept there and the whole thing had been a dream.

03:57:58.924 --> 03:58:00.364
And yet, not exactly.

03:58:00.684 --> 03:58:04.404
The thing had started from the southeast corner of the laboratory.

03:58:04.824 --> 03:58:09.524
It had come to rest again in the northwest against the wall where you saw it.

03:58:09.544 --> 03:58:13.024
That gives you the exact distance from my little lawn

03:58:13.024 --> 03:58:18.504
to the pedestal of the white sphinx into which the moorlocks had carried my machine.

03:58:19.784 --> 03:58:22.024
For a time, my brain went stagnant.

03:58:23.164 --> 03:58:25.684
Presently, I got up and came through the passage here,

03:58:25.944 --> 03:58:30.224
limping because my heel was still painful and feeling sorely begrind.

03:58:31.224 --> 03:58:35.244
I saw the Paul Moll Gazette on the table by the door.

03:58:36.264 --> 03:58:43.184
I found the date was indeed today, and looking at the timepiece, saw the hour was almost 8 o'clock.

03:58:44.064 --> 03:58:46.964
I heard your voices and the clatter of plates.

03:58:48.284 --> 03:58:51.084
I hesitated. I felt so sick and weak.

03:58:51.564 --> 03:58:54.844
Then I sniffed good wholesome meat and opened the door on you.

03:58:55.224 --> 03:58:56.004
You know the rest.

03:58:56.484 --> 03:58:59.364
I washed and dined, and now I am telling you the story.

03:59:00.344 --> 03:59:05.164
I know, he said after a pause, that all this will be absolutely incredible to you,

03:59:05.164 --> 03:59:10.144
to me the one incredible thing is that I am here tonight in this old familiar room

03:59:10.144 --> 03:59:14.244
looking into your friendly faces and telling you these strange adventures.

03:59:15.084 --> 03:59:16.604
He looked at the medical man.

03:59:17.044 --> 03:59:19.604
No, I cannot expect you to believe it.

03:59:20.824 --> 03:59:22.884
Take it as a lie or a prophecy.

03:59:23.344 --> 03:59:25.284
Say I dreamed it in the workshop.

03:59:25.784 --> 03:59:31.384
Consider I have been speculating upon the destinies of our race until I have hatched this fiction.

03:59:31.384 --> 03:59:37.364
Treat my assertion of its truth as a mere stroke of art to enhance its interest,

03:59:37.744 --> 03:59:40.384
and taking it as a story, what do you think of it?

03:59:41.404 --> 03:59:45.504
He took up his pipe and began in his old accustomed manner to tap

03:59:45.504 --> 03:59:47.904
with it nervously upon the bars of the grate.

03:59:48.364 --> 03:59:50.344
There was a momentary stillness.

03:59:51.584 --> 03:59:56.104
Then chairs began to creak and shoes to scrape upon the carpet.

03:59:56.844 --> 04:00:01.804
I took my eyes off the time traveler's face and looked round at his audience.

04:00:03.144 --> 04:00:08.384
They were in the dark, and little spots of color swarmed before them.

04:00:08.884 --> 04:00:12.804
The medical man seemed absorbed in the contemplation of our host.

04:00:14.104 --> 04:00:18.264
The editor was looking hard at the end of his cigar, the sixth.

04:00:19.084 --> 04:00:21.064
The journalist fumbled for his watch.

04:00:21.524 --> 04:00:24.284
The others, as far as I remember, were motionless.

04:00:25.504 --> 04:00:27.484
The editor stood up with a sigh.

04:00:27.984 --> 04:00:30.884
What a pity it is you're not a writer of stories, he said,

04:00:31.224 --> 04:00:33.304
putting his hand on the time traveler's shoulder.

04:00:33.944 --> 04:00:35.104
You don't believe it?

04:00:35.644 --> 04:00:37.384
Well, I thought not.

04:00:38.024 --> 04:00:39.544
The time traveler turned to us.

04:00:39.864 --> 04:00:41.224
Where are the matches, he said.

04:00:41.664 --> 04:00:44.804
He lit one and spoke over his pipe, puffing.

04:00:45.344 --> 04:00:48.304
To tell you the truth, I hardly believe it myself, and yet

04:00:48.844 --> 04:00:54.264
his eye fell with a mute inquiry upon the withered white flowers upon the little table.

04:00:54.284 --> 04:00:57.324
Then he turned over, the hand holding his pipe,

04:00:57.704 --> 04:01:01.664
and I saw he was looking at some half-healed scars on his knuckles.

04:01:02.564 --> 04:01:05.724
The medical man rose, came to the lamp, and examined the flowers.

04:01:07.504 --> 04:01:09.324
The gynesium's odd, he said.

04:01:09.684 --> 04:01:14.564
The psychologist leaned forward to see, holding out his hand for a specimen.

04:01:15.364 --> 04:01:18.244
I'm hanged if it isn't a quarter to one, said the journalist.

04:01:18.704 --> 04:01:19.764
How shall we get home?

04:01:20.604 --> 04:01:23.004
Plenty of cabs at the station, said the psychologist.

04:01:23.004 --> 04:01:25.104
It's a curious thing, said the medical man.

04:01:25.144 --> 04:01:27.704
But I certainly don't know the natural order of these flowers.

04:01:28.104 --> 04:01:28.944
May I have them?

04:01:29.804 --> 04:01:31.244
The time traveler hesitated.

04:01:33.464 --> 04:01:35.244
Then suddenly, certainly not.

04:01:36.184 --> 04:01:38.244
Where did you really get them, said the medical man.

04:01:38.584 --> 04:01:40.924
The time traveler put his hand to his head.

04:01:41.504 --> 04:01:45.124
He spoke like one who was trying to keep hold of an idea that eluded him.

04:01:46.164 --> 04:01:49.764
They were put into my pocket by Weena when I traveled into time.

04:01:50.184 --> 04:01:51.344
He stared round the room.

04:01:51.344 --> 04:01:53.104
I'm damned if it isn't all going.

04:01:53.984 --> 04:01:57.444
This room and you and the atmosphere of every day is too much for my memory.

04:01:58.184 --> 04:02:00.984
Did I ever make a time machine or a model of a time machine?

04:02:01.444 --> 04:02:02.824
Or is it all only a dream?

04:02:03.744 --> 04:02:06.504
They say life is a dream, a precious poor dream at times,

04:02:06.724 --> 04:02:08.824
but I can't stand another that won't fit.

04:02:09.184 --> 04:02:09.824
It's madness.

04:02:10.344 --> 04:02:11.924
And where did the dream come from?

04:02:12.324 --> 04:02:14.264
I must look at that machine if there is one.

04:02:15.164 --> 04:02:17.444
He caught up the lamp swiftly and carried it,

04:02:17.484 --> 04:02:19.564
flaring red, through the door into the corridor.

04:02:20.204 --> 04:02:21.144
We followed him.

04:02:21.924 --> 04:02:24.884
There in the flickering light of the lamp was the machine,

04:02:25.104 --> 04:02:28.284
sure enough, squat, ugly, and askew,

04:02:28.704 --> 04:02:34.684
a thing of brass, ebony, ivory, and translucent, glimmering quartz.

04:02:36.384 --> 04:02:39.784
Solid to the touch, for I put up my hand and felt the rail of it,

04:02:40.024 --> 04:02:42.564
and with brown spots and smears upon the ivory,

04:02:42.764 --> 04:02:45.004
and bits of grass and moss upon the lower parts,

04:02:45.424 --> 04:02:47.284
and one rail bent awry.

04:02:48.024 --> 04:02:51.384
The time traveler put the lamp down on the bench

04:02:51.384 --> 04:02:53.904
and ran his hand along the damaged rail.

04:02:54.964 --> 04:02:56.504
It's all right now, he said.

04:02:56.624 --> 04:02:58.564
The story I told you was true.

04:02:59.544 --> 04:03:01.884
I'm sorry to have brought you out here in the cold.

04:03:02.444 --> 04:03:05.544
He took up the lamp, and in an absolute silence,

04:03:05.804 --> 04:03:08.244
we returned to the smoking room.

04:03:09.504 --> 04:03:13.264
He came into the hall with us and helped the editor on with his coat.

04:03:14.084 --> 04:03:15.784
The medical man looked into his face,

04:03:15.784 --> 04:03:19.844
and with a certain hesitation, told him he was suffering from overwork,

04:03:20.164 --> 04:03:21.604
at which he laughed hugely.

04:03:22.904 --> 04:03:26.504
I remember him standing in the open doorway bawling good night.

04:03:27.924 --> 04:03:29.564
I shared a cab with the editor.

04:03:29.904 --> 04:03:31.944
He thought the tale a gaudy lie.

04:03:32.724 --> 04:03:36.724
For my own part, I was unable to come up with a conclusion.

04:03:37.564 --> 04:03:39.884
The story was so fantastic and incredible,

04:03:40.344 --> 04:03:42.904
the telling so credible and sober.

04:03:43.464 --> 04:03:45.764
I lay awake most of the night thinking about it.

04:03:46.344 --> 04:03:50.584
I determined to go, next day, and see the time traveler again.

04:03:51.124 --> 04:03:52.924
I was told he was in the laboratory,

04:03:53.384 --> 04:03:56.604
and being on easy terms in the house, I went up to see him.

04:03:57.544 --> 04:03:59.644
The laboratory, however, was empty.

04:04:00.384 --> 04:04:04.444
I stared for a minute at the time machine and put out my hand and touched the lever.

04:04:05.524 --> 04:04:09.864
At that, the squat's substantial looking mass swayed like a bow shaken by the wind.

04:04:10.604 --> 04:04:12.544
Its instability startled me extremely,

04:04:12.884 --> 04:04:15.504
and I had a queer reminiscence of the childish days

04:04:15.504 --> 04:04:17.784
when I used to be forbidden to meddle.

04:04:18.064 --> 04:04:19.704
I came back through the corridor.

04:04:21.044 --> 04:04:23.784
The time traveler met me in the smoking room.

04:04:24.164 --> 04:04:25.484
He was coming from the house.

04:04:25.884 --> 04:04:29.764
He had a small camera under one arm and a knapsack under the other.

04:04:30.224 --> 04:04:33.004
He laughed when he saw me and gave me an elbow to shake.

04:04:33.784 --> 04:04:36.964
I'm frightfully busy, he said, with that thing in there.

04:04:38.104 --> 04:04:39.864
But is it not some hoax?

04:04:40.004 --> 04:04:42.584
I said, do you really travel through time?

04:04:43.524 --> 04:04:45.604
Really and truly, I do.

04:04:46.144 --> 04:04:48.164
And he looked frankly into my eyes.

04:04:48.504 --> 04:04:49.364
He hesitated.

04:04:49.844 --> 04:04:51.424
His eye wandered about the room.

04:04:52.104 --> 04:04:53.704
I only want half an hour, he said.

04:04:53.944 --> 04:04:56.104
I know why you came, and it's awfully good of you.

04:04:56.584 --> 04:04:57.804
There's some magazines here.

04:04:58.064 --> 04:05:01.784
If you'll stop to lunch, I'll approve you this time traveling up to the hilt,

04:05:02.144 --> 04:05:03.324
specimen and all.

04:05:03.704 --> 04:05:06.264
If you'll forgive my leaving you now.

04:05:07.244 --> 04:05:09.544
I consented, hardly comprehending,

04:05:09.544 --> 04:05:13.884
then the full import of his words, and he nodded and went on down the corridor.

04:05:14.384 --> 04:05:16.624
I heard the door of the laboratory slam,

04:05:17.044 --> 04:05:20.304
seated myself in a chair, and took up a daily paper.

04:05:21.304 --> 04:05:23.344
What was he going to do before lunchtime?

04:05:23.644 --> 04:05:26.264
Then suddenly I was reminded by an advertisement

04:05:26.264 --> 04:05:29.504
that I had promised to meet Richardson, the publisher, at two.

04:05:29.784 --> 04:05:33.204
I looked at my watch and saw that I could barely save the engagement.

04:05:33.744 --> 04:05:36.624
I got up and went down the passage to tell the time traveler.

04:05:37.244 --> 04:05:41.464
As I took hold of the handle of the door, I heard an exclamation,

04:05:41.764 --> 04:05:44.664
oddly truncated at the end, and a click and a thud.

04:05:45.204 --> 04:05:48.084
A gust of air whirled round me as I opened the door,

04:05:48.204 --> 04:05:51.804
and from within came the sound of broken glass falling on the door.

04:05:52.804 --> 04:05:54.484
The time traveler was not there.

04:05:54.984 --> 04:05:58.844
I seemed to see a ghostly, indistinct figure sitting in a whirling mass

04:05:58.844 --> 04:06:04.164
of black and brass for a moment, a figure so transparent that the bench behind,

04:06:04.164 --> 04:06:07.264
with its sheets of drawings, was absolutely distinct,

04:06:07.644 --> 04:06:10.564
but this phantasm vanished as I rubbed my eyes.

04:06:11.544 --> 04:06:13.024
The time machine had gone.

04:06:13.424 --> 04:06:17.884
Save for a subsiding stir of dust, the further end of the laboratory was empty.

04:06:18.504 --> 04:06:21.944
A pane of the skylight had apparently just been blown in.

04:06:22.784 --> 04:06:24.744
I felt an unreasonable amazement.

04:06:24.824 --> 04:06:26.744
I knew that something strange had happened,

04:06:26.924 --> 04:06:30.524
and for the moment could not distinguish what the strange thing might be.

04:06:30.524 --> 04:06:36.364
As I stood staring, the door into the garden opened, and the manservant appeared.

04:06:37.084 --> 04:06:38.564
We looked at each other.

04:06:39.324 --> 04:06:40.744
The ideas began to come.

04:06:41.264 --> 04:06:43.944
Has Mr.—gone out that way?

04:06:44.464 --> 04:06:45.064
said I.

04:06:45.804 --> 04:06:47.244
No, sir, no one has come out this way.

04:06:47.244 --> 04:06:48.924
I was expecting to find him here.

04:06:49.684 --> 04:06:51.184
At that, I understood.

04:06:51.504 --> 04:06:53.244
At the risk of disappointing Richardson,

04:06:53.784 --> 04:06:55.724
I stayed on, waiting for the time traveler,

04:06:56.164 --> 04:06:59.264
waiting for the second, perhaps still stranger story,

04:06:59.264 --> 04:07:02.804
and the specimens and photographs he would bring with him.

04:07:03.404 --> 04:07:06.584
But I am beginning now to fear that I must wait a lifetime.

04:07:07.024 --> 04:07:09.424
The time traveler vanished three years ago.

04:07:10.124 --> 04:07:14.204
And, as everybody knows now, he has never returned.

04:07:16.724 --> 04:07:17.324
Epilogue

04:07:18.364 --> 04:07:20.924
One cannot choose, but wonder.

04:07:21.964 --> 04:07:23.144
Will he ever return?

04:07:24.224 --> 04:07:26.584
It may be that he swept back into the past,

04:07:26.584 --> 04:07:32.324
and fell among the blood-drinking hairy savages of the Age of Unpolished Stone,

04:07:32.804 --> 04:07:36.184
into the abysses of the Cretaceous Sea,

04:07:36.504 --> 04:07:41.844
or among the grotesque Sarians, the huge reptilian brutes of the Jurassic times.

04:07:45.344 --> 04:07:48.004
He may even now, if I may use the phrase,

04:07:48.184 --> 04:07:52.904
be wandering on some Plesiosaurus-haunted Ullitic coral reef,

04:07:52.904 --> 04:07:56.864
or beside the lonely saline lakes of the Triassic Age.

04:07:57.284 --> 04:08:00.564
Or did he go forward, into one of the nearer ages,

04:08:00.624 --> 04:08:02.224
in which men are still men,

04:08:02.604 --> 04:08:05.284
but with the riddles of our own time answered,

04:08:05.344 --> 04:08:07.244
and its wearisome problems solved?

04:08:08.244 --> 04:08:11.884
Into the manhood of the race, for I, for my own part,

04:08:12.004 --> 04:08:15.004
cannot think that these latter days of weak experiment,

04:08:15.704 --> 04:08:17.824
fragmentary theory, and mutual discord,

04:08:18.004 --> 04:08:20.504
are indeed man's culminating time.

04:08:20.824 --> 04:08:22.404
I say for my own part.

04:08:22.904 --> 04:08:27.164
He I know, for the question had been discussed among us

04:08:27.164 --> 04:08:29.544
long before the time machine was made,

04:08:30.024 --> 04:08:32.764
thought but cheerlessly of the advancement of mankind,

04:08:33.164 --> 04:08:37.664
and saw in the growing pile of civilization only a foolish heap,

04:08:38.044 --> 04:08:43.144
that must inevitably fall back upon and destroy its makers in the end.

04:08:44.164 --> 04:08:49.064
If that is so, it remains for us to live as though it were not so,

04:08:49.304 --> 04:08:52.124
but to me the future is still black and blank.

04:08:52.584 --> 04:08:57.644
Is a vast ignorance lit at a few casual places by the memory of his story.

04:08:58.464 --> 04:09:01.264
And I have, by me, for my comfort,

04:09:01.844 --> 04:09:05.964
two strange white flowers, shriveled now and browned,

04:09:05.984 --> 04:09:10.964
and flat and brittle, to witness that even when mind and strength had gone,

04:09:11.404 --> 04:09:17.204
gratitude and a mutual tenderness still lived on in the heart of man.

04:09:26.324 --> 04:09:30.484
End of The Time Machine by H. G. Wells
